<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 00:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, June 9, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
N.M. Park Superintendent To Retire
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- Roy Weaver, the park superintendent who approved a
prescribed burn that blew out of control and rolled through Los Alamos last
month, said Friday he will retire in July. Weaver, superintendent of Bandelier
National Monument for nearly 10 years, said he believed conditions had been just
right for the park's annual regimen of burning brush May 4 to stave off a
potentially disastrous fire. But after the burn was started, it became the
largest wildfire in state history, destroying more than 200 homes in Los Alamos
and forcing 25,000 people to evacuate.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Protesters Damage Cars in Lebanon
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KFAR KILA, Lebanon (AP) -- U.N. efforts to lay down borders between Lebanon
and Israel hit bumpy terrain Friday, with protesters stoning U.N. inspection
teams, officials raising objections and villagers threatening to evict
peacekeepers. Also Friday, Palestinians threw stones at Israeli troops on the
border. Several protesters cut the fence and walked through, drawing warning
shots from Israeli guards. The day's troubles highlighted the continuing
turbulence along the border, where there has been no real authority since last
month's Israeli troop withdrawal from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S., North Korea Reach Agreement
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- U.S. and North Korean officials reached an
agreement Friday to immediately resume the search for more than 8,000 U.S.
soldiers missing in action from the Korean War. The first search mission is
scheduled for June 25, the 50th anniversary of the outbreak of the Korean War.
The agreement to conduct five joint operations between June and November was
reached after three days of talks between the U.S. Defense Department and the
North Korean People's Liberation Army. As a result of previous negotiations,
U.S. teams have conducted 12 recovery operations inside North Korea since 1996
and found 42 sets of remains.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pop Artist George Segal Dies At 75
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- George Segal, an American pop art icon of the '60s
known for his life-size plaster sculptures, died Friday of cancer at age 75.
Segal began his career as a painter but later turned to sculpture. He received a
National Medal of the Arts from President Clinton in 1999. Segal's
three-dimensional sculpture scenes include ''Cezanne's Still Life,'' a breakfast
table with ripe fruit, tea pot and milk pitcher modeled after the famous
painting, and ''Woman on Orange Bed,'' a nude woman lounging on a rumpled,
sun-streaked bed.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Review: Race A Key In Capital Cases
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- At least nine men were sent to death row in Texas after a
psychologist recommended the death penalty partly because of the defendant's
race, a review has found. The death sentence that prompted the review was thrown
out Monday by the U.S. Supreme Court. Psychologist Walter Quijano had testified
that Argentine laborer Victor Hugo Saldano, a convicted murderer, was a future
danger to society because of his Hispanic heritage. Texas Attorney General John
Cornyn began investigating in April after his office found problems with the
Saldano case. Of the eight other cases, only six may result in further legal
action.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Court Reverses Makah Whaling Ruling
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A federal appeals court Friday overturned a ruling that
had allowed Washington state's Makah Indians to resume whaling for the first
time in more than 70 years. A panel of the 9th U.S. Circuit of Appeals ruled 2-1
that the environmental impact had not been adequately considered. The case now
goes back to federal court in Tacoma, Wash., for additional proceedings.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Arab-Americans Angry Over Policy
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Arab-Americans booed and shouted at Undersecretary of
State Thomas Pickering on Friday as he tried to give a luncheon speech in
support of continued sanctions against Iraq. ''Shame, shame on you,'' an
unidentified man shouted at Pickering, the State Department's third highest
official. Several dozen people walked out in protest. Pickering said sanctions
are needed because Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein has not complied with U.N.
resolutions passed after his 1990 invasion of Kuwait. The sanctions have been
blamed by critics for increasing suffering in Iraq -- rising poverty, illness
and death rates.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Drops 55; Nasdaq Gains 49
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in a quiet session Friday. The Dow Jones
industrial average fell 54.66 to close at 10,614.06. On the NYSE, gainers led
losers 1,667-1,188. The Nasdaq composite index rose 49.28 to close at 3,874.84.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mets Pound Yankees 12-2
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mike Piazza hit a grand slam as the New York Mets bombarded
Roger Clemens for nine runs -- matching the most he's ever allowed in a game --
in routing the New York Yankees 12-2 Friday in the opener of this year's Subway
Series. Slumping Derek Bell homered and drove in five runs and Edgardo Alfonzo
also connected for the Mets.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
</SUBHEAD>
