<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rice Steps Up For Lakers  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN NADEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Lakers' third option suddenly
became No. 2, and not by choice.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Rice, much maligned throughout the playoffs for his
inconsistent play on offense, was up to the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   And so were Ron Harper, Derek Fisher and Robert Horry, who also
moved up in the pecking order.
</P>
<P>
   An 11-year veteran known as one of the NBA's top outside
shooters but often a disappointment this season, Rice came through
after Kobe Bryant sprained his ankle in the first quarter, scoring
21 points as the Lakers beat Indiana 111-104 Friday night to take a
2-0 lead in the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, who made 1-of-8 shots and scored three points in the
Lakers' 104-87 victory in Game 1, bounced back with a 7-of-15
performance, including 5-of-6 from 3-point range. His point total
equaled his high in this year's playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Rice's biggest shot was a 3-pointer from the top of the key with
a little less than five minutes left, ending a 6-0 Indiana run and
giving the Lakers an 89-84 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers weren't closer than three points after that.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers took the lead for good on a foul shot by Shaquille
O'Neal with 2:53 left in the third quarter, and Rice followed with
his fourth 3-pointer in as many tries at that stage to give the
Lakers a 71-67 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Harper, forced to play more minutes than usual and become more
of a scorer as well because of Bryant's injury, also scored 21
points including four free throws in the final 32.5 seconds to
clinch the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Harper's running bank shot with a little more than eight minutes
left made it 82-78, and Fisher followed with a 3-pointer to give
the Lakers the game's biggest lead at that stage.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, a second-team All-NBA selection as well as first-team
all-defense pick, was injured while making his only shot of the
game, a 17-foot jumper with 3:26 left in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, who sprained his right foot in Game 5 of the Western
Conference finals against Portland but didn't miss any playing
time, landed on Jalen Rose' foot after releasing the shot, and went
down.
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious immediately that the injury was significant, as
he arose hobbling, and shortly thereafter, he left the court for
good.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's status for Game 3 at Conseco Fieldhouse on Sunday night
is unclear. The Lakers said Bryant, who scored 14 points in Game 1,
is day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, O'Neal set a playoff record by attempting 39 free
throws, making 18. He was fouled intentionally several times in the
late going, and made 5-of-10 in those situations.
</P>
<P>
   With the Lakers leading 99-96, the ball went into O'Neal, but he
dropped it to Horry before the Pacers could foul him, and Horry's
three-point play gave Los Angeles a six-point lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-10-00 0021 </TRAILER>
