<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diamondbacks 4, Angels 1  </HEADLINE>
By BOB BAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Randy Johnson allowed three hits in six innings
to become the National League's first 10-game winner Friday night
as the Arizona Diamondbacks snapped a five-game losing streak by
beating the Anaheim Angels 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson (10-1) struck out eight to tie fellow left-hander Mickey
Lolich for 13th on the career strikeout list with 2,832. Steve
Carlton is the only lefty to strike out more. Johnson walked one
and hit a batter.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who had missed his last start after receiving a
cortisone injection to relieve soreness in his left shoulder, left
the game after throwing 101 pitches. The six-inning stint was his
shortest outing of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is 7-0 with a 0.98 ERA at home this season.
</P>
<P>
   Vincente Padilla, Dan Plesac and Byung-Hyun Kim blanked the
Angels over the last three innings. Kim got his seventh save in
nine chances.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's only run came on a 457-foot homer by Troy Glaus in the
third inning. The blast, which landed in the dining area outside
Friday's Front Row restaurant far beyond the left-field wall, tied
Ron Gant for the third-longest in Bank One Ballpark. It was Glaus'
18th home run of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Gonzalez hit his fourth home run in five games, a two-run
shot off Brian Cooper (2-2) in the Diamondbacks' four-run fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Angels' first baseman Mo Vaughn committed two errors, one of
them costing a run.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, in his fourth start since being recalled from Triple-A
Edmonton, allowed three earned runs and six hits in five innings.
He struck out one, walked three and hit a batter.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Womack tripled into the right-field corner with one out in
the fourth, then scored on Jay Bell's single. Gonzalez followed
with his 15th homer, on Cooper's first pitch, to make it 3-1. Steve
Finley broke out of 1-for-11 slump with a two-out double. Turner
Ward followed with a one-bouncer to first, but Vaughn threw wildly
past the bag as Cooper tried to cover, allowing Finley to score.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks, back for a brief three-game home stand after a
1-5 trip, loaded the bases with one out in the fourth but failed to
score when Kelly Stinnett hit into a double play.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The Diamondbacks traded utility man Andy Fox to Florida for
outfielder Danny Bautista, who is to be in uniform for Saturday's
Arizona-Anaheim game. ... The Diamondbacks activated Travis Lee
from the DL (groin pull), and he started at first base. ...The only
home runs hit farther at Bank One Ballpark than Glaus' were by
Scott Rolen and Matt Williams. ... Anaheim's Darin Erstad was
0-for-3 to end his eight-game hitting streak. ... Johnson struck
out the side on 12 pitches in the first inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
