<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., North Korea Reach Agreement  </HEADLINE>
By RANJAN ROY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- On June 25 -- the 50th anniversary of the start
of the Korean War -- a U.S. military team will resume searching for
remains of U.S. servicemen at the scene of a stunning Chinese
onslaught that killed hundreds of American and South Korean troops.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement for the search at the Chongchon River area in
North Korea is part of a deal struck Friday by U.S. and North
Korean negotiators for a series of five joint excavations this year
-- for which the U.S. government agreed to pay North Korea a total
of $2 million -- that could yield the largest number of remains
since joint recovery missions began in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Remains searches were halted last fall in a dispute over North
Korea's demand for new humanitarian aid.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Liotta, the lead U.S. negotiator at this week's talks in
Malaysia, said in a telephone interview Friday that the United
States would pay about $400,000 for each of five excavation
operations.
</P>
<P>
   That is twice the $200,000 paid per mission in 1999. Liotta said
the price went up because the search and recovery teams will be
larger this year.
</P>
<P>
   The searches initially will be in Unsan and Kujang counties,
near the Chongchon River north of Pyongyang, the North Korean
capital. It was in this region that elements of the 8th U.S. Army
Cavalry Regiment encountered a surprise attack by hundreds of
thousands of Chinese troops who had slipped across the border
largely unnoticed in October 1950 as U.S. and South Korean forces
pressed toward the Yalu River.
</P>
<P>
   In his new book, ''MacArthur's War,'' author Stanley Weintraub
described the scene, which marked a reversal of fortunes for a
U.S.-led United Nations force that believed it was within days of
winning the war.
</P>
<P>
   ''Effective at infiltrating enemy positions, the Chinese quickly
created panic. Organized resistance evaporated. Rushed forward to
help, the 5th Regiment (1st Cav) lost whole units to encirclement.
Suddenly it was a new war.''
</P>
<P>
   Liotta, deputy director of the Pentagon's POW-MIA office, said
wartime records indicate there are upward of 1,500 unrecovered
remains of U.S. servicemen in the Unsan and Kujang areas. He said
it was impossible to estimate beforehand how many might be
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got a pretty good chance of bringing back good numbers
of remains,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement permits the United States to broaden its search
for remains all the way to the Yalu River, on the Chinese border,
Liotta said. Many hundreds of U.S. POWs died in camps on the Korean
side of the Yalu.
</P>
<P>
   Remains recovered during this year's searches will be flown by
U.S. military aircraft from the North Korean capital to a U.S. air
base in Japan. For years the United States insisted that war
remains be repatriated through the United Nations Command at
Panmunjom, the border village inside the Demilitarized Zone.
</P>
<P>
   By the Pentagon's count, 8,174 U.S. servicemen are unaccounted
for from the Korean War, which began June 25, 1950, with a North
Korean invasion that nearly drove responding U.S. troops off the
peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the deal struck Friday in Kuala Lumpur, the
United States will be allowed 20 people on its search teams. Each
mission will last 25 days.
</P>
<P>
   For many years after the war ended in 1953, the United States
had no means of recovering remains north of the Demilitarized Zone
that was established to divide the capitalist South from the
communist North. But in the early 1990s, North Korea began
unilateral returns of a small number of remains, and later it
negotiated terms of cooperation on joint recovery missions, the
first of which was conducted in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of 12 recovery operations inside North Korea since
then, 42 sets of remains believed to be those of American soldiers
were recovered, although only three have been positively identified
by the Army's Central Identification Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   The searches were halted in November 1999 and a subsequent round
of talks in December broke off when North Korea demanded new
American humanitarian donations, including the construction of
factories to produce children's clothing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
