<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kennedy GOP Opponent Clears Hurdle  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- The state's Democratic and Libertarian parties
have challenged the nominating signatures collected by Jack E.
Robinson, the only Republican in the state's U.S. Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   The two other parties are hoping to disqualify enough signatures
to knock Robinson off the Republican primary ballot in September.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Secretary of State William Galvin certified
10,139 of the signatures gathered by Robinson. Candidates for U.S.
Senate in Massachusetts need 10,000 certified signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic incumbent Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, who has held the
seat since the 1960s, and Libertarian Carla Howell both submitted
well over the 10,000 margin for signatures. The Libertarian Party
is the only other party recognized by the state.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties said they found several problems with Robinson's
paperwork, including signatures that might not be genuine and
incomplete forms.
</P>
<P>
   The formal challenges, filed Friday, will be sent on to the
five-member, bipartisan state Ballot Law Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats already have had handwriting experts scouring
Robinson's papers, Galvin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats also may try to use the so-called ''stray mark''
rule to kill entire sheets of signatures. The Supreme Judicial
Court has ruled that no stray marks can be allowed on signature
papers for ballot questions, but have not said whether the same law
applies to signature papers for candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Galvin said he hopes the dispute is resolved in time for his
office to print ballots, but is worried it might drag on through
the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''It may well end up in court,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The challenges are the latest obstacle for the 39-year-old
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Within days of announcing his candidacy, reports surfaced that a
woman had taken a restraining order out against Robinson years
earlier. The millionaire businessman countered by releasing an
11-page ''Robinson Report'' outlining his past, including flunking
the bar three times and being accused of plagiarism.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Gov. Paul Cellucci and the party immediately pulled
their support.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci recently appeared on a morning talk radio show and
repeated his opposition to Robinson based in part on the
candidate's personal history.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson issued a news release Friday criticizing Cellucci for
continuing to raise questions about his past.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very sad that the governor would lash out like this,''
Robinson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-10-00 0117 </TRAILER>
