<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Speaks At Last Commencement  </HEADLINE>
By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In his last commencement address as chief
executive, President Clinton spotlights his administration's
efforts to fully open the doors of higher education to all
qualified Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was speaking to the 423 graduating seniors at Carleton
College, an academically distinguished school in Northfield, Minn.,
about 40 miles south of Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the president will use this last commencement to talk
at length on a subject that's very important to him -- breaking down
the barriers of educational opportunity in this country,'' said
White House press secretary Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said Clinton will cite his administration's
achievements in making college education more open and affordable
''and then look to the future in terms of the great investment we
make in our own lives -- in our own prosperity -- by investing in
education.''
</P>
<P>
   The Carleton College speech is the 23rd commencement address
Clinton has delivered since taking office in 1993 and his third
this year.
</P>
<P>
   His practice has been to speak at a military academy, a public
college or university and a private institution each year. Over
eight years he has spoken twice each at the Army, Navy, Air Force
and Coast Guard academies and addressed graduates at a range of
institutions, including New Hampshire Technical College (1993 ),
Princeton University (1996) and Grambling (La.) State University
(1999).
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has already spoken this year at the U.S. Coast Guard
Academy in New London, Conn. and at Eastern Michigan University in
Ypsilanti, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1866, Carleton College has about 1,850 students and
normally draws an audience of about 3,700 people to its outdoor
commencement ceremonies. This year, with the president as a drawing
card, about 7,000 are expected.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is the first sitting president ever to deliver a
commencement address at the school and is the first to visit the
campus since President Dwight D. Eisenhower campaigned there in
1956.
</P>
<P>
   The White House noted that Carleton is often near the top in
U.S. News &AMP; World Report's annual rankings of national liberal arts
colleges.
</P>
<P>
   During his one-day Minnesota visit, Clinton also was to address
a Democratic National Convention luncheon and attend a Soul Asylum
rock concert and Democratic Party fund-raiser, both in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.carleton.edu/commencement2000/index.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
