<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Monks, Government Clash Over Pagoda  </HEADLINE>
By TINI TRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) -- The famed lotus-bedecked grounds of the
One Pillar Pagoda have become the backdrop of a simmering battle
for control of the Buddhist shrine, underscoring Vietnam's tight
controls on religious activities.
</P>
<P>
   A government campaign to dismiss and expel the two resident
monks from the pagoda and replace them with a government appointee
has sparked strong resistance from local Buddhists.
</P>
<P>
   The yearlong dispute -- pitting Hanoi officials against
80-year-old presiding monk Thich Thanh Khanh and his assistant
Thich Tam Kien -- has drawn attention from Buddhist groups
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   While Vietnam's constitution enshrines freedom of religion, the
government traditionally maintains a firm grip on religious
activities.
</P>
<P>
   International human rights groups claim Catholics, Protestants
and members of the government-banned Unified Buddhist Church of
Vietnam are regularly suppressed.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, however, the monks were part of the
state-sanctioned Vietnam Buddhist Church.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute began last July, when the local People's Committee
of Ba Dinh District issued a letter dismissing Khanh as ''Superior
monk'' and expelling Kien. Khanh was ordered to turn over control
of the pagoda to a state-appointed monk.
</P>
<P>
   Khanh promptly fired off a letter to Vietnam's leaders and the
Communist Party, claiming the intervention violated the church's
charter, which says it has sole power over its internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The pagoda's congregation rallied around the monks, sending a
petition last fall protesting the measure as ''unlawful (and)
uncivilized.'' They cited a government decree stating the People's
Committee has authority only to approve, not appoint, religious
clergy and hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   The One Pillar Pagoda, or Chua Mot Cot, was built by Emperor Ly
Thai Tong in 1049. Legend says the heirless emperor dreamed one
night of meeting the Goddess of Mercy who, seated in a lotus
flower, handed him a male child. Seeing it as a heavenly omen, Tong
married a young peasant girl he met by chance and promptly had a
son. In gratitude, he had the pagoda created to honor the goddess.
</P>
<P>
   The small but elaborate wooden pagoda sits on a stone pillar
four feet wide in the middle of a lotus pond, evoking the image of
a blossom rising from a sea of sorrows. Located behind the Ho Chi
Minh Mausoleum in Hanoi, it is in a compound next to a full-fledged
temple where the caretaker monks live.
</P>
<P>
   The People's Committee, backed by the Hanoi Buddhist
Association, says Khanh was only an interim head of the pagoda
following the 1996 death of his predecessor, Thich Tam Can. Local
officials also claim Can's chosen disciple, Thich Tam Kien, is
unsuitable to be a monk and tarnishes the Buddhist religion. Thich
is the Buddhist title for monk.
</P>
<P>
   It did not give specifics, and requests to interview People's
Committee officials were denied.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon at the immaculate, incense-filled pagoda,
Kien angrily claimed the objections have nothing to do with
religion and everything to do with control.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials and the Hanoi Buddhist Association have long had
an eye on the One Pillar Pagoda, which gets a sizable number of
visitors and donations, he said. The monks keep the money for
maintenance and charity work.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a very famous pagoda and there's a lot of economic
profits. They don't care about the Buddhist cause; they only want
the profits and prestige of running this pagoda,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is apparently not the first time Hanoi has tried to gain
control of the pagoda. The Paris-based International Buddhist
Information Bureau, the information arm of the Unified Buddhist
Church of Vietnam, said the government planned to confiscate the
pagoda in the mid-1980s and turn it into a museum honoring Ho Chi
Minh, the father of modern Vietnam. After Buddhists objected en
masse, the plan was dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, the two monks have appealed for aid in
letters to the National Assembly, the Communist Party, the
government and local media. Local Buddhists have sent letters to
the outlawed Unified Buddhist Church of Vietnam asking it to help
mobilize support.
</P>
<P>
   The People's Committee issued an ultimatum in March that Kien
leave the premises by April 30 or ''relevant agencies would be
assigned to enforce measures.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two months later, Kien remains ensconced in the pagoda
and said no efforts have been made to remove him.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the authorities try to remove me, the followers will block
their way,'' he said. ''There is a saying that the righteous tree
has no fear of falling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-10-00 0123 </TRAILER>
