<HEADLINE> Gore Hopes Tour Will Attract Voters  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Talking about the national economic prosperity he
hopes will propel him into the White House, Vice President Al Gore
told the nation's mayors: ''All of us stand on the shoulders of
those who came before us.''
</P>
<P>
   But as he prepared to launch a ''prosperity tour'' next week
that is meant to win his presidential campaign a fresh look from
voters, Gore spoke nothing of the one who came before him or the
shoulders on which he stands -- President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In six speeches during an exhaustive 17-hour campaign swing in
Washington state on Friday, Gore previewed themes for his two-week
tour.
</P>
<P>
   ''You've heard about the vicious circle -- where things start
going wrong and everything else starts going wrong? Well, now we're
in what they call a virtuous circle. Things are going right,
leading to other things going right. We want to keep that going,''
Gore told the U.S. Conference of Mayors meeting in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   He made just one passing mention of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has asked Clinton's former Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin
to join the ''prosperity tour,'' which begins Tuesday in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign hopes the swing through battleground states will
prompt voters to give him some credit for the longest economic
expansion in American history -- and cast him as the only choice for
keeping it going.
</P>
<P>
   Gore warned the mayors that bad decisions about how to handle
budget surpluses are just as dangerous as bad decisions about
deficits.
</P>
<P>
   ''We could kill the golden goose. We could end up damaging our
prosperity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Introducing Gore to the bipartisan assembly, Denver Mayor
Wellington Webb, a Democrat, said Gore -- not Republican rival
George W. Bush -- was the better pick for America's cities because
the vice president has worked so closely with the mayors.
</P>
<P>
   Webb joked that Clinton and Gore have had the mayors at the
White House so many times that they no longer swipe napkins from
the mess or other souvenirs with the presidential seal.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll say, it's not so funny around the White House,'' Gore
countered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
