<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EPA fines Kodak for faulty record-keeping  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - The federal Environmental Protection
Agency has fined Eastman Kodak Co. $51,491 for violations in its
chemical reporting from 1995 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA discovered discrepancies in the Toxic Release Inventory
records during a 1998 inspection of Kodak Park. The penalty comes
three months after the EPA lodged a complaint with the
multi-billion-dollar photo company.
</P>
<P>
   Among the EPA charges that Kodak underreported the amount of
nitrate compounds it discharged into the Genesee River in 1995 and
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak spokesman James Blamphin said the errors consisted of bad
calculations or misunderstandings of reporting requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are record-keeping errors and they shouldn't have
occurred,'' said Blamphin.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the misinterpretation of reporting requirements
for nitrate compounds meant the company initially didn't report the
discharge of about 300,000 pounds of nitrates into the Genesee,
according to Blamphin.
</P>
<P>
   But later when the company discovered its own error, it was
reported to the EPA.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak submits 60 toxic release reports a year to the EPA, each
one on a different toxic chemical the company makes, uses or
disposes.
</P>
<P>
   The high number of reports required, and their complexity,
probably led to the reporting errors, said EPA regional spokeswoman
Nina Habib Spencer.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do not expect to see these errors repeated,'' said Spencer,
who characterized Kodak's reporting missteps as ''oversights.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kodak-watcher Judy Robinson, Buffalo-based regional director
of the Citizens' Environmental Coalition, called the incident
''very disturbing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Judy Robinson, Buffalo-based regional director of the
Citizens' Environmental Coalition, called the incident disturbing.
She said it casts doubt on the quality of information in the Toxic
Release Inventory.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the only tool citizens have to understand what
facilities are putting into the environment,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   The inventory, established by the 1984 federal Emergency
Planning and Community Right-to-Know Act and in effect since 1987,
requires industries to report chemical releases to the air, land
and water.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
