<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diplomats Fly To Solomons  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM FOREMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONIARA, Solomon Islands (AP) -- Diplomats from Australia and New
Zealand flew to the troubled Solomon Islands today, hoping to help
resolve the political crisis there and seek peace between warring
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   A delegation led by Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer
and New Zealand Foreign Minister Phil Goff landed this morning in
Honiara, the capital. The officials met with Solomon Islands Prime
Minister Bartholomew Ulufa'alu and planned to hold talks with the
rebels later, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The visit comes after five days of heightened unrest in this
South Pacific nation that has seen 18 months of fighting between
rival rebel groups from different islands.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, efforts to reach a 14-day truce between the Malaita
Eagle Force and the Isatabu Freedom Movement collapsed when the
better-armed Malaita group declined to sign on, New Zealand High
Commissioner Nick Hurley said. But the rebels agreed to a two-day
cease-fire so the ministers could come and go without any problems.
</P>
<P>
   Honiara appeared calm this afternoon. There was little activity
around one of the rebel bases near the airport, which is quite
close to the front line in the fighting. Elsewhere, people were out
shopping and golfing.
</P>
<P>
   The Solomon Islands are located 2,230 miles northwest of
Wellington, New Zealand and 1,600 miles northeast of Sydney,
Australia. Tensions here erupted Monday when the Malaita rebels
seized Prime Minister Ulufa'alu, placed him under house arrest and
demanded he resign. They held him for several days before
reportedly freeing him late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The move escalated a low-level conflict that has been playing
out here for a year and a half: The Isatabu rebels are indigenous
to the nation's main island of Guadalcanal and are trying to push
migrants from Malaita island off Guadalcanal, while the Malaita
rebels are resisting. The prime minister is a Malaitan, but some
Malaitans accuse him of being a turncoat.
</P>
<P>
   At least 50 people have been killed or are missing in the
fighting, and more than 20,000 have been forced out of their homes.
</P>
<P>
   After the prime minister's seizure, the Malaita rebels took
newly captured machine guns and a stolen police gunboat and began
attacking their rivals from the Isatabu Freedom Movement. Both
sides claim to have inflicted casualties, but none of the claims
have been confirmed and no fresh fighting was reported Friday or
early today.
</P>
<P>
   Downer and Goff, in a delegation with representatives from
Botswana and Malaysia, hope to encourage a peaceful end to the
troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hope that we will be able to help them resolve their
problems and get the peace process, which was pretty shaky before
this latest blowup ... back on track,'' Downer said Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   In Munda, on the island of New Georgia, about 200 miles
northwest of Honiara, some residents said early today they had
their doubts about any peace efforts from overseas.
</P>
<P>
   One mine company employee said the rebels are probably too
entrenched in their dispute to take any advice from the foreign
ministers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think they'll listen,'' Albert Jacob told a reporter.
''Things have gotten way out of hand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-10-00 0136 </TRAILER>
