<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Rebels Split Up Hostages  </HEADLINE>
By JIM GOMEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOLO, Philippines (AP) -- Muslim rebels holding 21 mostly foreign
hostages in a southern Philippine jungle have separated their
captives into two groups because of fears of a possible military
rescue attempt, negotiators said today.
</P>
<P>
   The Abu Sayyaf rebels have moved all 10 Caucasian hostages to a
new location, said Abdul Rajab Azzarouq, a Libyan envoy who is
serving as a government negotiator. But the 11 captives from
Malaysia and the Philippines are still at the previous jungle camp,
where the government recently built a wooden shed for the hostages'
protection, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators are holding talks with the rebels in an attempt to
win freedom for the hostages, who have been held for almost seven
weeks. This week, chief government negotiator Robert Aventajado
said the government would not rule out the option of a military
rescue if talks failed.
</P>
<P>
   The Abu Sayyaf criticized those comments in a communique
obtained today by the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   ''We strongly condemn him for such irresponsible statements,''
the Abu Sayyaf said. The group warned that the lives of the
hostages ''will be exposed to extreme risks'' if any rescue
operation is launched.
</P>
<P>
   The developments appeared to be a setback to hopes for the
hostages' release. Nevertheless, Azzarouq and another government
negotiator, Farouk Hussein, headed back today to a village mosque
guarded heavily by hundreds of Abu Sayyaf rebels for more talks
with guerrilla leaders.
</P>
<P>
   In several hours of talks Friday, the guerrillas refused to give
up their demand for an independent Islamic nation in the southern
Philippines, the negotiators said. The government has repeatedly
ruled out any breakup of the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they cannot compromise on their position, probably we
cannot proceed,'' Hussein said of the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The Abu Sayyaf is one of two main rebel groups fighting for an
independent Muslim nation here. The rebels seized the hostages --
three Germans, two French, two Finns, two South Africans, a
Lebanese, nine Malaysians and two Filipinos -- on April 23 from a
Malaysian diving resort and brought them to Jolo, an island at the
tip of the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's meeting had been intended only as a preparatory session
for a second round of formal negotiations, but instead it focused
at length on all of the rebels' demands, the two negotiators said.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides have held only one formal negotiating session, on
May 27.
</P>
<P>
   The slow pace has been bitterly criticized by the hostages,
whose psychological state has deteriorated in recent weeks as
prospects for their speedy release have dimmed. Several of the
hostages have threatened suicide, and a government doctor urged
Thursday that one, Stephane Loisy of France, be hospitalized for
psychological distress.
</P>
<P>
   President Joseph Estrada has ordered the negotiators to make
substantial progress by Monday, the Philippine independence day.
</P>
<P>
   A separate group of Abu Sayyaf rebels has been holding eight
Filipino hostages -- two teachers and six children -- on nearby
Basilan island. Rebel spokesman Abu Ahmad said Friday that those
rebels have slipped through a military dragnet and escaped to Jolo
with six of the hostages. It was not clear what happened to the
other two.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
