<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Reverses Makah Whaling Ruling  </HEADLINE>
By SCOTT ANDREWS
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Makah whaling canoes are likely to be beached for
only a few months by an appeals court ruling that ordered another
environmental review of the tribe's gray whale hunts, a tribal
lawyer says.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, anti-whaling activists said they were elated by the
ruling Friday from a three-judge panel of the 9th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals, which they hope will lead to a permanent halt of
the hunt.
</P>
<P>
   The case now goes back to federal court in Tacoma for additional
proceedings, including the new environmental study by the National
Marine Fisheries Service.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very important to recognize that this is really a
temporary setback for the tribe. The court in no way questioned the
fact that the Makah have a treaty right to take whales,'' said John
Arum, Seattle-based attorney for the tribe, whose reservation lies
at the extreme northwestern tip of Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   Arum said the tribe may ask the full 9th Circuit to review the
panel's 2-1 ruling. But even if it does not, he expected any new
environmental study will find the Makah hunt would not hurt whale
populations, likely clearing the way for the tribe's fall hunt to
begin as scheduled in November.
</P>
<P>
   In their ruling, the San Francisco appellate judges said the
government's environmental assessment was biased in favor of
approving Makah whaling, because the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration had earlier signed an accord with the
Makah promising to support their efforts to resume whaling.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Gorman, a Seattle spokesman for the National Marine
Fisheries Service, which is a co-defendant in the case, said the
government had not decided whether to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But if the agency does do another environmental assessment, it
would make ''extremely sure that we are extremely careful and
forthright,'' Gorman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Makah had hunted whales for generations until the 1920s,
when commercial whaling decimated the whale population. But the
tribe moved to resume the hunt after gray whales were removed from
the Endangered Species List in 1994 and received approval, with the
backing of the federal government, from the International Whaling
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal members killed their first and only gray whale in May
1999, after U.S. District Judge Franklin Burgess in Tacoma rejected
a challenge by environmentalists and Rep. Jack Metcalf, R-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt that we were right all the time,'' Metcalf said Friday,
adding that he expected the tribe or government to appeal the
panel's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Makah whalers this spring have come close enough to hurl a
harpoon at whales, but they have made no kills. The tribe will not
hunt whales again until cleared by the courts, Keith Johnson, head
of the Makah Tribal Whaling Commission, told KIRO-FM.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-whaling activists will remain ''on standby'' at Neah Bay,
the launch site for tribal canoes, at least through the end of
June, said Jonathan Paul, president of Williams, Ore.-based Ocean
Defense International, which has attempted to disrupt several Makah
hunts.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Defense activist Erin Abbott, 23, who buzzed a Makah canoe
with a personal watercraft and was in turn run over by a Coast
Guard inflatable boat April 20, pleaded guilty Friday in U.S.
District Court in Tacoma to negligent operation of a vessel. She
faces a maximum year behind bars and a $100,000 fine when she is
sentenced Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott was hospitalized with shoulder and other injuries in the
boat incident.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-10-00 0145 </TRAILER>
