<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, June 9, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
N.M. Park Superintendent To Retire
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- Roy Weaver, the park superintendent who approved a
prescribed burn that blew out of control and rolled through Los Alamos last
month, said Friday he will retire in July. Weaver, superintendent of Bandelier
National Monument for nearly 10 years, said he believed conditions had been just
right for the park's annual regimen of burning brush May 4 to stave off a
potentially disastrous fire. But after the burn was started, it became the
largest wildfire in state history, destroying more than 200 homes in Los Alamos
and forcing 25,000 people to evacuate.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Philippine Rebels Split Up Hostages
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JOLO, Philippines (AP) -- Muslim rebels holding 21 mostly foreign hostages in
a southern Philippine jungle have separated their captives into two groups
because of fears of a possible military rescue attempt, negotiators said today.
The Abu Sayyaf rebels have moved all 10 Caucasian hostages to a new location,
said Abdul Rajab Azzarouq, a Libyan envoy who is serving as a government
negotiator. But the 11 captives from Malaysia and the Philippines are still at
the previous jungle camp, where the government recently built a wooden shed for
the hostages' protection, he said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Alaska Airlines Submits Plans
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Alaska Airlines on Friday filed its response to the Federal
Aviation Administration's concerns over the company's maintenance practices. A
recent audit and inspection by the FAA turned up more than 150 cases of missing
or incomplete maintenance records, the agency announced last week. The
inspection was launched after the Jan. 31 crash of an Alaska Airlines jet off
the California coast. Although further investigation found that the maintenance
in question had been adequately performed, the FAA is considering stripping
Alaska of the right to perform heavy maintenance -- work that requires an
aircraft be removed from service while major components are repaired or
replaced.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S., North Korea Reach Agreement
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- U.S. and North Korean officials reached an
agreement Friday to immediately resume the search for more than 8,000 U.S.
soldiers missing in action from the Korean War. The first search mission is
scheduled for June 25, the 50th anniversary of the outbreak of the Korean War.
The agreement to conduct five joint operations between June and November was
reached after three days of talks between the U.S. Defense Department and the
North Korean People's Liberation Army. As a result of previous negotiations,
U.S. teams have conducted 12 recovery operations inside North Korea since 1996
and found 42 sets of remains.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Protesters Damage Cars in Lebanon
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KFAR KILA, Lebanon (AP) -- U.N. efforts to lay down borders between Lebanon
and Israel hit bumpy terrain Friday, with protesters stoning U.N. inspection
teams, officials raising objections and villagers threatening to evict
peacekeepers. Also Friday, Palestinians threw stones at Israeli troops on the
border. Several protesters cut the fence and walked through, drawing warning
shots from Israeli guards. The day's troubles highlighted the continuing
turbulence along the border, where there has been no real authority since last
month's Israeli troop withdrawal from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Drops 55; Nasdaq Gains 49
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in a quiet session Friday. The Dow Jones
industrial average fell 54.66 to close at 10,614.06. On the NYSE, gainers led
losers 1,667-1,188. The Nasdaq composite index rose 49.28 to close at 3,874.84.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Giants Beat Mariners 9-2
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Kirk Rueter pitched 6 2-3 strong innings for his first
win in more than six weeks, and Ellis Burks and J.T. Snow homered as the San
Francisco Giants broke out of their interleague slump by beating the Seattle
Mariners 9-2 Friday night. Rueter (3-4) gave up two runs and seven hits and even
got his first two hits of the season in stopping a personal three-game skid. He
continued his dominating pitching in interleague play, improving to 8-1,
including a seven-game winning streak against AL teams. John Halama (6-2) lost
his second straight since becoming the third Mariner starter to open a season
6-0.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lakers Beat Pacers 111-104
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Lakers overcame an injury to Kobe Bryant
to defeat the foul-happy Indiana Pacers 111-104 Friday night in Game 2 of the
NBA Finals. Game 3 is Sunday, and the Pacers will be hard-pressed to come up
with a crazier strategy to turn this series around and try to become just the
third team in league history to come back from such a deficit in the finals.
Jalen Rose scored 30 to lead Indiana, Austin Croshere added 24 and Reggie Miller
had 21 -- just two coming in the fourth quarter.
</P>
