<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mets 12, Yankees 2  </HEADLINE>
By BEN WALKER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - By the time Roger Clemens walked off the mound,
almost every Yankees fan in the ballpark was booing except Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza once again derailed the Rocket, hitting a grand slam
Friday night that sent the New York Mets over the New York Yankees
12-2 in the opener of this year's Subway Series.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've always enjoyed the tradition of Yankee Stadium,'' Piazza
said. ''Just getting your name read over the public-address system
gives you a shot of adrenaline.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza's slam silenced the Yankees rooters in the sellout crowd
of 55,822. But not for long.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens (4-6) was tagged for nine runs - matching the most he's
allowed in 492 career starts - and was jeered after Edgardo
Alfonzo's two-run homer made it 9-2 with no outs in the sixth
inning. That was Clemens' final pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ''The boos, I was as hacked off as anybody else was,'' Clemens
said. ''I felt I had better stuff than the final score says it was.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was trying to keep the ball in the yard, gave up too many
homers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, wearing a Yankees cap, stood and applauded from next
to his favorite team's dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was ashamed that any Yankee fan would boo him. He's pitched
some great games for us,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It wasn't my happiest night here tonight, but I'll be back
Sunday,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Bell, who began the night in a 3-for-53 slump, hit a
homer, double and single and drove in five runs. The Mets closed
their deficit to 7-6 against the Yankees in four seasons of
interleague play.
</P>
<P>
   Al Leiter (7-1) beat Clemens for the third time in two years.
And in all three games, Piazza provided a big home run - this time,
launching a long drive to dead center field.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been fortunate to have some success in this series,''
Piazza said. ''These games are exciting and electric.''
</P>
<P>
   With the crowd standing and chanting, cheering and booing,
Piazza slowly strode to the plate with the bases loaded and no outs
in the third inning of a scoreless game.
</P>
<P>
   On a 1-0 pitch, he unloaded.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza stood to watch the ball sail for his 11th career slam and
second this year, while Clemens kicked at the rubber. It was only
the second slam Clemens had ever given up.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a very frightening guy to have on the other side,''
Yankees manager Joe Torre said. ''Not too many guys can hit a ball
to center field and flip the bat knowing it's a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Piazza's third home run in 11 career at-bats against
Clemens. The first homer came last June and helped reverse the
fortunes of both the Mets and Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets ended an eight-game losing streak that night, a day
after firing three coaches, and reached the .500 mark on their way
toward making the NL playoffs. Clemens, meanwhile, had his
AL-record 20-game winning streak stopped and has been a sub-.500
pitcher since.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, originally selected by the Mets in the June 1981
amateur draft, fell to 1-4 with a 9.10 ERA against them. He also
started against them twice for Boston in the 1986 World Series, and
did not get a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens has allowed nine runs on five occasions, mostly recently
on May 18, 1998, for Toronto against Seattle. The Mets tagged him
for eight earned runs and 10 hits.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter, the only Mets player who also spent time with the
Yankees, allowed two runs in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Jason Tyner led off the game with a double and later
singled, scored twice and made a diving catch in left field.
</P>
<P>
   ''I stepped in the box and looked up and it was like, 'Geez,
that's Roger Clemens,''' said Tyner, who grew up in Texas, where
the Rocket is revered. ''My first week in the big leagues and I'm
facing Roger Clemens at Yankee Stadium.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
