<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prison guard accused of beating inmate  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A 41-year-old state prison guard has been
charged with beating an inmate, setting-up an inmate-on-inmate
confrontation and planting a knife in a maximum security prison.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Carroll, a correction officer at Coxsackie Correctional
Facility, was suspended from duty on May 10.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll has not yet been arrested and has appealed the proposed
discipline - dismissal and loss of accrued leave.
</P>
<P>
   According to a notice of discipline sent to Carroll by the state
Department of Correctional Services, alleged crimes include
illegally giving an Albany FBI special agent a document taken from
a prisoner's cell.
</P>
<P>
   The notice also says Carroll failed to stop Sam Hall from
attempting to assault Justin Eldred during a lunchtime encounter on
July 24.
</P>
<P>
   The corrections department alleges that on the day of the
encounter between Eldred and Hall, Carroll struck Eldred
unnecessarily. Using his baton, he allegedly hit Eldred on his
back, legs and head while Eldred lay stomach-down on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day as those incidents, Carroll allegedly planted a
7-inch ''shank,'' or knife, where Eldred encountered Hall, the
notice says.
</P>
<P>
   The charges also state that Carroll filed a false ''inmate
misbehavior report'' on Eldred and lied to Special FBI Agent Marc
Promutico and the Inspector General's Office investigators about
the events of that day.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the alleged actions, the notice of discipline said,
constituted misdemeanors, while the introduction of a knife into
the prison would be a felony.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Foglia, a department spokeswoman, confirmed that a notice
of discipline was sent to Carroll and that he has been suspended
without pay since May 10.
</P>
</TEXT>
