<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 05:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Joe Puma, jazz guitarist, dead at 72  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Joe Puma, a jazz guitarist whose reflective
style placed him in demand as both a soloist and ensemble member,
died in the Bronx on May 31 of cancer. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
   Puma earned accolades across a half century for his versatility,
from his light, restrained sound and jaunty persona as a soloist to
his exceptional collaborative technique as an accompanist.
</P>
<P>
   A self-taught guitarist, Puma's career began in 1948, with his
first major job the following year with the vibraphonist Joe
Roland. He went on to record with jazz artists including Louie
Bellson, Artie Shaw's Gramercy Five, Eddie Bert, Herbie Mann, Mat
Mathews and Chris Connor. He later recorded with Bobby Hackett,
Gary Burton and Carmen McRae.
</P>
<P>
   Puma was a favorite accompanist of singers like Peggy Lee,
Morgana King, Helen Merrill and Tony Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, he formed a duo with Chuck Wayne, and they appeared at
the 1973 Newport Jazz Festival in New York. Puma later led his own
trio, and remained musically active until the late 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   He recorded on his own for the Bethlehem, Dawn Jubilee and
Columbia labels in the 1950s and 1960s, and led a later session for
Reservoir in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Among his recordings are ''Like Tweet,'' with songs based on
bird calls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
