<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 09:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ben Shahn Art Exhibit Opens  </HEADLINE>
By CARL HARTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ben Shahn, a foremost artist of the 1930s,
made his reputation painting realistic New York scenes from the
Great Depression, but a new exhibit at the Phillips Collection
shows that he found his photographs just as important.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a social painter or photographer,'' he once told an
interviewer. ''I find difficulty in making distinctions between
photography and painting. Both are pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 14 easel paintings and 112 photos in the show, which
opened Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Turner, curator of the show, called Shahn ''one of
America's greatest artists.''
</P>
<P>
   He liked doing paintings that closely followed the photos he had
snapped himself or found in newspapers. He based one painting on an
Associated Press photo of a demonstration in New York's Union
Square on May 1, 1932.
</P>
<P>
   Putting a right angle viewfinder on his 35 mm. Leica camera
enabled Shahn to shoot faces while appearing to focus in a
different direction. That gave him candid shots without his
subjects knowing they were being pictured. His painting called
''Myself Among the Churchgoers'' depicts him doing just that.
</P>
<P>
   Some photographers think such deception unethical. That didn't
bother Shahn, though he called flash bulbs ''immoral'' because he
felt they destroyed the natural darkness and mystery of a scene.
</P>
<P>
   Shahn got his first and only lessons from Walker Evans, the
classic photographer. They worked together both in lower Manhattan
and picturing poverty in the southeast for the New Deal's Farm
Security Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Giving instructions on how to set his photo exposure, ''F/9 on
the sunny side of the street, F/4.5 on the shady side of the
street,'' was all Walker told Shahn. ''For a 20th of a second hold
your camera steady.''
--------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: www.phillipscollection.org
</P>
<P>
   ''Ben Shahn's New York: The Photography of Modern Times'' will
be at the Phillips Collection through Aug. 27. Weekend admission:
Adults $7.50; Seniors $4; 18 and under free. On weekdays
contributions are suggested in the same amounts.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit moves to the Grey Art Gallery, New York University,
New York, N.Y. Oct. 14, 2000 to Jan 27, 2001 and the David and
Alfred Smart Museum of Art, University of Chicago, April 19 to June
17.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-10-00 0904 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000610.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 11:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police arrest 12 in New York-Philadelphia crack ring  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BINGHAMTON, N.Y. (AP) - A federal prosecutor said a Jamaican
drug ring that brought more than a pound of crack cocaine a week to
upstate New York from Philadelphia was cracked.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve people were arrested in a series of raids Friday in the
southern tier and in Philadelphia. Three more are sought in the
18-month investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the Jamaican drug ring operated in Broome County for
more than a year, moving large amounts of crack. Assistant U.S.
Attorney Miroslav Lovric said the investigation began in January
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Charged in the federal indictment with conspiracy to distribute
and possess with intent to distribute crack cocaine were: Roger
Beecham, 40, and Regina Williams, 34, of Johnson City; Elaine
Shannon, 47, and Tislam DuPont, 23, also known as James Douglas, of
Binghamton.
</P>
<P>
   A fifth suspect named in the federal indictment, Walik Skeete,
23, of Binghamton, remains at large.
</P>
<P>
   Also arrested was Norris C. Taylor, 47, of Binghamton, charged
with eight counts of third-degree criminal sale of a controlled
substance, one count of third-degree criminal possession of a
controlled substance and one count of fourth-degree conspiracy, all
felonies. Taylor also is charged with unlawful possession of
marijuana, a misdemeanor.
</P>
<P>
   Police in Philadelphia arrested Alvin Jordan, 21, of
Philadelphia, charging him with two counts of third-degree criminal
sales of a controlled substance, a felony.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation continues, with two other people still being
sought.
</P>
<P>
   Beecham, Williams, Shannon, Taylor, Jordan and DuPont were
arraigned either in federal or local court and held in jail Friday.
Others were released on bail.
</P>
</TEXT>
