<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five sentenced in $35 million upstate theft ring  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW HARTFORD, N.Y. (AP) - Five more members of an organized
shoplifting ring that operated in 11 counties to steal more than
$35 million in merchandise have been sentenced.
</P>
<P>
   The massive and organized shoplifting case was broken with
eavesdropping devices, said Alan Blumenkopf, an assistant deputy
attorney general with the state Organized Crime Task Force. Now, 13
of more than 25 members of the ring have been sentenced as a result
of the theft and distribution of goods in central New York. The
arrests were made in February.
</P>
<P>
   Among stores targeted were national retail chains, such as
Wal-Mart, K-Mart, CVS, Eckerd Drugs, Ames, BJs Wholesale Club,
Sears, J.C. Penney, Staples, Office Max and Hallmark.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the ring are alleged to have worked in teams and
targeted specific items that were believed to be easy to re-sell,
including videos, razor blades, batteries, compact discs, video
games, Texas calculators, over-the-counter medications, film,
disposable cameras, electric razors, tools, compact radios and CD
players.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Joseph J. Tebsherany, 67, of Oneida Street, Utica,
was sentenced to a year in Oneida County jail.
</P>
<P>
   John C. Alberico, 39, of Walker Road, Deerfield, who previously
pleaded guilty to a charge of fourth-degree criminal possession of
stolen goods, told Dwyer he made ''a terrible choice'' in becoming
involved in the theft ring and asked for the court's leniency.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're someone who really upsets me,'' Dwyer replied,
according to the Utica Observer-Dispatch. ''You have the
intelligence and the means to support yourself legally, like
everyone else. There is no reason for you to get involved in this
nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing a responsibility by Alberico to care for his children,
Dwyer decided not to place him in jail. Instead, Alberico received
five years' probation, a $3,500 fine and was ordered to perform 100
hours of community service. As a condition of his probation,
Alberico must maintain ''suitable employment.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I will give you one more chance,'' Dwyer added. ''But, believe
me, if you let me down, you will regret it.''
</P>
<P>
   Also sentenced to five years probation were Robert Lavalla, 51,
of Frankfort, and Frank Meola, 35, and Joel M. Galinn 62, of Utica.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
