<HEADLINE> No fish tale: fishermen illegally catch 100 pounds of bass in afternoon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PENFIELD, N.Y. (AP) - It's a fishermen's nightmare: catching 98
bass in four hours and not being able to tell anyone.
</P>
<P>
   But after trying to sell the catch to an undercover officer for
sale despite a health concern, they talked.
</P>
<P>
   Now Gerald Locurcio, 50, and Gary Holtz, 47, of Rochester have
each been fined $750 for the illegal sale, possession and
transportation of the 115 pounds of bass from Lake Ontario. They
pleaded guilty to the violations after police say they tried to
sell the catch for $250 to an undercover officer.
</P>
<P>
   They could be banned from game fishing in New York for up to 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Environmental Conservation officials say Locurcio
and Holtz used rods and reels to catch the fish off Sodus Point in
Wayne County during a four-hour span last summer. The daily limit
is five per person during the season, which runs from mid-June
through November.
</P>
<P>
   Selling game fish such as black bass and lake trout is illegal.
Despite the ban, grocers who serve poor neighborhoods sometimes buy
them.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said the DEC has charged several Rochester stores during
the past 18 months with offering game fish for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Markets can buy black-market fish for $2 or $3 a pound and
double the price to customers and still undercut supermarket
prices.
</P>
<P>
   But black-market fish are health risk. The state recommends
eating no more than half a pound of Lake Ontario bass a month.
Pregnant women and children should avoid them completely.
</P>
<P>
   ''The upside is: That's how good the fishing is,'' said Lt. Dave
Baker, a DEC enforcement officer. ''The downside is, it creates the
ability for people to take large quantities to sell them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
