<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Die in Japan Chemical Plant Blast  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- A chemical plant exploded Saturday north of Tokyo,
killing four workers, injuring at least 27 people and shattering
the windows of nearby homes.
</P>
<P>
   The four workers killed were inside the plant run by Nisshin
Chemical Co., and four other workers in the plant at the time of
the blast were hospitalized, police said.
</P>
<P>
   One person lost an ear in the accident in Gunma Prefecture, 65
miles north of Tokyo, they said. Many were cut by flying pieces of
glass.
</P>
<P>
   The fumes were not toxic, Ojima city official Eiichi Kanai said.
The explosion took place during the mixing of hydroxylamine with a
water solution, Kanai said. Hydroxylamine is used to remove oxygen
from other substances.
</P>
<P>
   A fire set off by the blast was brought under control late
Saturday, police said. The cause of the explosion was under
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The workers were processing semiconductors, an electronic part
used in transistors and computers, Kyodo News agency said. The
explosion also caused power failures at more than 200 households,
Kyodo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
