<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inmate's death on work detail raises concern over inmate safety  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WILTON, N.Y. (AP) - An inmate working on a church during a work
detail died Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Clark, 34, of Brooklyn was in a crew of nine inmates and a
corrections officer from the Mt. McGregor Correctional Facility's
minimum security camp. They were refurbishing a church in the
Saratoga County town of Wilton when Clark touched an aluminum
ladder as a gust of wind knocked it into a 7,600-volt overhead
power line. The jolt was fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Clark is the first inmate to die in a work-related crew accident
in at least 15 years, a state official said.
</P>
<P>
   Prison system critic Alice Green, however, said inmates have
little protection during community work projects.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they were free people, they would have all kinds of
protections under the Department of Labor. Here, because they are
exploited slave labor, there is very little concern about their
safety,'' said Green, director of the Center for Law and Justice
based in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   While an official for the federal Occupational Safety and Health
Administration said the agency has no jurisdiction in the case, a
state official said those safety rules are followed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was told we follow the OSHA standards for inmates,'' said
corrections spokesman James Flateau. ''One of the reasons we do
that is that inmates are out there supervised by officers, and we
can't send the inmates to do things the officers can't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
