<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Rebels Split Up Hostages  </HEADLINE>
By JIM GOMEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOLO, Philippines (AP) -- Muslim rebels, fearing a military raid,
have moved 10 Caucasian hostages to a new hiding place in the
southern Philippine jungle, negotiators said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Abu Sayyaf rebels, who have been holding 21 mostly foreign
hostages, kept the 11 captives from Malaysia and the Philippines at
the previous jungle camp, where the government recently built a
wooden shed for the hostages' protection, said Abdul Rajab
Azzarouq, a Libyan envoy who is serving as a government negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels also announced they will no longer talk to chief
government negotiator Robert Aventajado, who suggested earlier in
the week that the government might consider a military rescue if
talks for the hostages' release break down.
</P>
<P>
   ''We strongly condemn him for such irresponsible statements,''
the Abu Sayyaf said in a communique. The group warned that the
lives of the hostages ''will be exposed to extreme risks'' if any
rescue operation is launched.
</P>
<P>
   Aventajado said today that his comment was taken out of context.
''The government panel does not consider, much less endorse, an
armed response to the hostage crisis,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the developments appeared to be a considerable
setback to hopes for the hostages' release.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to start again from the beginning,'' said Farouk
Hussein, another government negotiator. ''This is a very sad
development.''
</P>
<P>
   Hussein and Azzarouq headed back Saturday to a village mosque
guarded by hundreds of rebels for a second day of talks with
guerrilla leaders. ''The talks are going on, but it's a tough
one,'' Azzarouq said after their return.
</P>
<P>
   During the latest talks, the guerrillas refused to give up their
demand for an independent Islamic nation in the southern
Philippines, the negotiators said. The government has repeatedly
ruled out any breakup of the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   The Abu Sayyaf is one of two main rebel groups fighting for an
independent Muslim nation here. The rebels seized the hostages --
three Germans, two French, two Finns, two South Africans, a
Lebanese, nine Malaysians and two Filipinos -- on April 23 from a
Malaysian diving resort and brought them to Jolo, an island at the
tip of the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   The slow pace of negotiations has been bitterly criticized by
the hostages, whose psychological state has deteriorated in recent
weeks as prospects for their speedy release have dimmed. Several of
the hostages have threatened suicide, and a government doctor urged
Thursday that one, Stephane Loisy of France, be hospitalized for
psychological distress.
</P>
<P>
   President Joseph Estrada has ordered the negotiators to make
substantial progress by Monday, the Philippine independence day.
</P>
<P>
   In another part of the southern Philippines, at least six Muslim
rebels belonging to the Moro Islamic Liberation Front were killed
and two civilian militiamen wounded Saturday after guerrillas
attacked a village, said Maj. Lito Aso of the army's 6th Infantry
Division.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
