<HEADLINE> Guerrillas Attack Russian Positions  </HEADLINE>
By RUSLAN MUSAYEV
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZRAN, Russia (AP) -- Chechen guerrillas attacked Russian
positions in Chechnya six times overnight, the military command
said Saturday, while police in the capital Grozny searched for
gunmen who killed three Russian medical specialists.
</P>
<P>
   A group of epidemiologists were riding in an Emergency
Situations Ministry car near a Grozny hospital Friday when gunmen
opened fire on them. Three of the specialists were killed and three
were wounded, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Police carried out selective passport checks in the Zavodskoi
district of Grozny, where the attack took place, and were searching
through the rubble of destroyed buildings nearby, where the rebels
could be hiding out, the military's press center said.
</P>
<P>
   The military concedes that as many as 500 rebels are still in
Grozny, even though the Russians took control of the Chechen
capital more than four months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Chechen rebels opened fire on six units of Russian Interior
Ministry troops overnight in different parts of the breakaway
republic, the press center said. It said there were no Russian
casualties in the assaults.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Vladimir Putin, in an interview with Germany's
ARD and ZDF television, said his decision to impose direct
presidential rule on Chechnya and suspend local elections was
legal. Putin's decision still must be approved by the Russian
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything we are saying and doing to strengthen legality is
absolutely in keeping with the Constitution,'' he said in the
interview aired on Russian television Saturday. ''Not a single step
of the government or the president is intended to abolish
democratic institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin's move formalized the Kremlin's control of the republic.
Direct presidential rule means a suspension of Chechnya's right as
part of the Russian federation to elect its own officials,
legislature and regional government.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, Chechnya would be run by a provisional
administration headed by a Putin-appointed chief. Putin said the
appointment of the administrator would be made soon.
</P>
<P>
   After that, he said, ''we shall go over to normal democratic
procedures, to elections, as soon as the social sphere is
restored.''
</P>
<P>
   The rebels, who want independence, show no sign of giving up the
war.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian offensive against Chechnya, which began in late
September, has stalled for months in the rugged southern mountains.
The rebels have kept up ambushes and bombings in the northern
lowlands that have inflicted a steady stream of losses on Russian
forces and sapped troop morale.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 2,000 rebels remain in the mountains and many of them
are spreading into other parts of the republic, Gen. Viktor
Kazantsev, a top commander in the Caucasus, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians were driven out of Chechnya in a 1994-96 war. They
re-entered in September after Islamic militants based there seized
several villages in the neighboring Russian region of Dagestan, and
after about 300 people died in apartment bombings the government
blames on Chechens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
