<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 13:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fear in Israel-Free South Lebanon  </HEADLINE>
By ZEINA KARAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOULA, Lebanon (AP) -- Prone on a mattress with a slightly
bloodied bandage on his forehead, Mohammed Ayoub is too scared to
say much about the beating he suffered when he returned to his
village.
</P>
<P>
   His neighbors are nearly as reticent, only hinting that the
unidentified assailants had decided that a Beirut court was wrong
in ruling that Ayoub was too old to prosecute for any links to a
pro-Israeli militia, the South Lebanon Army.
</P>
<P>
   In their fearful silence is a warning of a new cycle of violence
now that Israeli troops have pulled out of south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Since Israel's hasty May 24 withdrawal and the collapse of the
SLA, there has been little violence against those who once worked
with the Jewish state. The restraint is all the more remarkable
considering Lebanon's long years of sectarian civil war, but it is
clear the veil of calm could easily be torn away.
</P>
<P>
   There have been reports of harassment and up to 30
extra-judicial arrests by Shiite Muslim guerrillas in dozens of
southern villages, targeting people for alleged pro-Israeli
activities during the 18-year occupation of the area set up as a
buffer zone against cross-border guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Israeli army left, the guerrillas have been the main
security presence in a region that is a patchwork of Muslim and
Christian villages.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of police officers, State Security and military
intelligence agents have been dispatched to the area, which makes
up 10 percent of Lebanon and is home to 120,000 people, but no
serious Lebanese army presence.
</P>
<P>
   The deployment of U.N. peacekeepers along the border awaits
official verification of the Israeli pullout.
</P>
<P>
   The reports of harassment, in addition to widespread anger over
what many perceive to be light sentences for people they describe
as former tormentors, have fed concerns about the future in the
south.
</P>
<P>
   Many members of the 2,500-strong SLA fled to Israel with the
retreat of the Israeli troops. Up to 1,500, however, surrendered to
Lebanese authorities and await trial for treason. A Beirut military
court has already ruled in more than 130 cases, sentencing most of
the former militiamen to one year in jail. Other sentences ranged
from one month to 10 years. In the toughest sentence, one received
15 years.
</P>
<P>
   In a few cases, elderly defendants or those with health problems
were released on humanitarian grounds, including Mohammed Ayoub
from Houla. The 60-year-old father of 14 was let go last week
during preliminary interrogations to return to this Shiite Muslim
village just a few miles from the Israeli border.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear how Ayoub was linked to the SLA. Some of those
who surrendered were just cooks or doorkeepers or people who had
gone to Israel for jobs because work was scarce in economically
depressed south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was injured in a fight with my neighbor that was started by
our kids,'' the visibly distraught man said, denying he was ever a
member of the SLA.
</P>
<P>
   Ayoub's fate is proof Hassan Rizk has reason to worry. His son
Osama, who he says was coerced into joining the SLA in 1995, was
sentenced last week to 18 months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ''What if some crazy guy decides my son deserves to die and
kills him when he returns to the village?'' asks Rizk, 62, a Shiite
like the dominant Hezbollah and Amal guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   Hassan Hijazi, a former guerrilla who fought against Israel with
a small Communist party, was tortured in the SLA-run Khiam
detention center and says he cannot forgive his captors -- now in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Hijazi says he was paralyzed when he was caught in a shoot-out
between a friend and robbers in Paraguay, where he fled upon his
release from Khiam. Now the green-eyed, bearded Hijazi sits in a
wheelchair and drags slowly on a cigarette at his father's grocery
store as he contemplates the possible return of his SLA torturer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would slit his throat,'' he said thoughtfully.
</P>
<P>
   Zeinab Abbas, modest in a black robe and headscarf, feels the
same. She says her 28-year-old brother, Khalil Asaad, was shot and
killed on the streets of their town by an SLA militiaman who now
awaits trial. Her brother, who she says was not a guerrilla, has
been dead 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   If her brother's killer returns to her village, ''I will take
matters into my own hands . ... If the government does not recover
our dignity, we will have to do it ourselves,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah guerrillas have warned of violence if former
militiamen return even after serving sentences. Mindful of the
volatility, the military court ordered some ex-militiamen it
sentenced to prison terms to stay away from their villages for up
to 15 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-10-00 1305 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000610.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spending Bills Help GOP Donors  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN D. SALANT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Less money for a federal lawsuit against the
tobacco industry. No pressure for more fuel-efficient cars. Delayed
mining regulations. Free tests for egg producers.
</P>
<P>
   Big Republican donors are getting all sorts of help in their
battles against Clinton administration regulations, thanks to
special measures the GOP-controlled Congress has buried in agency
spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   The White House is hoping to make the special measures, called
riders, election-year issues.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., is trying to persuade his
Republican troops to limit the provisions and avoid an impasse on
spending bills like the ones that shut down the government in 1995
and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're trying to take riders off the bills,'' Hastert spokesman
John Feehery said. ''We want to get these bills done as quickly as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the special-interest provisions are piling up in the
legislation to fund federal agencies in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president simply cannot and will not sign bills so
burdened by riders that they do serious harm to the environment and
otherwise damage the interests of the American people,'' said Jack
Lew, President Clinton's budget director.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, the House refused to drop one of them -- a
provision to quash new workplace regulations for preventing
repetitive stress injuries. Companies reviled the regulations,
fearing new costs. Unions, the biggest financial backers of
Democrats, backed the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential aides have identified at least 40 such provisions
in spending bills and are drawing parallels to 1995. ''They're back
to their old tricks,'' White House chief of staff John Podesta
said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans counter that their measures are needed to fix a
government too eager to impose regulations without considering the
financial impact.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jack Kingston, R-Ga., has inserted a provision in an
agriculture spending bill that would block the Food and Drug
Administration's plan to require egg producers to pay the cost of
federal tests for salmonella in eggs.
</P>
<P>
   ''They shouldn't be putting this on the backs of the farmer,''
Kingston said, noting the government pays for similar meat and
poultry inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Critics note many of the measures help large GOP donors in an
election year when both the White House and control of Congress are
up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, egg and poultry farms have given $174,000 to
federal candidates this election cycle, two-thirds of it to
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ''These appropriations bills have become laden down with
language to protect the wealthiest and most influential special
interests in the country,'' said Rep. Maurice Hinchey, D-N.Y., a
member of the House Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Other provisions would:
</P>
<P>
   --Delay any Environmental Protection Agency decision on cleaning
up PCBs until after the National Academy of Sciences completes a
study due this fall. The legislation was championed by Rep. John
Sweeney, R-N.Y., whose district includes a General Electric plant
that disposed of PCBs in the Hudson River. GE has contributed
$356,600 to federal candidates, more than 80 percent to
Republicans. Scientific studies have linked PCBs, or
polychlorinated biphenyls, to cancer. They have been banned in the
U.S. manufacture of products since the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   --Prevent other federal agencies, like the Veterans
Administration, from helping finance the Justice Department's
lawsuit against big tobacco. The industry has been among the top
contributors to the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco PACs have contributed $670,869 to Republicans, compared
with $300,806 to Democrats. The industry also has contributed $1.7
million in unregulated soft money donations to the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the Justice Department wants to proceed with a lawsuit,
that's fine,'' said Rep. James Walsh, R-N.Y., chairman of the House
Appropriations subcommittee that oversees veterans and housing
funds. ''But don't let them take it out of veterans' medical
care.''
</P>
<P>
   --Stop the government from forcing automakers to produce more
fuel-efficient vehicles. The auto industry has contributed $2.8
million to congressional candidates, almost three-fourths to
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ''It makes a lot more sense to let the marketplace determine the
kind of vehicles consumers want and not a government mandate,''
said the GOP sponsor, Rep. Joe Knollenberg, who is from the Big
Three automakers' home state of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   --Restrict federal efforts to limit waste produced at gold and
copper mines. The mining industry has given $484,713 to GOP
candidates, more than three times the $140,965 contributed to
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say that in some cases Republicans are simply undoing
help the Clinton administration gave to its biggest donors, such as
the Labor Department's repetitive stress injury rules that were
pushed by labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's clear they want to get it out while Clinton is still
president,'' said Dan Danner, a National Federation of Independent
Business vice president. ''If George W. Bush is elected, this will
quickly die on the vine.''
</P>
<P>
   Danner's group has given $274,600 of its $283,100 in political
action committee contributions to Republicans. Labor PACs have
contributed $17.8 million to Democrats and just $1.9 million to
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans say the special provisions offer them
bargaining chips for negotiations with the administration.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the end of the day, there are some things that are given
up,'' said Rep. Tom Davis of Virginia, chairman of the National
Republican Congressional Committee. ''The more things you have in,
the more you can give up in exchange.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: House Appropriations Committee:
http://www.house.gov/appropriations
</P>
<P>
   Senate Appropriations Committee:
http://appropriations.senate.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
