<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Hard-Liners Launch Crackdown  </HEADLINE>
By ALI AKBAR DAREINI
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- Iranian hard-liners are expanding a
crackdown on the pro-democracy movement to include student
activists, a board member of Iran's largest student organization
said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Five members of the student group Office for Fostering Unity
have been summoned by courts since Wednesday and released only
after signing ''pledges not to take part in protest rallies and
demonstrations,'' Akbar Atri, one of seven members of the group's
board of trustees, told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Liberal newspapers and university students have strongly
supported President Mohammad Khatami's efforts to loosen social
controls in place since the 1979 Islamic revolution installed
clerical rule in Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-liners -- who still control the judiciary -- began fighting
back in April by banning nearly every publication that supported
the presidential reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ''After closing down almost all pro-reform newspapers, the
judiciary has now concentrated on student groups in its crackdown
on the popular reform program,'' Atri said. ''We are ready to pay
the price for our activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Atri described the forced pledges, newspaper closures and recent
detentions as ''part of a plan to frighten the public opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   February elections gave reformists their first -- and
overwhelming -- majority in Iran's parliament, a clear sign of the
swelling public support for reform-minded politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, students demonstrated at Tehran University against
hard-liners who were seen to be trying to manipulate the
long-delayed results of the legislative polls.
</P>
<P>
   Following the protests, former President Hashemi Rafsanjani
forfeited his seat. A change in results had given Rafsanjani, who
is more closely aligned with hard-liners, a far better showing in
the polls than the initial vote count.
</P>
<P>
   Atri also said he was summoned Thursday to the press court, and
that he was charged with ''spreading lies and disturbing public
opinion'' in his speeches at student gatherings.'' No trial date
has been set.
</P>
</TEXT>
