<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Veterans getting diplomas, thanks to new law  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LEDYARD, Conn. (AP) - Colleen Fenn and Charles Connerton are
generations apart.
</P>
<P>
   Fenn is a 13-year-old student at Ledyard Middle School
completing the seventh grade. Connerton is a 76-year-old retiree
who lives in East Lyme. They've never met; never once talked.
</P>
<P>
   But next week, Connerton will be the beneficiary of a campaign
by Fenn in support of legislation to grant diplomas to World War II
veterans who left high school to join the service. The measure last
month passed the Legislature unanimously, and was signed into law
by Gov. John G. Rowland.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd like to thank that little girl,'' said Connerton, who left
East Lyme High School in 1944 to serve three years in the Merchant
Marines. ''I didn't know it was someone so young. It feels great.
It brings faith in human nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Fenn wrote 41 letters to legislators, the
governor's office and state agencies seeking to amend the criteria
for receiving a high school diploma in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''My grandfather was kind of embarrassed for not having his,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fenn first learned about Operation Recognition, a national
campaign to win high school diplomas for World War II vets, from a
newspaper article about a similar program enacted in Massachusetts.
She contacted Robert McKeon, the Massachusetts commissioner of
Veteran Services, for information and then began lobbying
legislators.
</P>
<P>
   She testified at a public hearing in favor of the bill when an
amendment was offered that would award only honorary diplomas.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't want it to be honorary,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be. Fenn, and her grandfather, Hudson Pelton Jr., of
Old Saybrook, attended the ceremony when Rowland signed the
legislation into law.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's going to help a lot of veterans,'' Pelton said.
''It was embarrassing when the question came up. You let it quietly
slide by. I think it means a lot to a lot of veterans, not just
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Connerton and at least seven World War II vets will receive
their diplomas at the East Lyme High School graduation Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Another 10 veterans are scheduled to receive diplomas at the
Milford High School graduation Wednesday. In Berlin, arrangements
are being made for a special ceremony later this year, which could
be attended by as many as 20 World War II vets.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300,000 Connecticut men and women served in World War
II. No one knows exactly how many are eligible to receive high
school diplomas under the new law.
</P>
<P>
   Several school districts have enthusiastically embraced the
idea. Milford began planning to include World War II vets in next
week's graduation exercises months before the bill was passed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We called senior centers and convalescent homes asking for
people to come forward,'' Superintendent Mary Jo Kramer said.
</P>
<P>
   Some question whether simply giving out the diplomas weakens
their significance.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's a tremendous opportunity for our community,''
East Lyme High School Principal Gerald Mistretta said. ''It's a
chance to recognize these men who left high school at age 16, 17,
to go and defend our country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
