<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Great Lakes shipping industry hurting from drop in water levels  </HEADLINE>
By PETER WOODALL
The Buffalo News
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Giant freighters carrying coal, grain and
iron ore floated easily across the Great Lakes only three years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ships were filled to capacity without worry about scraping lake
bottoms. Water levels then were among the highest they had been in
the last century.
</P>
<P>
   No longer. Water levels on four of the five Great Lakes have
dropped between one and three feet in just two years, forcing ships
to lighten loads and cutting profit margins at a time when the
industry is already pinched by high fuel costs.
</P>
<P>
   The ''Indiana Harbor,'' a freighter owned by Williamsville's
American Steamship Co. is currently carrying only 55,000 tons of
iron pellets, instead of the 60,000 tons it tows under normal
conditions. That hurts when you multiply by the 45 trips the ship
will take this year, said Michael Scheidt, American Steamship's
senior vice president.
</P>
<P>
   American Steamship accounts for about 25 percent of the dry bulk
cargo shipped in the Great Lakes by American companies. Its 11-ship
fleet normally carries 25 million tons.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we had more ships available we would use them, but we
don't,'' Scheidt said. There is no way to increase the number of
trips because the shipping season runs only from March to January
on a fixed navigation system, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our members have all suffered losses in cargo carried this
season,'' said George Ryan, president of the Cleveland-based Great
Lakes Carriers' Association. ''Almost every ship is in service and
the overall tonnage is still down from last year.''
</P>
<P>
   The largest ships have to drop 270 tons for every inch of water
in draft, Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some members estimate that they are losing from $25,000 to
$40,000 per trip in revenue,'' Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   The situation isn't as bad as it might have been. ''Because we
had a mild winter, ships were able to begin moving coal in March.
It helped keep the flow of cargo to the customers moving,'' Ryan
said. ''We can only hope we have a mild winter so we can continue
carrying as late in January as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   But a mild winter is a double-edged sword. Less snow fall means
less spring runoff to fill the lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Snowfall above Lake Superior this winter was so minimal - only
about an inch of water - that it could be called a drought,
according to Roger Gauthier, a U.S. Army Corps of Engineers
hydrologist. ''Snowfall was almost nonexistent for half of the
watershed. That is so unusual,'' he said. ''That is why we say low
water levels will continue through this summer and likely be below
average next year.''
</P>
<P>
   The exception is Lake Ontario - the only one of the five Great
Lakes which has a water level higher than the June average.
</P>
<P>
   Last August Lake Ontario's level stood at 7 inches below
average, posing problems for recreational cruisers but not
affecting commercial shipping.
</P>
<P>
   Lake St. Clair, south of Lake Huron, measures 11 inches below
average.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest reason for the dropping water level in most of the
lakes is higher temperatures since the El Nino winter of 1997 and
summer of 1998, Gauthier said. There's also been very little ice
cover on the Great Lakes, resulting in increased evaporation. All
has added up to the quickest decline in the 150 years since Great
Lakes water levels have been recorded. A total of 63 trillion
gallons have been lost among all the Great Lakes since 1997,
Gauthier said.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how a prolonged drop in water levels would affect
shipping.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't intend to suffer through,'' said Scheidt. American
Steamship will try to recoup revenues by increasing freight rates,
he said. If low water levels continue, surcharges may have to be
levied, much as higher gasoline prices have already been passed
along to consumers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those consumers include the construction industry that buys
stone and cement. Utilities like Niagara Mohawk and other power
producers get coal from Great Lakes shipping.
</P>
<P>
   A prolonged drop in water levels wouldn't be unprecedented,
Gauthier said. ''We have seen Lake Erie lower than we are today,
about six or seven times since we've been recording water levels,
so this is by no means a near record low on the lakes. The lake
level on Lake Erie has been lower than it is today for almost 45
years (in a row). So in many respects, Lake Erie may be returning
to the elevation in normally has been at.''
</P>
<P>
   That's no consolation to Ryan. He's asked Congress to study
dredging channels and ports. Failing that, he says that all the
industry can do is work hard and pray for rain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
