<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> America's favorite orphan gets a makeover and a new creative team.  </HEADLINE>
By JUDIE GLAVE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Gone are the little red dress and the unruly mop
of curls. With her platform sneakers, blue jeans and slicked-back
hair, Little Orphan Annie is now, in the lexicon of her 11-year-old
modern peers - mad sick.
</P>
<P>
   Translation for those who don't speak tween: Leapin' Lizards!
America's favorite orphan has gotten a makeover and is suddenly
cool.
</P>
<P>
   Her new do and duds were shown off for the first time last week
when artist Andrew Pepoy and writer Jay Maeder officially took over
the strip from longtime ''Annie'' cartoonist Leonard Starr, who
retired in February. The strip was in reruns until last week.
</P>
<P>
   Pepoy, a free-lance cartoonist who has drawn characters for
Marvel (Mutant X), DC (Sonic the Hedgehog and Scooby-Doo) and
Archie comics, said both he and Tribune Media Services, the
Chicago-based company that syndicates the 75-year-old strip,
thought Annie looked dated next to her new companion, the sexy and
edgy Hispanic aviator Amelia Santiago. So a few pencil strokes
later, out went Annie's tired old red dress, black Maryjanes and
ankle socks; in came jeans, a red T-shirt and platform sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   Her hair is different, too. But not drastically so, says Pepoy.
</P>
<P>
   The artist imagines Annie, like many 11-year-olds, standing
daily at the bathroom mirror with gobs of gel in her hand, slicking
back her mane of unruly red curls. The result is a sleeker looking
hairdo, complete with two barrettes (non-matching, of course.)
</P>
<P>
   But fans of America's favorite blank-eyed youngster - yes, she's
still pupil-less - shouldn't worry. Underneath, Annie hasn't
changed.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there's some kind of feeling out there that Little Orphan
Annie is now a typical 11-year-old who goes to rock concerts and
has pictures of 'N Sync on her wall, no, this is not happening,''
said writer Maeder. ''In fact, if you ask me what kind of music
she'd listen to, I'd say Tommy Dorsey.''
</P>
<P>
   The 53-year-old Maeder, a journalist for the Daily News and a
comic historian, doesn't understand the fuss about Annie's updated
look.
</P>
<P>
   ''I haven't changed her fundamental character in any way. Anyone
who ever loved Little Orphan Annie will not look at this and say
this is a totally different person.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he said, she's worn jeans before. Starr drew Annie in
jeans many times, but readers tend to associate her with the little
red dress with white cuffs.
</P>
<P>
   Maeder says he has no plans to turn Annie or any other character
into modern day valley girls. She'll still exclaim, ''Leapin'
Lizards,'' and Sandy will still say, ''Arf,'' Maeder says.
</P>
<P>
   The intent, says Pepoy, is to make her look ''more like a real
11-year-old ... without straying too far from the Annie everyone
loved.'' He said reaction so far has been positive.
</P>
<P>
   The strip, created by Harold Gray, first appeared in the Daily
News, Aug. 5, 1924. Annie is said to have been modeled after silent
screen star Mary Pickford. During Gray's four-decade reign - he
died in 1968 - Annie and her millionaire guardian Daddy Warbucks
battled everything from big government during the Depression to
Communism in the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Starr took over the strip in 1979 - after interest in it was
revived by the Broadway musical ''Annie.''
</P>
<P>
   In the updated version, Even Warbucks has a new, more casual
look. He has lost his perennial penguin suit and will be seen in
stylish, tie-less suits, sweaters and (Yikes!) even shorts.
</P>
<P>
   Annie will also experiment with fashion, wearing her hair in a
ponytail occasionally and donning Capri pants. But don't expect her
in a halter top. ''We don't want her to be too trendy,'' says
Pepoy, whose wife, Chris, helps him stay up to date on preteen
styles.
</P>
<P>
   As for the story line, Maeder says Warbucks' paid assassins,
Punjab and the Asp, are out, as is Warbucks' high-tech research
laboratory, which has fallen into legal difficulty after a toxic
spill.
</P>
<P>
   Warbucks will soon withdraw for a while, and the action will
center on pilot Santiago and Annie, who will act as her co-pilot
for encounters with lost tribes, underwater cities, train wrecks
and mountain bandits.
</P>
<P>
   And what will become of Sandy, Annie's shaggy companion?
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry loyal readers. ''The dog never goes away,'' says
Maeder. ''He's like Old Faithful himself. He'll be right there with
them during their adventures around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.annie75.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-10-00 1339 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
