<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man arrested for selling stun guns  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - A merchant has been arrested for selling
electronic stun guns out of his store in Flushing.
</P>
<P>
   Jian Ping-Li was arrested Friday at his Ash Avenue store,
Kingsland International, after police confiscated 21 stun guns, 17
air pistols, seven air rifles, a taser and other illegal weapons,
said Queens District Attorney Richard A. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Ping-Li, 47, was charged with the possession and sale of
electronic stun guns and firearms as well as 21 counts of criminal
possession of a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Police were tipped off after they found a store receipt on a man
charged in a June 4th stun gun attack of a woman during an argument
at the Queens Plaza subway stop, Brown said in a statement released
Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
