<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.: Syria To Stay in Peace Search  </HEADLINE>
By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHFIELD, Minn. (AP) -- President Clinton expressed condolences
today to Syrian President Hafez Assad's family and said he expects
to continue working with Syria's leaders toward a comprehensive
Middle East peace.
</P>
<P>
   The president was told of reports of Assad's death while Clinton
flew on Air Force One to Minnesota, where he gave the commencement
speech at Carleton College. An aide handed Clinton a note
confirming the death as Clinton sat on the dais before delivering
the speech. He did not mention the Assad's death in his brief talk.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement issued after the address, Clinton said:
''Over the past seven years, I have met him many times and gotten
to know him very well. We had our differences, but I always
respected him.
</P>
<P>
   ''Since the Madrid Conference, he made a strategic choice for
peace and we worked together to achieve that goal. Throughout my
contacts with him, including our last meeting, he made clear
Syria's continued commitment to the path of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   That 1991 peace conference in Spain, sponsored by the United
States and Russia, brought together Israel, the Palestinians, Syria
and other major Middle East parties.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first such all-encompassing gathering and led to
other meetings and a general relaxation of tensions between the
Israelis and their Arab neighbors, although negotiations between
Israel and Syria have been difficult to sustain.
</P>
<P>
   ''We look forward to working with Syria to achieve the goal of a
comprehensive peace,'' Clinton said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in Minneapolis, Clinton said it was too early to say what
impact Assad's death would have on the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be a period of sorting out and the Syrian people
will make some decisions and then we'll see what happens,'' Clinton
said. ''But you know, we've been at this for years because of the
decision he made to go back to negotiations and to try to move away
from conflict. and it's certainly a path I hope the country will
stay on.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright also expressed her
condolences and said that ''in all our talks he remained
committed'' to peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ''We strongly believe that was the right choice and we expect
that Syria will continue on the path of peace,'' she said in a
statement issued in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Albright met with Syria's foreign minister in
Cairo, Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   Syria showed interest in reopening peace talks with Israel, but
Farouk al-Sharaa did not signal any shift in his country's
territorial demands. Assad has steadfastly demanded return from
Israel of all the Golan Heights, a border plateau that Israel took
in the 1967 Six-Day War.
</P>
<P>
   ''I did not get any indication of a change,'' Albright said of
her meeting with al-Sharaa. She also said that after talks this
coming week in the Washington area between senior Israeli and
Palestinian negotiators, she will decide whether to return to the
region.
</P>
<P>
   Syria's constitution says the vice president succeeds to the
presidency, but the process is expected to be less clear-cut in
practice and could take some time to clarify itself.
</P>
<P>
   A senior State Department official said al-Sharaa told Albright
his government would like to remain in touch.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has offered to return the Golan. But Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak balked at Syria's demand for a sliver of land
along the shores of the Sea of Galilee, the source of about 40
percent of Israel's water.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was unable to change Assad's mind when he renewed the
Israeli offer at a March meeting with Assad in Geneva.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
