<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Statement on Assad's Death  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   President Clinton's statements Saturday on the death
of Syrian
President Hafez Assad:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Written statement issued in Northfield, Minn., where Clinton
gave the commencement address at Carleton College:
</P>
<P>
   ''I am saddened by the news of President Assad's death and want
to offer my condolences to his family and to the Syrian people.
</P>
<P>
   ''Over the past seven years, I have met him many times and
gotten to know him very well. We had our differences, but I always
respected him. Since the Madrid Conference (in 1991), he made a
strategic choice for peace and we worked together to achieve that
goal. Throughout my contacts with him, including our last meeting
(in Geneva in March), he made clear Syria's continued commitment to
the path of peace.
</P>
<P>
   ''We look forward to working with Syria to achieve the goal of a
comprehensive peace.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Statement Clinton gave later at the Minneapolis airport:
</P>
<P>
   ''As you know, I received word not very long ago of President
Assad's death in Syria today. I was very saddened by it, and I want
to offer condolences to his son, his family and the people of
Syria.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know, over the last seven years, I had the occasion to
meet with President Assad many times, and I believe I got to know
him well. And while we had our disagreements, I always respected
him because I felt he was open and straightforward with me and
because I felt he meant it when he said he had made a strategic
choice for peace.
</P>
<P>
   ''I regret that that peace was not achieved in his lifetime, and
I hope that it can still be achieved in no small measure because of
the commitment that he made.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think today rather than speculate about the future it would
be best for all of us just to extend our condolences and our best
thoughts to the family and the people of Syria.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how Assad's death would affect the peace process, he said:
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's premature to say. There will be a period of
mourning in Syria. There will be a period of sorting out, and the
Syrian people will make some decisions. And then we'll see what
happens.
</P>
<P>
   ''But you know, we've been at this for years because of the
decision he made to go back to negotiations and to try to move away
from conflict. And it's certainly a path I hope the country will
stay on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
