<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Accused rabbi deals with pain of wife's murder  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CHERRY HILL, N.J. (AP) - His jaw clenches whenever Rabbi Fred J.
Neulander is asked about the 1994 murder of his wife Carol, a
brutal bludgeoning authorities say he arranged so he could continue
an affair with a congregant.
</P>
<P>
   Alone in the home here where they raised a daughter and two
sons, the rabbi tells the story he has stuck to ever since: Police
and prosecutors have framed him. Two men who claim he offered them
$30,000 to kill her are lying. Robbers killed his wife of 29 years,
whom he loved and misses ''very much.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's too painful, emotionally painful'' to discuss her, the
58-year-old Neulander told The Philadelphia Inquirer in its Sunday
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander, a seventh-generation rabbi, is charged with
accomplice murder and conspiracy to commit murder. He could become
the first New Jersey clergyman to face the death penalty when he is
eventually tried. Free on $400,000 bail, he admits only to
committing adultery, but knows he is under a cloud of suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have done some things I am not proud of,'' he said in
October after a court hearing in Camden. ''But I have not done all
the things they have said I have done.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities allege Neulander planned the murder because
Philadelphia radio host Elaine Soncini, with whom he had been
having an affair, was threatening to end it if he didn't leave his
wife. Neulander was worried a divorce would cost him his job as
senior rabbi at Congregation M'kor Shalom, the Cherry Hill
synagogue he and Carol had founded in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, fallout from the murder did, including the disclosure
that Neulander had had an affair with another congregant. When the
board of the 900-family synagogue asked him to resign in February
1995, Neulander complied, saying, ''it was the right thing for me
and the congregation.''
</P>
<P>
   After a 5 1/2-year investigation, two men came forward to say
they had carried out the murder: Len Jenoff, 54, of Collingswood
and Paul Michael Daniels, 27, of Pennsauken. Both have pleaded
guilty to aggravated manslaughter charges in the past 10 days,
admitting they struck Carol Neulander several times with a pipe;
Jenoff, who was once counseled by the rabbi, has promised to
testify against him.
</P>
<P>
   At his lawyers' instruction, Neulander refused to discuss the
murder or charges against him during a half-dozen meetings since
January with Inquirer reporter Barbara Boyer; he only allowed her
to take notes at the final two sessions, after Jenoff and Daniels
were arrested. During one meeting, the rabbi and reporter sat on
his living room floor - on new carpet that had replaced the
bloodied one where Carol Neulander died.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to integrate death into your life,'' Neulander said.
''There are moments of happiness, laughter and moments of sadness.
But there's never closure. How can there be closure for someone who
was such a large part of my life?''
</P>
<P>
   That changed the night of Nov. 1, 1994, when Neulander returned
home from the synagogue. The rabbi found his wife beaten to death
on the living room floor and called 911.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's middle child, Matthew, now 27, had been working as
an emergency medical technician that night and rushed home when he
heard the call; his father had him kept outside so Matthew wouldn't
see the body.
</P>
<P>
   In initial interviews with police, Soncini and Neulander both
denied they were having an affair, but she later told authorities
and a grand jury that she and Neulander were in love.
</P>
<P>
   ''I truly regret the things I have done, the people I have hurt
and those I have disappointed,'' Neulander said during one of a
half-dozen interviews with Boyer since January. ''That's something
I'm going to have to live with.''
</P>
<P>
   Neulander said he enjoys his new job writing curricula for
educational field trips. He also tutors a friend's children and, on
request, officiates at funerals and weddings.
</P>
<P>
   He is writing a book about his experiences as a rabbi - and
mulling another one about his life.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to reinvent yourself,'' he said. ''It's either that
or suicide or staying under the covers all day.''
</P>
<P>
   The rabbi has resisted pressure to move out of the house from
his children: Matthew, Rebecca, 29, and Ben, 24.
</P>
<P>
   There's ''a lot of beautiful memories in this house. There's
happiness, birthdays, bat mitzvahs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   All three children called him one evening as he watched a
favorite television program in the family room, where a picture of
Carol and the rest of the family is displayed.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the last conversation, with Ben, Neulander said,
''I love you, too.''
</P>
<P>
   After years of counseling and comforting congregants, Neulander
said there still are no words to explain why innocent people must
suffer.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is during my private moments that I allow myself to break
down. In fact, I need to break down, for my heart crumbles also,''
Neulander said. ''I, too, raise my fist against heaven and I demand
answers, just like everyone else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-10-00 1418 </TRAILER>
