<DOCNO> APW20000610.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Observers To Carry On  </HEADLINE>
By ANGUS SHAW
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- The withdrawal of U.N. observers from
Zimbabwe will not affect the role of other foreign observers who
are in the southern African nation to make sure that upcoming
parliamentary elections are free and fair, officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations said Friday that President Robert Mugabe had
reneged on an agreement to permit the world body's observers to
coordinate all foreign observer missions and that there was not
enough time for the United Nations to renegotiate its role there.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we are not doing the coordination, there is no point in us
being there,'' U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said in New York.
</P>
<P>
   However, observers from the Commonwealth of former British
territories, the European Union and the 14-nation Southern Africa
Development Community will remain in place to monitor the June
24-25 poll.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are here to see whether conditions exist for a free
expression of will by electors,'' said Gen. Abdulsalami Abubakar of
Nigeria, chairman of the 44-member Commonwealth group.
</P>
<P>
   Sanna Jonson, a spokeswoman for the 210-member EU observer
group, said the U.N. pullout was regrettable but ''we will carry
on.''
</P>
<P>
   The main opposition party in Zimbabwe, the Movement for
Democratic Change, criticized the decision by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan to withdraw U.N. observers.
</P>
<P>
   ''For any electoral process to receive the stamp of moral
authority from the international community, it needs recognition
from the United Nations,'' said party leader Morgan Tsvangirai.
</P>
<P>
   Abubakar said the presence of international observers and about
14,000 domestic election monitors from church, human rights and
civic groups at 4,000 polling stations across the country aimed to
ensure voters' security and give them confidence.
</P>
<P>
   The human rights group Amnesty International said Thursday it
doubted that free and fair elections were possible because of a
wave of land takeovers spearheaded by veterans of the war that led
to independence from white minority rule in 1980. The government
has ignored constitutional ownership rights and laws protecting
private property during the often-violent occupations of more than
1,400 white-owned farms that began in February.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the government announced the state would
immediately begin seizing 804 mostly white-owned farms.
</P>
<P>
   More than 5,000 cases of political violence have been reported
in Zimbabwe since February, when a government-sponsored referendum
on a new constitution was defeated. At least 30 people, mainly
opposition supporters, have been killed.
</P>
<P>
   The election poses the biggest challenge to Mugabe since he led
the nation to independence from Britain in 1980. Opponents say his
support for the farm occupations is a ploy to increase his vote in
the poll.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-10-00 1421 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000610.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Residents who repaired flood-damaged homes may lose them to redevelopment </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOUND BROOK, N.J. (AP) - Sophie Dachnowski is 80 now. Her
husband of 54 years died last year, a few months before last
September's flood filled their home with water.
</P>
<P>
   ''They had to come get me out,'' Dachnowski said, pointing to a
window high on the second floor.
</P>
<P>
   Dachnowski spent $30,000 to repair the insides of her sturdy
white house, where she spends afternoons sitting on the porch,
talking to neighbors in the breeze. She was born in it, and lived
there with her parents and three siblings, who all have died. Her
only child died in 1981. Still, she has her house.
</P>
<P>
   But under a plan approved this week by the borough council,
Dachnowski's home may be condemned by the city and given over to a
developer with plans to create a new business district for the
flood-ravaged town.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was born here and where am I going to go now?'' said
Dachnowski, dabbing tears from her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   About 600 properties on a 150-acre tract of land are vulnerable
to condemnation a few years down the road, under a contract
approved this week with The Advance Group of Bedminster. The
developer and the town have visions of a corporate village
surrounding expanded train service, a hotel-conference center and
perhaps a satellite campus to turn around the fortunes of Somerset
County's oldest town after Hurricane Floyd-related flooding turned
its streets into a brown river.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need upkeep here. We need to spruce up the town,'' said
Mayor Frank Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   Borough administrator Thomas Brodbeck says the town needs
''ratables right now, and I don't really care what kind.''
</P>
<P>
   The 9,000-resident town's property values have dropped $45
million since the flood, and Ryan says that without new
development, the tax rate will skyrocket for residents.
</P>
<P>
   So the borough passed a redevelopment plan earlier this year
that gives it the right to use the power of eminent domain to
condemn houses to make way for development. The contract with
Advance allows the developer to ask Bound Brook to take possession
of the properties it is unable to buy.
</P>
<P>
   For residents who suffered through the worst flood in the town's
history, the irony is acute. After spending thousands to rebuild
the homes the water took away, they might have to leave anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ''All our hard work put in here,'' said Jenny Jeskie, sitting in
a living room that has been rebuilt from top to bottom since the
flood. ''They better not come in and rip it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeskie and her husband, Stanley, spent 45 years in the modest,
two-story brown house, raising six children. They spent more than
$30,000 to recreate their bedroom, living room, kitchen and
bathroom, and got hand-me-down replacement furniture from family.
</P>
<P>
   ''You put all your years in here,'' Jenny Jeskie said.
''Forty-five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Relax, say Ryan and other borough officials. No one may lose
their home. The Advance Group hasn't submitted a development
proposal yet for the land, and the proposal might not require the
removal of homes.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not the time to yell and scream,'' said Phyllis
Pournaras, a restaurant owner who sits on a redevelopment advisory
committee. She said two property owners in the redevelopment area
have 23 acres between them and want to sell. The land might be
enough for Advance, she said.
</P>
<P>
   And homeowners would receive a fair price for their property and
be relocated, whether their homes are condemned or not, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, many believe that the developer's interest in
the town is spurring the beginning of a long-overdue flood control
project that the low-lying city on the Raritan River desperately
needs. In September, construction will begin on a 15- to 17-foot
berm along one of the town's borders and a bridge that crosses
Green Brook will be raised.
</P>
<P>
   The contract with Advance has the developer promising to develop
10 percent of the land every year from the time the flood control
project is finished in 2003 or 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the flood, Bound Brook had begun redevelopment plans
to revitalize a business district that has had to compete with the
Bridgewater shopping mall and strip malls along Route 22.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's only restaurants'' along the town's Main Street, said
Dachnowski. Years ago, the streets were lined with drug stores,
clothing stores and other shops, residents say.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, who has lived here for 68 of his 69 years and was not
flooded out last year, acknowledged that some people may have to
lose their homes for the greater good of the town.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've got to look to the future,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But residents, who filed a lawsuit earlier this year to block
the redevelopment plan, say their lives in Bound Brook are the only
ones they've known. The residential area outlined for redevelopment
has many of the town's oldest inhabitants, many coming from Polish,
Italian and German immigrant families.
</P>
<P>
   Months ago, the streets of these neighborhoods were strewn with
mud, garbage, furniture and chunks of people's homes. Now the
streets are clean, many homes are freshly painted and plants are
growing outside Dachnowski's one and only home.
</P>
<P>
   She said she didn't want to live anywhere else. When told that
homes wouldn't be vulnerable to condemnation for another three or
four years, she shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll be dead by then.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
