<DOCNO> APW20000610.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corzine ads confuse Pennsylvanians, overshadow their Senate race  </HEADLINE>
By CLAUDE R. MARX
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - No presidential spouse is in the race and no
one spent millions of dollars of his own money to win the party
nomination. So it is no surprise that Pennsylvania's U.S. Senate
race has dropped off the radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Democratic nominee, U.S. Rep. Ron Klink.
</P>
<P>
   Some voters in the Philadelphia area told Klink's staff they
could not help him because they are committed to Jon Corzine.
</P>
<P>
   Those voters have it half right.
</P>
<P>
   The former Goldman Sachs chairman saturated the Philadelphia
television market while spending $33 million, mostly from his own
pocket, to win the Democratic senate nomination in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Pennsylvania Democrats, Klink's financial
situation is worlds away from Corzine's.
</P>
<P>
   Klink, a television newscaster turned four-term congressman from
suburban Pittsburgh, had to take a second mortgage on his house to
finance his primary win. He was so cash-strapped that he did no
advertising on Philadelphia television.
</P>
<P>
   Through March 31, Klink raised $1.5 million and had only
$119,162.17 in the bank. Klink's funds include $300,000 he lent his
campaign by putting a second mortgage on his house.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, U.S. Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa., had raised $6
million through the end of March and had $3.7 million in the bank.
He benefits from the Corzine-Klink confusion. Several people have
told Pennsylvania's junior senator they want to help him because
they resent that Corzine is trying to buy a Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   The financial gap, the Klink-Corzine mix-up, and Santorum's
efforts to move to the center on a range of issues, have prompted
many so-called experts to declare the election a done deal. Neither
major national party ranks the race among its top priorities.
</P>
<P>
   But before declaring Santorum's re-election a fait accompli, one
would do well to remember the words of the sage philosopher and New
York Yankee great Yogi Berra: ''It ain't over till it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   For starters, most voters are more concerned about where they
are going on their summer vacation than whom they will support in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Klink has made only a handful of appearances since winning
the April 4 primary. He has spent most of his time getting ready
for the fall by engaging in that time-honored political pastime,
''dialing for dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   If Klink's efforts to rebuild his bank account are successful,
he and Santorum will so saturate the airwaves in the fall that
voters will think they have known both of them for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are also counting on what they call the public's
strong dislike of Santorum to help turn the tide.
</P>
<P>
   Former state Labor Secretary Tom Foley, who finished third in
the six-candidate Democratic senate primary, said Santorum is
extremely polarizing.
</P>
<P>
   ''When he annoys people, he doesn't just annoy them, he annoys
their whole family. That's all to the good for Klink,'' Foley said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, most voters have not formed a strong opinion of
Klink, who has never run a statewide race. In Pittsburgh, he is
remembered as an amiable talking head who had a
moderate-conservative record in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   That record, which includes strong opposition to both gun
control and abortion rights, will make it hard for Santorum to
portray Klink as a liberal.
</P>
<P>
   That's why it is risky at best to predict in June what will
happen in November.
</P>
<P>
   -
</P>
<P>
   Claude R. Marx covers Pennsylvania issues in Washington for The
Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-10-00 1441 </TRAILER>
