<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Plans To Curb Extremists  </HEADLINE>
By ZAHID HUSSAIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Pakistan, hard pressed by the United
States to curb Islamic militants, plans to take gradual action
against extremist groups involved in religious killings and
regulate Islamic schools accused of fanning sectarian violence.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are doing everything to contain sectarian organizations and
also those groups which are suspected of terrorism,'' Interior
Minister Moinuddin Haider told The Associated Press on Saturday.
''We have to clean our country and bring our house in order.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, a U.S. Congressional advisory commission
asked Washington to designate Pakistan and Greece as nations ''not
cooperating fully'' with anti-terrorism efforts. Washington has
also asked Islamabad to ban extremist religious groups, including
Harakat-ul-Mujahedeen, which was declared a terrorist organization
by the United States two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of people have been killed throughout Pakistan in recent
months in tit-for-tat killings between rival Sunni Muslim and
Shiite Muslim extremists groups. Sunni Muslims, who are a majority
in Pakistan, live peacefully with their Shiite Muslim brethren. But
small extremist groups of both sects regularly clash.
</P>
<P>
   Haider, a retired general, said that the 8-month-old
military-led government has already taken several tough steps to
curb religious violence, including a ban on carrying weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ''These steps are being taken not to please the outside world,
but in the larger national interest. We want to remove the
impression that we are a soft state,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The government also plans to regulate an estimated 60,000
religious schools, he said. The government will introduce modern
education of science, mathematics and computers in their
curriculum, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has asked Pakistan to help persuade Afghanistan's
Taliban rulers to hand over Osama bin Laden, who is accused of
masterminding the deadly bombings of U.S. embassies in Africa in
1998. Washington says he runs an international terrorist network
from Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   But Pakistan, one of only three countries to recognize the
Taliban government, says its influence on the Taliban is limited.
</P>
<P>
   The Afghan Taliban have closed two militant training camps in
their war-battered country at Pakistan's request, Haider said.
Pakistani extremists groups' members received military training in
those camps. But he gave no details.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan has also started expelling foreign Muslim nationals who
came to the region fight the former Soviet Union during its
occupation of Afghanistan in 1980s, Haider said.
</P>
<P>
   Islamabad also plans to curb the free flow of people across the
border that separates Afghanistan and Pakistan by gradually
introducing travel restrictions, Haider said.
</P>
<P>
   There are no quick solutions to the problem of militancy and
terrorism, he said. ''We have to move gradually and reinforce the
authority of the law for the country's good,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-10-00 1445 </TRAILER>
