<HEADLINE> U.N. Inspects Israel-Lebanon Border  </HEADLINE>
By ZEINA KARAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMIYEH, Lebanon (AP) -- A team of United Nations and Lebanese
officials verifying Israel's troop withdrawal from southern Lebanon
Saturday worked slowly along the international border, despite
pressure for a speedy conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   The officials drove out in 10 U.N. vehicles in the morning to
survey the border. They stopped at points off a road near the
border on the Lebanese side and walked to the border fence or drove
along it in four-wheel-drive vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Seven hours later, they had covered only three miles of terrain
beyond the 12 miles surveyed Thursday, the first day of the
verification process of the 140-mile border.
</P>
<P>
   The slow progress pushes back the deployment of U.N.
peacekeepers to the turbulent border region, where armed
anti-Israeli guerrillas have been the only real authority since
Israel pulled out last month. The 4,500-member U.N. Interim Force
in Lebanon is required to secure the border under a Security
Council resolution.
</P>
<P>
   But before that happens, U.N. experts must make sure Israeli
troops are behind the new international border drawn by U.N.
cartographers following the Israeli withdrawal. No work was
conducted Friday because Lebanon objected to some parts of the
border.
</P>
<P>
   The verification process resumed Saturday after the United
Nations agreed to Lebanon's demand to have a U.N. cartographer at
hand. A Russian, Vladimir Bessarabov, was assigned the job.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just here for technical questions if anybody has'' them,
Bessarabov told The Associated Press. But he said he was getting
few clarification requests from the Lebanese army officers who
accompanied the U.N. officials during the inspection of two
positions near the village of Yarin.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan instructed UNIFIL
to complete the verification urgently, within 24 hours, if
possible. Annan is planning a visit to the Middle East beginning
next Thursday, according to diplomatic sources at the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   But a Lebanese member of the verification team shrugged off
Annan's comment, saying accuracy, not speed, is required.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Lebanese protesters hurled stones at the U.N. team
verifying the border on the Israeli side of the fence. But the team
did not stop the verification process, which began simultaneously
on both sides of the border.
</P>
<P>
   The new border, which sliced in half the Arab village of Ghajar,
has angered residents who have threatened to evict peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's withdrawal ended an 18-year occupation of southern
Lebanon and the almost daily battles with Lebanese resistance
guerrillas. The occupation was aimed at protecting northern Israeli
towns from cross-border guerrilla raids.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas, however, have refrained from attacking Israel
since the withdrawal. But Lebanese civilians have frequently
thronged at the border fence and hurled stones at Israeli soldiers
on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   The state-run National News Agency reported that the Lebanese
government plans to form a strike force of 1,000 army and police
troops to maintain security in areas vacated by the Israeli army.
</P>
<P>
   In a Friday night report, the agency said 500 army soldiers will
be drawn from anti-terrorism and anti-espionage units as well as
military police. The rest of the force will be made up of 500
Internal Security policemen and will be under Interior Ministry
command, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-10-00 1446 </TRAILER>
