<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ballot Decides Who Is for Milosevic  </HEADLINE>
By KATARINA KRATOVAC
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The bottom line for municipal
elections in Montenegro's two key cities boils down to one simple
question -- who supports Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and
who does not.
</P>
<P>
   A day before voters go to the polls in the capital Podgorica and
the coastal resort of Herceg Novi to choose municipal officials,
fear of an emotional explosion remained high Saturday in
Montenegro, Serbia's junior partner in the two-state Yugoslav
federation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Divisions are deep in Montenegro where the least spark can
trigger a blood bath,'' said historian Rados Ratkovic. ''Our
biggest danger is our emotional creed.''
</P>
<P>
   The test comes Sunday when voters in the two key cities --
comprising almost a third of Montenegro's 600,000 population -- cast
their ballots. Although local, the elections will measure the
extent of support for Montenegro's pro-Western government under
President Milo Djukanovic, a bitter Milosevic opponent.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the first challenge to Djukanovic's government since
he won 1998 elections.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition comprises hardline Milosevic allies who advocate
Yugoslav patriotism and closer ties with Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegrins -- proud highlanders bound by tradition and tribal
history -- are known for feuds started by less than a difference in
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything is taken far too seriously,'' says Melita Rastoder,
19, a student volunteer in an independent monitoring group, CEMI.
Her generation, she claims, is pressured by the elderly and parents
for whom politics is a matter of ''catastrophic importance.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratkovic, a political science professor, estimates that 49
percent of the voters unwaveringly back Djukanovic. The Montenegrin
president has steered a tentative course to independence in
everything but name, falling short of outright secession to avoid a
possible armed conflict with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Ratkovic says the votes of about 30 percent of the electorate
still undecided are needed to solidify Djukanovic's grip on power.
</P>
<P>
   The run-up to the election has been characterized by a heated
campaign by Milosevic's allies.
</P>
<P>
   ''Montenegro's only future is one of togetherness with Serbia,''
says Predrag Bulatovic, the pro-Belgrade camp's candidate for
Podgorica mayor. His group has pushed the ''historic brotherhood''
of Serbs and Montenegrins and has echoed Milosevic's defiance of
the West, which bombed Yugoslavia during NATO's 78-day bombing
campaign last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Montenegrin government claims Milosevic's supporters are
fomenting the divisions, pitting locally stationed federal army
troops loyal to Milosevic against the police, who answer to
Djukanovic.
</P>
<P>
   The two groups have had previous close calls. Last Wednesday, in
the village of Berane, the army positioned a platoon outside the
local police station after the arrest of two soldiers who had
reportedly harassed villagers. The soldiers were later released and
the army withdrew.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
