<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> London Pedestrian Bridge Holds Sway  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BARR
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- London opened its first footbridge across the
Thames River Saturday, a graceful suspension structure designed to
sway in the wind. For some walkers, it turned out to be more like a
thrill ride.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think you need to take your seasickness pills before
crossing,'' said Margaret Vint, 60. ''I wouldn't recommend it if
you are feeling at all tipsy.''
</P>
<P>
   Police restricted access to the Millennium Bridge Saturday
afternoon to give the bridge a chance to settle down, and engineers
checked whether the 1,090-foot suspension bridge was moving more
than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Somerville, 52, who crossed with her 11-year-old daughter,
Rachel, said the bridge was beautiful but ''the walk across was
very hair-raising.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It was like doing the cake walk -- we were looking at each
other asking 'Is it supposed to do this?'''
</P>
<P>
   The engineering firm of Ove Arup and Partners said the bridge
was designed to stand up to gales of 85 mph, with a lateral motion
of no more than about 14 inches at the center. On Saturday, winds
in London were about 11 mph, the Meteorological Office said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was awful this morning when there were hundreds of people
on it,'' said Alison Buckley, 37. ''It's taken me a full hour to
get my balance back.''
</P>
<P>
   The bridge is the heart of a new pedestrian corridor starting
outside the dome of St. Paul's Cathedral and crossing the river to
the Tate Modern art gallery, which recently opened inside a
converted power station. Planners expect it to carry 4 million
people per year.
</P>
<P>
   Before its opening, the Millennium Bridge had been praised for
its innovative design.
</P>
<P>
   An editorial published Saturday in The Guardian newspaper
delighted in the lightness of the span: ''You hover above the water
as if hanging in the basket of a hot-air balloon. And you realize
what a beautiful city London can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Road bridges across the Thames have walkways, but visitors may
find it difficult to find the access. Once on a bridge they have to
contend with the noise and fumes of traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The new Millennium Bridge was a cooperative effort among Foster
and Partners architects, sculptor Sir Anthony Caro and Ove Arup and
Partners. It was the winning entry among 226 entries in a worldwide
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Funding for the $27.3 million project included a grant of $5.2
million from the Bridge House Estates Trust Fund. It traces its
origins to the 11th century when a tax was imposed to help repair
London Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   That wooden bridge was replaced in the 12th century by a stone
structure which not only carried traffic, but was jammed with shops
and houses. Rents from those properties, bridge tolls and tolls
from ships passing under the bridge were collected by the fund,
along with bequests ''to God and the Bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bridge House Estates Trust Fund was tapped for the
construction of Tower Bridge, which was completed in 1894 and was
the last Thames bridge before this one.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On The Net:
</P>
<P>
   Engineers -- http://www.arup.com/MillenniumBridge/
</P>
<P>
   Architects -- http://www.fosterandpartners.com/newsmenu.html
</P>
<P>
   Webcam -- http://www.mbridge.FT.com/
</P>
<P>
   Thames bridges --
http://www.cityoflondon.gov.uk/history/index.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
