<HEADLINE> Italy Mob Boss Recaptured  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPLES, Italy (AP) -- Police have recaptured one of Italy's
most-wanted criminals -- a convicted mob boss who escaped from a
crowded courtroom two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Police stormed a fortified villa outside Naples during the night
and surprised Ferdinando Cesarano as he was eating dinner on the
terrace.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest, announced Saturday, was hailed as a victory in the
long battle against the Neapolitan mob, the Camorra. Interior
Minister Enzo Bianco flew to Naples on Saturday to congratulate the
officers who captured Cesarano.
</P>
<P>
   The head of one of the most powerful Camorra clans, Cesarano
escaped from a courtroom in the southern city of Salerno two years
ago while court was in session.
</P>
<P>
   The escape was stunning. A hole had been cut in the floor of the
high-security cage inside the courtroom where the defendants sat
during their trial. The hole led to a tunnel -- and freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Already serving life sentences for mob-related crimes, Cesarano
was one of dozens of defendants in the trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
