<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavs Mark Bombing Anniversary  </HEADLINE>
By DRAGAN ILIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEKSINAC, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Vowing to prevent further wars in
Yugoslavia, an army general and several officials on Saturday
marked the first anniversary of the end of NATO's 78-day air attack
in this mining town, where Allied bombs killed 19 civilians.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,000 people attended the ceremony -- called ''Memory and
Hope'' -- which is to become an annual event commemorating the day
NATO suspended its bombing campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the crowd, the Yugoslav army's chief of staff, Gen.
Nebojsa Pavkovic, blasted the United States and NATO for their
''cowardly aggression'' in the air raids, and promised his troops
would prevent any further wars in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The army ''is united, firm and combat-ready to prevent any
secessionist scenarios from Yugoslavia,'' he said, referring to
Montenegro, Serbia's pro-Western partner in today's Yugoslavia.
''We will do our utmost to stop the civil war.''
</P>
<P>
   Pavkovic also announced a reorganization of the army, seriously
crippled during the bombing. ''Our armed forces will be reformed
into a smaller, modern and ubiquitous force,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Allies of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic attended the
service, including his wife, Mirjana Markovic, Serbia's Premier
Mirko Marjanovic and Deputy Premier Nikola Sainovic. The state
sponsored several other anniversary ceremonies across the country.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1999 bombing campaign, Aleksinac was hit on seven
different occasions, including an April 5 attack on an apartment
complex that killed 17 civilians.
</P>
<P>
   NATO launched its air war to stop Milosevic's crackdown on armed
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. After more than two months of daily
bombing raids, Milosevic caved in to NATO demands and pulled Serb
troops and police out of the southern Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, a NATO-led peace force entered Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Serbia's largest opposition party, Vuk Draskovic's
Serbian Renewal Movement, announced Saturday it would not
participate in this year's elections unless Milosevic's regime
stopped its crackdown against the opposition, student groups and
independent media.
</P>
<P>
   ''Without the cessation of state terror, violence, lawlessness,
and without the return of all independent media to its rightful
owners, there will be preconditions for democratic elections in
Serbia,'' a party statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Police on Saturday arrested dozens of opposition activists in
several Serbian towns, Beta news agency reported. Ten activists of
the opposition Democratic Party were detained in the southeastern
town of Zajecar, it said.
</P>
<P>
   Though all but two were released after one hour of
interrogation, police beat one activist and harassed a female
lawyer who was seven months pregnant, said Cedomir Jovanovic, of
the Democratic Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
