<HEADLINE> Key Dates in Assad's Life  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A look at key dates in the life of Syrian President Hafez Assad,
who died Saturday at the age of 69.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 6, 1930 -- Hafez Assad born in Qardaha, an Alawite Muslim
village on the west coast of Syria, then ruled by France.
</P>
<P>
   May 15, 1948 -- Syria, independent since 1946, and other Arab
states invade newly declared state of Israel. Arab failure to crush
Jewish state leads to decades of instability in Syria and conflict
in region.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 23, 1966 -- Baath's radical left wing, dominated by minority
Alawites and Druse army officers, overthrows Maj. Gen. Amin Hafez.
Among coup activists is Maj. Gen. Hafez Assad, who is named defense
minister.
</P>
<P>
   June 1967 -- Israel captures Syria's Golan Heights -- a strategic
plateau and the base for Syrian shelling of Israeli villages -- in
Arab-Israeli War.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 13, 1970 -- Assad seizes power in bloodless coup after
Jordan mauls Syrian forces sent to aid Palestinians fighting King
Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   March 12, 1971 -- Parliament elects Assad president for
seven-year term.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 6, 1973 -- Syria and Egypt jointly launch surprise attacks
on Israel to recapture territory lost in 1967. Syria almost regains
Golan, but Israelis rally and push Assad's forces back.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 16, 1976 -- Assad, alarmed by civil war in neighboring
Lebanon, sends forces into Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   March 27, 1979 -- Egypt signs peace with Israel. Assad condemns
move.
</P>
<P>
   June 26, 1980 -- Amid escalating rebellion by Muslim
fundamentalists, Assad narrowly survives assassination in Damascus.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 14, 1981 -- Israel annexes the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Feb.2, 1982 -- Assad sends forces into Hama to crush Muslim
Brotherhood uprising. An estimated 10,000 people killed.
</P>
<P>
   June 1983 -- Assad expels Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat from
Syria in bid to seize control of Palestinian cause. Syrians sponsor
a mutiny by PLO radicals against Arafat in Lebanon, driving him out
of his last stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 12, 1983 -- Assad has heart attack. While he is ill, rivals
flex their muscles, including his younger brother Rifaat.
</P>
<P>
   May 28, 1984 -- Assad banishes Rifaat.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 2, 1990 -- Iraq invades Kuwait. Assad sends 29,000 troops to
join U.S.-led coalition, establishing himself firmly in Western
camp.
</P>
<P>
   July 14, 1991 -- Assad agrees to U.S.-sponsored peace talks with
Israel, attends Madrid Conference in November, 1991.
</P>
<P>
   March 1996 -- On-off peace negotiations end when Israel break off
talks after Syria refuses to condemn series of terror attacks in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   December 1999 -- Israeli-Syrian peace talks resume in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   January 2000 -- Talks postponed indefinitely over Syria
preconditioning progress on Israel's return of Golan Heights.
Israel wants to retain sovereignty over Sea of Galilee at foot of
Golan.
</P>
<P>
   March 26, 2000 -- Assad meets President Clinton in Geneva, but
their talks fail to narrow the gap with Israel to enable peace
talks to resume.
</P>
<P>
   June 10, 2000 -- Assad dies at age 69.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-10-00 1518 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000610.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Speaks at Last Commencement  </HEADLINE>
By DEB RIECHMANN
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHFIELD, Minn. (AP) -- It was President Clinton's last
commencement address, and he offered a sober message Saturday to
graduates of a private liberal arts college where annual costs
exceed $29,000: ''Our country cannot afford to leave any students
behind simply because they can't afford to pay for college.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Over the past 20 years, the cost of college has quadrupled,''
Clinton told 423 graduates of Carleton College, about 40 miles
south of Minneapolis. ''I'll bet there are a lot of parents here
who have taken second mortgages or second jobs to help pay those
tuition bills.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, clad in cap and gown, strode before the crowd of about
6,000 people in this sleepy community whose motto is ''The City of
Cows, Colleges and Contentment.'' He threw his head back and
laughed when he noticed a life-sized cardboard cutout of himself
that someone waved in the audience. During his talk, he joked about
how someone had painted his likeness on a water tower. ''I still
kind of wish you hadn't painted it over,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His mood, however, was dampened by the news of the death of
Syrian President Hafez Assad. As he sat on the dais waiting to
deliver his speech, Clinton was handed a note, confirming Assad's
death on Saturday. But he did not mention the 69-year-old
president's death in his talk.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he focused on his administration's work to make higher
education more accessible.
</P>
<P>
   He touted the administration's Direct Student Loan program,
saying it had lowered the cost of borrowing for students by
allowing them to get loans directly through the government without
a financial institution acting as a middle man. He boasted about
expanding the Pell Grant program and creating the $1,500 HOPE
Scholarship tax credit to make the first two years of college as
universal as high school.
</P>
<P>
   He also called on Congress to approve a measure that would let
families claim a tax deduction worth up to $2,800 for up to $10,000
in college tuition costs.
</P>
<P>
   ''As student aid has increased, so has college attendance, now
to record levels,'' he said. ''Two-thirds of our high school
graduates go straight to college -- that's an all-time high. And for
the first time in history, a majority of young African Americans
are enrolling in higher education.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Rep. Bill Goodling, R-Pa., chairman of the House
Committee on Education and the Workforce, said he was disappointed
that the president would use a commencement speech to advance a
''misguided political agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodling said the Direct Student Loan program, for example, had
many administrative problems the president failed to mention in his
speech. And he said that Congress had not acted on the president's
elementary and secondary school proposals because of their ''big
government, Washington-knows-best mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   This was Clinton's 23rd commencement address since taking office
in 1993, and his third this year. Clinton has already spoken this
year at the U.S. Coast Guard Academy in New London, Conn. and at
Eastern Michigan University in Ypsilanti, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   During his one-day Minnesota visit, Clinton also was to address
a Democratic National Convention luncheon and attend a Soul Asylum
rock concert and Democratic Party fund-raiser, both in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   In his weekly radio address on Saturday, Clinton announced new
regulations by the Labor Department that would allow states to
provide paid leave after the birth or adoption of a child. He also
announced a new regulation, effective June 20, that allows federal
employees to use up to 12 weeks of sick leave to care for a
seriously ill family member.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think no American should ever have to choose between the job
they need and the parent or child they love,'' Clinton said. ''The
actions we take today will help to ensure that they won't have to
make that choice.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republican Conference Chairman J.C. Watts of Oklahoma
complained that the new regulations will ''shred the safety net for
the unemployed'' by raiding unemployment insurance trust funds.
''This is an ill-conceived plan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.carleton.edu/commencement2000/index.html
</P>
<P>
   http:// www.whitehouse.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-10-00 1518 </TRAILER>
