<HEADLINE> Ebert Lauds School on Siskel Center  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- The decision by the The School of the Art
Institute of Chicago to rename its film center after the late film
critic Gene Siskel has received two thumbs up from Roger Ebert, his
former partner.
</P>
<P>
   Ebert, who is leading a $5 million campaign to pay for new
facilities at the center, says Siskel also would have given the
decision rave reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ''Gene Siskel loved movies and he loved the Film Center of the
School of the Art Institute,'' Ebert said. ''A cinematheque in the
heart of the Loop would have had his enthusiastic support.''
</P>
<P>
   The center will include two theaters equipped with Dolby
surround sound, custom-designed lighting and teleconferencing
capabilities. It also will have a restaurant, a lobby gallery and a
concession stand.
</P>
<P>
   Siskel died last year at age 53 from complications following
surgery to remove a growth from his brain in May.
</P>
<P>
   The Film Center, founded in 1972, presents premieres of new
American and foreign films, revivals of classics, retrospectives
and festivals.
</P>
</TEXT>
