<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fighting Rages on in Congo  </HEADLINE>
By HRVOJE HRANJSKI
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISANGANI, Congo (AP) -- Ugandan and Rwandan troops fought street
battles and traded artillery rounds in this Congo River port on
Saturday, as U.N. military observers tried to secure yet another
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   Ugandan forces requested a truce starting Saturday evening,
apparently so their troops could withdraw across the Tshopo River
Bridge north of Kisangani, where they have tried for six days
unsuccessfully to mount a siege.
</P>
<P>
   Rwandan troops controlled most of the port, including two
airports and the city center. Rwandan army officials said they had
pushed Ugandan units away from the city's Tshopo district and
toward the bridge. The claim could not be confirmed by U.N.
military observers.
</P>
<P>
   A cease-fire would give both armies enough time to withdraw and
spare the 200,000 trapped Congolese civilians further death and
destruction. At least 150 people have been killed and 700 wounded
since Monday, the Red Cross said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a humanitarian crisis. We want to have a cease-fire
with a compromise by the both local commanders to withdraw their
troops,'' said Lt. Col. Danilo Paiva, head of the 22-strong U.N.
observer team. ''A cease-fire without a withdrawal cannot hold.''
</P>
<P>
   Rwandan Col. Karenzi Karake said his troops were ready to quit
Kisangani, but not under fire from the Ugandan side.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, dawn on Saturday signaled a renewed battle for
survival in the besieged city, as residents scurried to fetch water
from the chocolate-colored Congo River, and others scrounged for
food amid the rising din of mortar and machine-gun fire. Running
water and power have been cut off for six days.
</P>
<P>
   Thick smoke billowed up from the barrels of Rwandan guns firing
from the Congo River bank, drawing occasional response from the
Ugandans, who fired back at the city. Both sides used multiple
rocket launchers.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. observers blamed local Rwandan and Ugandan army commanders
for failing to heed a cease-fire they had agreed to at least 20
times since Monday. On Thursday, Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
and his Rwandan counterpart, Paul Kagame, ordered the armies to
stop firing, but the clashes have continued.
</P>
<P>
   ''African armies are like that. They fight for their chiefs, not
for their nations,'' said U.N. Maj. Ramadan Sissoko, of Mali.
</P>
<P>
   Both armies were withdrawing from the city under a prearranged
plan Monday when the fighting broke out. Since then, 6,000 mortar
shells have fallen on the city, U.N. observers said.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda and Uganda are both in Congo because of their involvement
in the central African country's 22-month civil war. The two were
nominal allies, backing rival rebel factions fighting to oust Congo
President Laurent Kabila. But since August they have clashed with
each other in Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
   Under last year's peace accord, signed by the various armies in
Congo's civil war, U.N. observers are to be reinforced by a
5,537-strong peacekeeping force. So far, though, only 100 U.N.
personnel have been deployed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
