<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> With BC-CT--Snack Tax-Glance  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) - Like fat creeping up on a person's
thighs, a penny tax on junk food and soda would be little-noticed
at first but have long-term impact, two researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   The tax could generate $1.8 billion annually for programs in
schools and communities to teach people to eat healthy and
exercise, according to Yale professor Kelly Brownell and Michael
Jacobson, executive director of the Center for Science in the
Public Interest.
</P>
<P>
   A paper by the researchers in the June issue of the American
Journal of Public Health notes that dozens of states and
municipalities already tax snacks and soft drinks, although most of
the money does not pay for health programs.
</P>
<P>
   ''The food industry derides the notion of junk food taxes, never
even realizing or acknowledging more than a dozen states already
collect these taxes, and the states collect a billion dollars a
year,'' said Jacobson.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called ''snack tax'' or ''Twinkie tax'' is opposed by the
food industry and by grocers, who have to collect the tax. Some
states that have enacted such taxes later repealed them.
</P>
<P>
   Makers of candy, baked snacks, soda and other goodies that would
fall under the tax say their products are perfectly all right for
someone to consume in moderation, as part of a balanced diet.
</P>
<P>
   ''What is inherently wrong about eating an Oreo?'' asked Hank
Sandbach, vice president of public relations for cookiemaker
Nabisco.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe moderation and balance and variety are key to good
nutrition, not selecting certain foods and giving them labels,''
Sandbach said.
</P>
<P>
   The tax revenue would help counter ads for junk food, sodas and
candy that bombard consumers, said Brownell, a psychology professor
who heads the Yale Center for Eating and Weight Disorders.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are tipping the scales at ever-heavier weights - a
situation that calls for bold measures, Brownell said.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we're facing is a crisis with respect to poor diet and
weight. The prevalence of obesity in the U.S. is rapidly rising,
and there's no sign of the prevalence slowing,'' he said. ''The
disease and death caused by this is staggering, and I haven't heard
a single good idea of how to turn this around other than through
public policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The paper proposes a penny tax per 12-ounce can of soda, and a
penny tax per pound of candy, chips, snack foods and fats and oils.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike large sin taxes on alcohol or cigarettes that are
designed to discourage consumption, a small tax may be more
politically feasible and would mostly go unnoticed by the public,
the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   This approach seems to work in states such as Arkansas, where a
two-cent tax per can of soda and $2 per gallon tax of soft drink
syrup generates $40 million annually for Medicaid, the study says.
</P>
<P>
   The study leaves legislatures to decide exactly what could be
taxed and how the revenue would be collected.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a question of whether the public would go for such
a tax.
</P>
<P>
   Brownell said the public would be more willing to accept the tax
if they knew the money was going toward public health. Taxes in
some states have failed, in part because the tax was enacted just
to find another way for the government to make money.
</P>
<P>
   A telephone poll last year conducted for the Washington
D.C.-based Center for Science in the Public Interest found that 45
percent of those polled would favor a one-cent or five-cent tax to
fund a national health program. About 53 percent of those polled
opposed the tax at either amount.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't imagine that for somebody who likes their snacks, a
nutrition program is something they're going to vote for,'' said
Nabisco's Sandbach.
</P>
<P>
   Lunchtime eaters were divided on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Ullman of Hamden, an occupational therapist, said people
in the inner city need nutrition information to help them live
better, but she did not know if a snack tax would have other
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think they better do a pilot study first, because lots of
inner city people have problems getting healthful food - they have
enough money for a bag of chips, but they may not have enough for
other food,'' Ullman said.
</P>
<P>
   Jamal Brown, a New Haven truck driver, was puzzled by the very
idea of a snack tax as he picked up a bag of chips and a large Coke
for lunch at a convenience store.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tax my chips? Tax my Coke? I don't like the sound of that,''
Brown said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-10-00 1526 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000610.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 14 Detained on Vieques Bombing Range  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Military security agents detained
14 people Saturday morning for trespassing on the U.S. Navy bombing
range on the Puerto Rican island of Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   The group was taken to Naval station Roosevelt Roads on the main
island of Puerto Rico, Navy spokesman Robert Nelson said. They were
not charged, but were cited to appear before a federal judge at an
undetermined date before being released a few hours later, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among those arrested was a former director of the U.S.
territory's local Administration of Courts, Euladio Torres.
</P>
<P>
   Those in the group entered the bombing range at about 9:45 p.m.
Friday, and were walking on the main road of the Navy's Camp Garcia
base when they were detained, said Vieques activist Robert Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   The activity was meant to draw attention to opposition of Navy
bombing on the island and ''make the normal functioning of military
activities inside Camp Garcia impossible,'' Rabin said.
</P>
<P>
   Until last month, protesters had camped out on the bombing range
for nearly a year following a bombing accident that killed a
civilian security guard. On May 4, U.S. marshals raided the camps
and arrested more than 200 protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Since then dozens have been detained for trespassing, including
a group of 25 protesters and six journalists detained June 1 and
charged with trespassing on federal property.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy resumed bombing with concrete-filled dummy bombs
shortly after the May 4 raid. Islanders are to decide in a
referendum whether the Navy should leave in 2003, or stay longer
and resume using live ammunition. The referendum has yet to be
scheduled.
</P>
</TEXT>
