<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Confident on Burundi Plans  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- Former President Nelson
Mandela, who is acting as a peace mediator in Burundi, said
Saturday he was confident that some of the problems still plaguing
the war-torn country will be solved.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela was scheduled to travel Monday to Burundi for three days
to meet political dissidents and visit so-called regroupment camps,
where the Tutsi-led government has herded Hutu villagers displaced
by the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   During a meeting with Mandela on Wednesday in Johannesburg,
Burundi president Pierre Buyoya agreed to close down the
regroupment camps by July 31. The camps have garnered international
condemnation, and Mandela had called them concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   However, the issue of political prisoners remained unsolved.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela said Saturday he was confident the political prisoners
would be released. Mandela, himself a former political prisoner,
said he strongly disapproved of the ongoing incarceration of
''innocent people.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandela also said that Wednesday's agreement to give Tutsis and
Hutus equal representation in the army might need some tweaking. As
of now the army is Tutsi-dominated.
</P>
<P>
   The Hutu rebels originally demanded that they make up 70 percent
of the military, a demand Mandela called impractical.
</P>
<P>
   At least 200,000 people -- Hutus and Tutsis -- have been killed in
Burundi since October 1993, when paratroopers from the minority
Tutsi community assassinated the county's first democratically
elected president, a Hutu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
