<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex Pro-Israelis Sentenced to Jail  </HEADLINE>
By HUSSEIN DAKROUB
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- A pro-Israeli militiaman who shot and
killed a guerrilla after capturing him and another who served in a
notorious prison camp in Israeli-occupied southern Lebanon were
sentenced by military court to up to 15 years in jail, the toughest
punishment in the ongoing trials of Lebanese who dealt with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The court heard 72 cases Friday and decided on the cases of 36
suspects, eight of them women.
</P>
<P>
   One of the 36 was acquitted, and a woman was sentenced in
absentia to two years in jail. Thirty-four other defendants who
appeared in court were found guilty of charges of collaboration,
passing on information to the enemy, joining the South Lebanon Army
militia or entering Israel. They received prison terms ranging from
one month to seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Still technically at war with Israel, Lebanon prohibits any
dealings with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers for the third group of militiamen to be tried
had called for acquittals or lenient sentences, saying their
clients were coerced or forced into collaborating with Israel,
court officials said on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   But the sentences included the toughest since the trials began
Monday amid an uproar from guerrilla groups that the court went
soft on the first two batches of suspects.
</P>
<P>
   In the late Friday sentences, a former militiaman who shot dead
a guerrilla he captured during one of the attacks during the
18-year Israeli occupation received the toughest punishment -- 15
years in jail. He also was banned from returning to his hometown in
the former Israeli-occupied zone for 15 years after serving his
prison term.
</P>
<P>
   Another former militiaman received a 10-year prison sentence and
a 15-year banishment from his hometown after he serves his
sentence. He was convicted of collaboration, meeting with Israeli
military officers and passing information to the enemy. He also
served 18 months at the Khiam prison camp, where thousands of
people suspected of anti-Israeli or anti-SLA activities were held
without trial for years.
</P>
<P>
   The prison's 145 inmates were freed by villagers after the SLA
collapsed the day before Israeli troops withdrew from southern
Lebanon on May 24.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups have long accused the SLA of using torture
to punish Khiam inmates or to extract information from them.
</P>
<P>
   Two other ex-militiamen, an officer and an intelligence agent,
received a seven-year prison sentence each.
</P>
<P>
   Two more were sentenced to three years imprisonment, nine got
two years in jail, two received an 18-month term each and 14 were
sent to prison for a year. An architect who worked with the
occupation's civil administration was sentenced to six months in
jail.
</P>
<P>
   The court, whose verdicts cannot be appealed, already has
sentenced 101 former militiamen to jail terms of up to five years.
Anti-Israeli guerrillas have viewed the sentences as lenient;
relatives of the accused and some politicians have called them too
harsh.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,500 former SLA members surrendered to Lebanese
authorities during and after Israel's troop withdrawal last month
from southern Lebanon. About 7,000 Lebanese -- ex-militiamen and
their families -- sought refuge in Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-10-00 1628 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000610.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Plans Paid Leave Guidelines  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton opened the door Saturday for
states to provide unemployment pay to workers who take unpaid time
off to care for a newborn child or sick relative, expanding an
already popular Family Leave Act.
</P>
<P>
   In his weekly radio address, Clinton announced new regulations
by the Labor Department that would allow states to provide paid
leave after the birth or adoption of a child. He also announced a
new regulation, effective June 20, that allows federal employees to
use up to 12 weeks of sick leave to care for a seriously ill family
member.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he sought the changes because many workers cannot
afford to take time off without pay as stipulated under the 1993
Family and Medical Leave Act, the first bill he signed as
president.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that 20 million people have taken advantage of the law
to care for a newborn or a sick relative, and said more might do so
if they didn't have to lose pay.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are too many families that aren't making use of the law
because they simply can't afford to take the time off if it means
sacrificing a paycheck,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen states are considering legislation to provide paid leave
through means such as unemployment insurance, and the president
said he hopes more states will join them.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe those which do can provide this new benefit while
still preserving the fiscal soundness of their unemployment
insurance programs,'' Clinton said. ''The first few months with a
newborn are precious ones, and no parent should have to miss
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Sen. Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts, whose state is
considering a proposal to provide paid leave through unemployment
insurance, said Clinton's announcement ''gives hope to families
that cannot afford to take time off to spend time with their
newborn or newly adopted children.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Judith L. Lichtman, president of the National Partnership
for Women and Families: ''It is time -- past time -- to update our
policies to fit today's work force and today's families.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, chairman of the House
Republican Conference, said the plan was ''ill-conceived.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Under Clinton's proposal, there will be nothing there if we
have an economic downturn and more Americans are suddenly
unemployed,'' Watts said. ''Clinton's proposal will shred the
safety net for the unemployed.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Labor Department regulations, states would have the
option to amend unemployment compensation systems to provide paid
leave for new parents. States that do opt to offer paid leave would
receive help from federal labor officials in assessing the
long-term fiscal impact of that decision.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cited a federal study that found the number of married
mothers working outside the home has increased from 38 percent to
68 percent over the past 30 years, and the average parent has 22
fewer hours per week at home compared with a generation ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are working more jobs and longer hours than ever
before, forcing many of them to make the unacceptable choice
between being good workers and the best parents or caregivers,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Some state unemployment insurance programs are financially flush
because the booming economy has put more people to work than at any
time in 30 years. But employers, who provide those funds, oppose
using the money for purposes other than unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   The White House: www.whitehouse.gov
</P>
<P>
   Labor Department, for pre-publication copy of regulation:
www.dol.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-10-00 1645 </TRAILER>
