<HEADLINE> Israel Sees Risks, Chances in Syria  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA KING
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- For Israel, the death of Syrian President Hafez
Assad carries great risk -- and enormous opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   The risk: that the sudden passing of a strongman who ruled Syria
single-handedly for three decades will deal a heavy blow to peace
prospects by ushering in a prolonged period of instability, even
chaos.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity: that a bit of Syria's implacable enmity toward
Israel -- if only a bit -- might have died along with its hard-line
leader.
</P>
<P>
   For the 69-year-old Assad, hating Israel was something personal
-- a bitter and long-nursed grievance. But for the 34-year-old son
Assad had groomed as his heir in recent years, Syria's state of war
with Israel -- which continues to this day -- is more of an
abstraction, a chain of historical events that played themselves
out while he was still only a child.
</P>
<P>
   Assad never got over his fury at losing the Golan Heights to
Israel in the 1967 Middle East War. Defense minister at the time,
he viewed it as an affront to his personal pride. When Syria
regained a bit of the territory in bloody fighting six years later,
the Syrian leader traveled there himself to raise the flag.
</P>
<P>
   As Syria entered into negotiations with Israel in December,
centering on the all-but-assured return of the Golan Heights, Assad
radiated mistrust and suspicion. He would not even allow his top
diplomat, Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa, to shake the hand of
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   The talks broke down within weeks amid Assad's insistence that
Israel commit -- even before the negotiations could progress -- to
returning to prewar 1967 borders.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has long kept a watchful eye on Assad's likely successor:
his son Bashar, an ophthalmologist by profession.
</P>
<P>
   Although a political neophyte, he is known to be an enthusiastic
supporter of economic reform -- something that could bode well for
restarting peace talks. Reviving Syria's moribund, isolated economy
would require much greater engagement with the outside world than
the elder Assad ever allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Barak extended condolences to the Syrian people, his
aides were rushing to offer flattering assessments of Bashar Assad.
Within hours of the announcement of Assad's death, Israeli media
were citing senior Barak associates as calling his son intelligent
and thoughtful.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the greatest peril posed by Assad's death lies in its
timing: a scant three weeks after Israel withdrew its troops from
south Lebanon. Because Syria essentially runs Lebanon's affairs,
the big question in the wake of Israel's pullout has been whether
Assad would keep a tight rein on the Hezbollah guerrillas who led
the fight to drive Israel out of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ''The belief that quiet will reign in Lebanon after the
withdrawal from there depends on the desire of Syria to influence,
to ensure that quiet and the stability,'' said Itamar Rabinovich, a
former ambassador to the United States who served as head of
Israel's earlier negotiations with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as a result of Assad's death, ''there are question marks
over both the desire and the ability (of Syria)'' to keep fighting
from breaking out, he told Israel's Channel One.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has said previously that any renewal of Hezbollah's
cross-border attacks would bring an extremely harsh response,
possibly targeting Syrian troops in Lebanon -- and raising the risk
of a larger regional conflagration.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we need to see is ... that the new Syrian leadership does
not permit Hezbollah or any other organization to renew their
actions in south Lebanon,'' Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh
told Channel Two.
</P>
<P>
   Cabinet minister Amnon Lipkin Shahak, a former army chief who
was deeply involved in past negotiations with Syria, told Israel
television it could be a long time before the succession question
is worked out and Bashar Assad's intentions become clear.
</P>
<P>
   Others echoed that view. ''We can only guess and estimate what
will happen now, because internal politics and changes and the
ability to take charge and take the leadership are things that
cannot be known beforehand,'' said Rabinovich, who has written
books on Assad.
</P>
<P>
   To some Palestinians, Assad's death meant the possibility of
improved Syrian-Palestinian relations.
</P>
<P>
   ''He wasn't popular among us because throughout the years he has
taken the hard line against us, against the Palestinian
Authority,'' said Hiyam Nasserdin, a 45-year-old math teacher from
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Khaled Jabari, 47, said he would refuse to close his shop to
mark the three days of mourning called for by Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ''I won't close for Hafez Assad because he was bad to the
Palestinians and he always attacked our leaders and did not support
us at all,'' Jabari said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the very real fears of a potential power struggle in
Syria, the death of so unrelenting a foe could not help but bring a
few sighs of relief in Israel's official circles. Implicitly
acknowledging that, Public Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami chose
to remind his compatriots of a biblical injunction.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rejoice not,'' he said, ''in your enemy's death.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
