<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The writing's on the wall: Guernsey's to hold auction of graffiti art </HEADLINE>
By DEEPTI HAJELA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The writing started out small in the late 1960s
- names scribbled on walls, subway cars, doors.
</P>
<P>
   But in the early 1970s, the letters got bigger, more colorful,
more stylized. The spray-painted monikers like Tracy 168 WILDSTYLE
and Phase 2 began taking up sides of whole subway cars. Then, into
the 1980s, came the murals, often running along the length of whole
trains, showcasing their creators' visions throughout the five
boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   The subway art in New York is mostly gone now, cleaned up and
painted over and replaced by other trains. But for two days next
week, the spotlight will be back on graffiti art, at an auction
believed to be the first of its kind.
</P>
<P>
   Guernsey's, the auction house that sold Mark McGwire's 70th
home-run baseball and a controversial collection of Kennedy
memorabilia, will feature the works of about 100 graffiti artists
during a two-day sale on Wednesday and Thursday nights at the Puck
Building. Previews start at noon Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Arlan Ettinger, the auction house's president, said he had been
interested in graffiti ever since the late 1960s, when he noticed
that Taki 183, considered one of the first known ''taggers,'' had
written his name on spots all over the city.
</P>
<P>
   ''Something for years had been gnawing at me ... that would have
been an interesting auction to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ettinger assumed it had already been done, but said Guernsey's
research couldn't find any evidence of any other auction of this
kind.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the works for sale are spray paint on canvas, but there
are the more unusual items: A door from the apartment above 51 X
Gallery, tagged by the likes of Jean-Michel Basquiat and Keith
Haring, a pinball machine, a subway map. There are also photographs
of the painted subway trains that used to run through the city.
</P>
<P>
   Tagging trains was more of a status-builder in the graffiti art
community than anything else, because the trains were seen by
millions, said Tracy 168 WILDSTYLE.
</P>
<P>
   ''If your name led the train, you were the man,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the artists involved in the auction, many of them longtime
taggers who have graduated from subway cars to displaying their
pieces in galleries and collections, it's good to see graffiti art
getting such recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ''The auction is neat,'' said Taki 183, who has long since left
his tagging days behind him and is reluctant to give out much of
his current personal information. ''You never think that is going
to happen in a million years.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We are one of the few arts that originated in America,'' said
Lady Pink, one of the few well-known women artists in the heavily
male-dominated graffiti world.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, she said, ''This is a piece of New York history that you
can no longer see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
