<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, June 10, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Regrets Assad Missed Peace
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NORTHFIELD, Minn. (AP) -- President Clinton said today he is disappointed a
peace agreement between Israel and Syria was not achieved while President Hafez
Assad was alive. The 69-year-old Assad had steadfastly demanded return from
Israel of all the Golan Heights, a border plateau that Israel took in the 1967
Six-Day War. Israel has offered to return the Golan. But Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak balked at Syria's demand for a sliver of land along the shores of the
Sea of Galilee, the source of about 40 percent of Israel's water. The president
said it was too early to assess the impact Assad's death will have on Middle
East peace negotiations. The autocratic leader, who suffered from heart
problems, died Saturday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Delivers Final Commencement Address
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NORTHFIELD, Minn. (AP) -- President Clinton today told graduates of a private
liberal arts college where annual costs exceed $29,000 that the United States
can't afford to deny college to students just because they don't have the money
for it. ''Over the past 20 years, the cost of college has quadrupled,'' Clinton
told 423 graduates of Carleton College, about 40 miles south of Minneapolis.
''I'll bet there are a lot of parents here who have taken second mortgages or
second jobs to help pay those tuition bills.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Yugoslavs Mark Bombing Anniversary
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ALEKSINAC, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Vowing to prevent further wars in Yugoslavia,
an army general and several officials on Saturday marked the first anniversary
of the end of NATO's 78-day air attack in this mining town, where Allied bombs
killed 19 civilians. About 2,000 people attended the ceremony -- called ''Memory
and Hope'' -- which is to become an annual event commemorating the day NATO
suspended its bombing campaign against Yugoslavia. Addressing the crowd, the
Yugoslav army's chief of staff, Gen. Nebojsa Pavkovic, blasted the United States
and NATO for their ''cowardly aggression'' in the air raids, and promised his
troops would prevent any further wars in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mrs. Clinton Can't Open Gap in NY
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Despite the departure of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani from the
closely watched U.S. Senate race in New York, Hillary Rodham Clinton has been
unable to open up a gap over the Republican opposition, according to three
independent polls. When Giuliani pulled out of the race on May 19, Republican
leaders predicted that by late summer or early fall their new candidate, Rep.
Rick Lazio, would be running even with the first lady. But on June 7, the
Quinnipiac University Polling Institute came out with its offering. It showed
Clinton and Lazio tied, at 44 percent each.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Greece Seeks Ex-CIA Chief Testimony
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- A Greek court summoned a former Central Intelligence
Agency director to testify, as efforts to track down the killers of a British
diplomat generated little success, authorities said today. A public prosecutor
wants to interview James Woolsey after the former spymaster reportedly suggested
that members of Greece's Socialist government could identify terrorists in the
November 17 group, but had done nothing to arrest them. The terrorist group has
killed 22 people, including four American officials, since 1975, but none of its
members have ever been caught.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Commendable Wins Belmont Stakes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Commendable, whose only previous victory was a maiden race
last August, snapped a six-race losing streak and won the Belmont Stakes on a
sweltering Saturday. The victory was the fourth Belmont win for D. Wayne Lukas
and the 13th victory in a Triple Crown race for the Hall of Fame trainer.
Commendable, ridden by Pat Day, who won the Belmont for the third time, took
charge on the final turn and turned back all challengers. Missing from the
11-horse field were Kentucky Derby winner Fusaichi Pegasus and Preakness winner
Red Bullet. It was the first time since 1970 that the Derby and Preakness winner
both missed the Belmont.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Yankees Romp Mets 13-5
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Jorge Posada greeted Pat Mahomes with a tiebreaking
three-run homer in a five-run fifth inning, and the Yankees twice came from
behind to beat the Mets 13-5 today in the Bronx and even this year's Subway
Series at a game apiece. A day after routing the two-time World Series champs
12-2 in their first meeting this season, the Mets led 3-2 and 5-3 before the
Yankees took over. Before a raucous sellout of 55,839, Bernie Williams and Tino
Martinez hit consecutive RBI doubles in the first -- right fielder Derek Bell
let Martinez's catchable fly fall behind him.
AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON 
</P>
</TEXT>
