<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assad's Death May Halt Peace Effort  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The death of Syrian President Hafez Assad is
likely to set already stalled U.S. peace efforts further back as
his successor takes hold and decides whether to show more
flexibility in dealing with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton declined in a statement Saturday to
''speculate about the future'' but said he hoped peace still could
be achieved because of Assad's strategic commitment to it.
</P>
<P>
   Battling severe ailments for years, Assad had been grooming his
son, Bashar, to succeed him and presumably in the process was
imbuing him with the father's determination to recover all
territory lost to Israel in Syria's humiliating defeat in the 1967
Six-Day War.
</P>
<P>
   Assad was unwilling to bend. A major question is whether his
successor will bend -- or will feel strong enough to soften Assad's
position -- for the sake of a deal with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the question whether Israel would have the
confidence to count on a new and untried leader from the minority
Alawite sect to follow through.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, chosen by the
president to lead the U.S. delegation to Assad's funeral, stressed
in statements of condolence that Assad made a decision for peace
with Israel, and they would proceed on the assumption it would
survive him.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Haass, vice president of the Brookings Institution,
said: ''I'm not so sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Haass, who was Middle East adviser to former President Bush,
said Assad's commitment to peace was incomplete. ''He may have had
a commitment in principle, but it did not translate into
practice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Haass said in an interview, ''in order to make peace
you've got to be strong internally, and it's inconceivable his
successor will have a domestic position of strength for some time
to come, if ever.''
</P>
<P>
   On a similar note, Samuel W. Lewis, a former U.S. ambassador to
Israel and assistant secretary of state, said, ''For the next few
months, and probably a good deal longer, the problem of settling in
a new leadership in Damascus will be all-consuming, in great
likelihood.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis added: ''There is really no chance you can have a serious
return to the negotiating table until quite a lot of time has
elapsed.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking an entirely different view, Richard Perle, an assistant
secretary of defense in the Reagan administration, said Assad's
death ''should in time open the way for a much more constructive
Syrian policy.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a country that supports terrorism,'' Perle said in an
interview. ''Assad was personally responsible for the murder of
thousands of people, and it's hard to imagine that he could ever
become an instrument for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   For the right peace terms, Assad could have regained from
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak virtually all the Golan Heights,
a militarily valuable border highland. Assad insisted also on a
strip of land on the shores of the Sea of Galilee, the source of
some 40 percent of Israel's water. Barak balked and turned his
attention to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton went to Geneva, Switzerland, in March to renew Israel's
offer. Assad turned him down. Still, Clinton stressed in Saturday's
condolence statement that Assad had made a ''strategic choice'' for
peace and had made clear to him ''Syria's continued commitment to
the path of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate statement, Albright said, ''We strongly believe
that was the right choice and expect that Syria will continue on
the path of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Progress on a settlement between Israel and the Palestinians is
slow, as well. Senior Israeli and Palestinian negotiators are due
in Washington to resume talks on Tuesday after a two-week lapse,
and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat is scheduled to see Clinton on
Wednesday at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate indication that Assad's death would
affect the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Only last Wednesday, while in Cairo, Albright tested Syria's
disposition toward reopening negotiations with Israel that were
held under U.S. auspices last January.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa, she told
reporters that Syria was interested but that he had not signaled a
shift in his country's territorial demands.
</P>
<P>
   ''I did not get any indication of a change,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign minister said in Cairo, meanwhile, that his one-hour
talk with Albright had cleared the air and ''removed much of the
misunderstanding that occurred in the past few months, particularly
that concerning the Geneva summit'' between Assad and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Sharaa also said Syria would not sacrifice its rights --
presumably referring to every last bit on land it once held.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Barry Schweid has covered Middle East diplomacy
for The Associated Press since 1973.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
