<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Homeless Man Bluffs Into Hospital  </HEADLINE>
By TIM MOLLOY
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- A homeless man carrying fake credentials
bluffed his way into a hospital emergency room and worked through
the night shift as a physician's assistant before revealing he is
HIV-positive and had sneaked into other hospitals before, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   The man, who identified himself as Gary Lee Stearley, 26, was
closely supervised throughout the shift at Mercy Hospital and no
patients were hurt, police Sgt. Charles Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   He always wore gloves, Mercy spokeswoman Linda Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Stearley carried identification cards for two other
hospitals, but they had not yet verified his story, whether he is
indeed HIV-positive, or even his name.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said Stearley told him he had a history of mental
illness and had once studied to be a paramedic in Tampa, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ''Do I think he had any malicious intentions? No,'' Rodriguez
said. ''It more seemed he was acting out his passion to be an ER
person, to be in that setting helping people medically.''
</P>
<P>
   Stearley was charged with trespassing and false impersonation
and was being held Saturday in lieu of $25,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said the man carried ID cards with the name Joshua A.
Caldwell for Virginia Commonwealth University hospital in Richmond,
Va., and Howard University hospital in Washington, D.C. He said
Stearley told him he got photo ID cards by pretending to be a new
worker.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the two hospitals did not return calls for comment
Saturday, but police said neither listed him as an employee.
</P>
<P>
   Mercy employees said Stearley arrived early Thursday wearing
surgical scrubs and apologized for being late for the midnight to 8
a.m. shift. He said he had arranged to complete a two-week study
program and presented the Virginia ID.
</P>
<P>
   Ross said hospital workers questioned him because they had not
expected him, but allowed him to work the shift because he was
dressed like an assistant, gave the name of the doctor with whom he
had supposedly arranged to study, and ''spoke medical jargon.''
</P>
<P>
   Stearley made the rounds with doctors, and treated at least one
patient. Police said one witness saw him apply stitches, but Ross
said he only tied stitches that a hospital employee had applied.
</P>
<P>
   Stearley was caught when a secretary discovered the phone
numbers and addresses he gave on a registration form were false,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   Security officers confronted him when he returned to the
hospital Thursday night for another shift. He voluntarily checked
into the hospital's psychiatric ward and was arrested when he tried
to leave Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Ross said no hospital employees would be disciplined for
allowing him access to the emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   Stearley is also wanted in Richmond in connection with the
disappearance of a laptop computer from the medical college, and in
Seattle for missing a court date on a charge of possessing stolen
property, Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Stearley said he had been traveling the country since he ran
away from home somewhere in Michigan at age 14, police said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-10-00 1803 </TRAILER>
