<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fire Risk Makes for Unusual Summer  </HEADLINE>
By STEVE KARNOWSKI
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALONG THE GUNFLINT TRAIL, Minn. (AP) -- In the nation's most
popular wilderness area, people can canoe, hike, fish and camp to
their heart's content. This summer, though, they can't enjoy one of
the enduring traditions of the North Woods -- sitting around an open
campfire.
</P>
<P>
   The problem in the Boundary Waters Canoe Area Wilderness is more
than 1,000 miles removed from parts of the West and Southeast that
have been charred by wildfires in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But despite some recent rain and more than 1,000 lakes and
streams, much of the northern wilderness area has been experiencing
very dry conditions at a particularly bad time.
</P>
<P>
   This wild, beautiful stretch of country near the Canadian border
became a tinderbox full of kindling when a ferocious wind storm
last July 4 knocked down millions of trees on about a third of the
1.1 million-acre BWCA, which lies within the Superior National
Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say fires are inevitable. In some places, fallen trees
make up as much as 150 tons of fuel per acre.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Forest Service has banned open fires in roughly half of
the wilderness area, which draws more than 200,000 adventurers from
around the world every year. This summer, those people are doing
their cooking on portable camp stoves if they're in the fire zone.
Similar restrictions affect a relatively small slice of the
adjoining 1.2 million-acre Quetico Provincial Park in Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   National Geographic Traveler magazine recently listed the
Boundary Waters as one of the 50 ''must-see spots'' that every
''real traveler'' should visit at least once his or her lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   And it was one of the favorite spots of the late CBS newsman
Charles Kuralt.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it is absolute solitude you want, you have only to paddle
far enough,'' he wrote in his 1995 book, ''Charles Kuralt's
America.''
</P>
<P>
   ''In two or three days of paddling and portaging, you can be
reasonably assured of reaching the beautiful lake of your fondest
dreams, where you can set up camp for a week or two without hearing
another human voice.''
</P>
<P>
   On days when the wind is still, the silence is as stunning as
the rugged scenery. People are often few and far between, even
though there are about 6,000 to 12,000 visitors within the
wilderness on any given summer day. There are no roads, and motors
are banned except for storm cleanup and firefighting.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters and tanker aircraft will be on alert all of this
summer and probably for several summers. Prescribed burns and
salvage logging are being done just outside the BWCA to reduce the
wildfire danger. And the Forest Service is planning controlled
burns inside the BWCA starting next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ruined trees and the restrictions, many canoeists
who have trekked through the Boundary Waters recently say it's
still well worth the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ''The power of God was neat to see,'' said Emily Slinger, one of
a group of seven young people from the Minneapolis-St. Paul area.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's some areas up there where there's not a tree
standing,'' said David Fink, another member of the party.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the damage has been covered up by this year's new
growth. And even in severely affected areas, trees right along the
lakes often managed to withstand the storm as the flattened areas
are often patchy, interspersed with intact stands of timber.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy enough to route a trip away from the blowdown area
into zones where campfires are still allowed.
</P>
<P>
   But the storm damage was part of the attraction for Charlie Cole
and Cliff Pomeroy, who traveled from Indiana to retrace a route
they had covered on a previous trip.
</P>
<P>
   ''It wasn't the only reason we came, but it was part of it,''
Pomeroy said at his journey's end at Round Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ''And it was pretty awesome,'' Cole agreed.
</P>
<P>
   One of their favorite campsites, on Gabimichigami Lake, was
still beautiful despite the loss of about 20 big trees, they said.
Pine trees were snapped off midway up, while birches had been
knocked on their sides.
</P>
<P>
   ''Overall I'm really pleased with the way everything still
looks,'' Cole said. ''It's not destroyed. ... There's a few spots
that are total devastation, but they're small and few. Mostly it
looks about like it did before.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Superior National Forest and Boundary Waters:
http://www.snf.toofarnorth.org
</P>
<P>
   BWCA online reservations: http://www.bwcaw.org
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Department of Natural Resources fire info:
http://www.ra.dnr.state.mn.us/fire
</P>
<P>
   Quetico Provincial Park:
http://www.mnr.gov.on.ca/MNR/parks/quet.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-10-00 1840 </TRAILER>
