<DOCNO> APW20000610.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Hopes for Political Revival  </HEADLINE>
By RON FOURNIER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The loyal sidekick to a self-styled ''Comeback
Kid,'' Vice President Al Gore hopes he is in the midst of a
political revival of his own.
</P>
<P>
   After a week in which he launched a multimillion-dollar TV ad
campaign, released the first in a series of economic initiatives
and announced a lengthy ''progress and prosperity tour,'' Gore said
this may be a turning point in his campaign against George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor kept a steady pace in battleground states,
promising in government reform speeches to usher in an era of
political civility. It was a high-minded, poll-tested tone designed
to capitalize on voter disgust with partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   ''In just seven months ... we will leave our current president
to the judgment of history,'' Bush said Thursday. ''What matters
now is whether the bitterness that now prevails in Washington will
continue after this term.''
</P>
<P>
   For both Bush and Gore, this is the season to tinker with themes
and shore up political standing for the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   National polls show the race is tight, after Bush held slight
leads in recent weeks. Bush remains ahead in the more important
state-by-state battle, however, with leads in enough states to give
him more than two-thirds of the 270 electoral votes required to win
the White House. Gore is ahead in enough states to give him fewer
than half the votes he needs.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats believe Gore has allowed Bush to get the upper hand in
the battle to court moderate and ticket-splitting voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''What you're going to see out of Gore this month is whether you
can jump-start this race with an electorate that still has little
interest in the campaign,'' Democratic consultant Jim Duffy said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's an important time because the policy positions of
both candidates are becoming more clear with each passing day,''
said Montana Gov. Marc Racicot, a Bush adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Tuesday in New York, the vice president will begin
rolling out a series of economic initiatives in battleground
states. His goal: take credit for the largest economic surge in the
nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and his top policy advisers met Saturday in an all-day wonk
session to hash out the announcements the vice president will make
on his tour.
</P>
<P>
   Gore jumped the gun last week, announcing his support of a
''lock box'' to protect Medicare surpluses from budgetary raids.
Aides said Gore feared that Republicans or fellow Democrats would
beat him to the punch.
</P>
<P>
   In a private meeting, President Clinton, who called himself the
''Comeback Kid'' in the 1992 campaign, gave Gore the go-ahead to
embrace the initiative, one that had been discussed by Clinton's
own advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that this is a turning point -- more for the country
than the campaign -- because it's time to start the discussion of
what we're going to do with the surplus and how we can safeguard
our prosperity,'' Gore said in an interview with The Associated
Press.
</P>
<P>
   Voters are not giving Gore much credit for the unprecedented
economic boom. Polls indicate voters are about evenly divided on
whether Gore or Bush is the best candidate to continue the surge.
</P>
<P>
   The tour will take Gore to a number of key states -- including
Kentucky, Pennsylvania, Ohio and Wisconsin -- where analysts say he
is not getting credit for the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only possible thing to do, is say 'Hey, folks, I'm part of
this administration. Look at how good things are; look at how
pleased you are with the president. I'm part of that team,''' said
Charles Jones, a political science professor emeritus at the
University of Wisconsin-Madison.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even Pennsylvania, which suffered the most in the transition
from the industrial to the information age, has come around. We are
enjoying unprecedented levels of employment,'' said Mark Singel, a
former lieutenant governor of Pennsylvania. ''Al Gore rightfully
can take some of the credit.''
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say Gore will have a hard time getting heard when
voters are planning summer vacations and not watching the White
House race.
</P>
<P>
   ''Coming to the state is probably the most effective way to
communicate with people who aren't interested in being communicated
with about the presidential campaign,'' said Paul Tipps, former
state chairman of the Democratic Party in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bush are running even in Pennsylvania and Wisconsin,
Gore is slightly behind in Ohio and behind by double digits in
Kentucky, state polls show.
</P>
<P>
   Meant to help Gore, the Democratic ad campaign unveiled last
week reflects the vice president's problems. Not only are the ads
running in traditional swing states like Michigan and Pennsylvania,
but Gore has been forced to spend his limited money in Democratic
bastions.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the 15 states airing the ads voted for Democratic
candidates in the past three presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we have to fight in Oregon and Washington, it's not a
good sign,'' consultant Duffy said. ''You can conclude from their
(ad) buy that they felt they could not wait, especially in
Washington, Oregon, Iowa and Wisconsin, where he needs to go and
define who he is and move this campaign in another direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush will spend a chunk of this week at his family's retreat in
Kennebunkport, Maine. His senior advisers will present their
recommendations for the Republican National Convention, which
begins July 31 in Philadelphia, and Bush may work on his list of
about 12 vice presidential prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's team already has spread the word that the convention will
be less partisan than past gatherings. Though Gore will surely be
criticized, Bush is intent on keeping the focus on his own agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Let Gore suffer the wrath of voters weary of partisan attacks,
Bush seems to be saying.
</P>
<P>
   ''Americans look upon the spectacle of Washington and they do
not like what they see,'' he said in a speech last week. ''I agree
with them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-10-00 1840 </TRAILER>
