<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, June 10, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Syrian President Hafez Assad Dies
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) -- Syrian Presiden Hafez Assad died Saturday before he
was able to win back the treasured Golan Heights he lost to the Jewish state 33
years ago. Assad, 69, had been suffering from heart problems. No funeral plans
were immediately announced. The skillful and ruthless leader's death could deal
a blow to Mideast peace prospects by triggering a prolonged period of
instability. But it could also mean an opportunity for Syria to forsake at least
part of its enmity toward Israel. The Syrian parliament moved to clear the way
for Assad's son, Bashar, to assume the presidency, amending the constitution to
lower the minimum age for presidents to 34 -- Bashar's age.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Region Sorrowful Over Assad's Death
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Syria's neighbors mourned the death of President Hafez
Assad, saying that it robbed the region of a visionary who stood unwavering in
the face of challenges to the Arab nations. Around the Arab world, including the
United Arab Emirates, Qatar, Egypt, Libya, Kuwait, the Palestinian Authority,
Morocco and Bahrain, a three-day mourning period was declared. In Lebanon, where
Syria has 30,000 troops stationed and has served as the main power-broker for
more than two decades, a one-week mourning period was declared during which
flags would be flown at half-staff. Jordan declared a 40-day mourning period.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
S. Koreans Focus on Summit Symbolism
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- For the first-ever meeting between leaders of
South Korea and North Korea, a South Korean official is warning against high
expectations. ''The picture of two leaders smiling and shaking hands, the
picture itself is a great message for world peace,'' South Korean Culture and
Tourism Minister Park Jie-won said. The three-day summit between South Korean
President Kim Dae-jung and North Korean leader Kim Jong Il, which starts Monday
in Pyongyang, caps six months of vigorous diplomacy with China, Italy,
Australia, the United States and other countries. Prospects for reconciliation
remain unclear.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Urges Higher Education for All
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NORTHFIELD, Minn. (AP) -- President Clinton today told graduates of a private
liberal arts college where annual costs exceed $29,000 that the United States
can't afford to deny college to students just because they don't have the money
for it. ''Over the past 20 years, the cost of college has quadrupled,'' Clinton
told 423 graduates of Carleton College, about 40 miles south of Minneapolis.
''I'll bet there are a lot of parents here who have taken second mortgages or
second jobs to help pay those tuition bills.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mrs. Clinton Can't Open Gap in N.Y.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Despite the departure of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani from the
closely watched U.S. Senate race in New York, Hillary Rodham Clinton has been
unable to open up a gap over the Republican opposition, according to three
independent polls. When Giuliani pulled out of the race on May 19, Republican
leaders predicted that by late summer or early fall their new candidate, Rep.
Rick Lazio, would be running even with the first lady. But on June 7, the
Quinnipiac University Polling Institute came out with its offering. It showed
Clinton and Lazio tied, at 44 percent each.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Homeless Man Bluffs Way Into Hospital
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- A homeless man carrying fake credentials bluffed his way
into a hospital emergency room and worked through the night shift as a
physician's assistant before revealing he is HIV-positive and had sneaked into
other hospitals before, police said. The man, who identified himself as Gary Lee
Stearley, 26, was closely supervised throughout the shift at Mercy Hospital and
no patients were hurt, police Sgt. Charles Rodriguez said. He always wore
gloves, Mercy spokeswoman Linda Ross said. Stearley was charged with trespassing
and false impersonation and was being held today in lieu of $25,000 bail.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Commendable Wins the Belmont Stakes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Commendable, whose only previous victory was a maiden race
last August, snapped a six-race losing streak and won the Belmont Stakes on a
sweltering Saturday. The victory was the fourth Belmont win for D. Wayne Lukas
and the 13th victory in a Triple Crown race for the Hall of Fame trainer.
Commendable, ridden by Pat Day, who won the Belmont for the third time, took
charge on the final turn and turned back all challengers. Missing from the
11-horse field were Kentucky Derby winner Fusaichi Pegasus and Preakness winner
Red Bullet. It was the first time since 1970 that the Derby and Preakness winner
both missed the Belmont.
AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON 
</P>
</TEXT>
