<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-NY-BRF--Mudslide Mess,0167  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BETHLEHEM, N.Y. (AP) - A 90-foot roadside cliff that last month
lost a 300-foot chunk of itself in a landslide again shifted
Saturday, covering two bulldozers with dirt.
</P>
<P>
   No one was injured in what state Department of Transportation
officials termed a ''readjustment'' of the slope.
</P>
<P>
   DOT engineers have been working since the May 16 landslide to be
able to reopen the roadway, a crucial link between the city of
Albany and the Delmar community in the suburban town of Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
   Since the slide, two families evacuated, business has slumped
and thousands of commuters have been detoured. A produce market
became a pile of timber when it toppled from the cliff two days
after the slide.
</P>
<P>
   The bulldozers are the property of a subcontractor hired by the
DOT to assist in stability tests, which spokesman Michael Fleischer
said was the first step in reopening at least part of the road.
</P>
<P>
   The landslide is blamed on a combination of heavy rains and the
Normans Kill creek below, which cut into the base of the weak
clay-soiled hill.
</P>
</TEXT>
