<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AMA Holds Annual Meeting  </HEADLINE>
By LINDSEY TANNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Doctors want the American Medical Association to
sharpen its attacks against managed care and take the lead in
shaping Internet medicine.
</P>
<P>
   But as the nation's largest group of physicians debates those
issues at its annual meeting beginning Sunday, the AMA's leaders
have another pressing concern on their minds: Find a remedy for
anemic membership and ailing finances.
</P>
<P>
   They fear that without a cure, the AMA could lose the clout it
needs to address physicians' and patients' worries.
</P>
<P>
   ''Membership must be a prime consideration in everything the AMA
does,'' AMA leaders said in a recent letter to meeting delegates.
</P>
<P>
   The AMA gained nearly 3,000 new members last year -- its first
increase in five years. But about two-thirds of the nation's
800,000-plus doctors, residents and medical students have not
joined.
</P>
<P>
   And much of the recruitment effort focuses on students and new
doctors eligible for substantial discounts on the $420 annual dues.
</P>
<P>
   Membership revenue fell by $4.8 million in 1999 and expenses
exceeded revenues by $9.2 million -- nearly $3 million more than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   The AMA is in the midst of a restructuring it hopes will show
members ''that their dues dollars are wisely and strategically
spent on the programs most meaningful to them,'' the letter to
delegates said.
</P>
<P>
   But the AMA's focus on managed care and e-medicine also may help
it win support from patients, who share the frustration and worry
about the privacy of health records in the electronic age, said
Lawrence Gostin, the health, law and ethics editor of the Journal
of the American Medical Association, the AMA's weekly medical
journal.
</P>
<P>
   At last year's annual meeting, the AMA responded to doctors'
frustration with managed care in a landmark vote to form a union
for doctors, the Physicians for Responsible Negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking ''a new direction'' in the fight, Missouri delegates to
this year's meeting want the AMA to work with states to find
grounds for class-action lawsuits against insurers who deny or
delay payment of legitimate claims.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the first such actions by a state medical society, the
California Medical Association last month filed a federal lawsuit
against the three largest for-profit national health plans in
California for allegedly forcing doctors to provide
less-than-adequate health care to patients.
</P>
<P>
   C.C. Swarens of the Missouri State Medical Association said
lawsuits may be the best recourse ''if insurers are going to put up
roadblocks at every occasion, instead of trying to work with the
medical community.''
</P>
<P>
   A managed-care industry spokeswoman said focusing on lawsuits
would be misguided.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are many other and better avenues for problem-solving
that don't involve sending things to the courts,'' said Susan
Pisano of the American Association of Health Plans.
</P>
<P>
   In related resolutions before the 550-member policy-making House
of Delegates, the AMA is being asked to:
</P>
<P>
   -- Back legislation that would prevent managed care from giving
doctors financial incentives to limit care and to allow patients
unrestricted access to any doctor in a health plan.
</P>
<P>
   -- Develop model legislation banning ''all-products clauses''
that require doctors to accept patients from all health plans
offered by an insurer instead of allowing them to pick and choose
the least restrictive.
</P>
<P>
   -- Launch a publicity campaign urging Congress to amend antitrust
laws to give doctors new rights to bargain collectively with health
maintenance organizations. The House Rules Committee delayed action
on the legislation late last month.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would lift federal antitrust laws banning collective
bargaining by the self-employed -- doctors not employed by a
hospital or a municipality. The AMA says that would benefit
patients by allowing doctors to fight as a group against
restrictions such as limits on testing imposed by managed-care
insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say it could disrupt patient care and result in higher
costs. But, like the Physicians for Responsible Negotiations, it
would not give doctors the right to strike.
</P>
<P>
   Several proposals at the meeting address e-medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates will discuss the growing challenge to the AMA as a
provider of medical information, given the rapid growth in
competing health-news sites on the Internet. Dr. E. Ratcliffe
Anderson, Jr., the AMA's executive vice president, said proceeds
from the AMA's $20 million sale of its former headquarters site in
downtown Chicago will go to e-commerce -- ''areas that serve the
public and doctors better.''
</P>
<P>
   One resolution would put the association on the offensive by
asking it to consider launching a grading system for medical
information on the Net. Others seek to protect the privacy of
electronic health records and e-mail between doctors and patients.
</P>
<P>
   Such issues ''may not currently be the most important thing to
doctors, but they will be in the next five years'' as the transfer
of medical records from paper to electronics becomes complete,
Gostin said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It really will affect how doctors gain access to medical
information'' and, he said, will affect ''their relationship to
patients in terms of confidentiality.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-10-00 1914 </TRAILER>
