<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rutgers raising housing, dining, student fees  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) - The Rutgers University Board of
Governors has voted to increase the cost of annual room, board and
fees, and created a new charge for campus residents who will have
access to a campus-wide communications network.
</P>
<P>
   Following the Friday vote, housing costs will increase 4
percent, bringing the cost of a double-occupancy dormitory room up
$134 to $3,482.
</P>
<P>
   Dining services will go up 3 percent, increasing the cost of the
most popular meal plan for first-year students $70 to $2,550.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in student fees will vary from campus to campus,
ranging from 1.9 percent to 3.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said fees for students at the Camden campus would
increase between 4.3 percent and 6.9 percent to pay for new
athletic programs.
</P>
<P>
   A new fee will be added for dormitory and apartment residents,
who will have access to services through RUNet, a communications
network that eventually will connect all academic and residential
buildings with audio, video and data links.
</P>
<P>
   The network has been installed in 12 academic buildings and 27
residence halls, according to university President Francis L.
Lawrence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
