<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assad's Death Saddens Israel, U.S.  </HEADLINE>
By AUDREY WOODS
<TEXT>
<P>
   The United States and Israel expressed sorrow on the death
Saturday of Syrian President Hafez Assad, who faced them across the
Arab-Jewish divide and across the negotiating table for so many
painful years.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Israeli government understands the sorrow of the Syrian
people over the passing of President Hafez Assad,'' said a
statement from the office of Prime Minister Ehud Barak, whose
moderate government had sought peace with Syria before talks broke
down in January.
</P>
<P>
   ''Israel worked in the past to achieve peace and will continue
to do so in the future,'' the government said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, too, focused on Assad's moves toward the
peaceful settlement of its long fight with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ''He made a strategic choice for peace,'' at the 1991 Madrid
Conference, Clinton said, ''and we worked together to achieve that
goal. ... He made clear Syria's continued commitment to the path of
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We had our differences, but I always respected him,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   The president offered his condolences to the Syrian people and
said, ''We look forward to working with Syria to achieve the goal
of a comprehensive peace.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 1990-91 Persian Gulf crisis, Syria had put aside its
enmity with the United States, Israel's major supporter, to join
the U.S.-led coalition against longtime rival Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   In Lebanon, where Syria has been unquestioned power since its
soldiers moved in during the 1975-90 civil war, Assad's loss was
described by Prime Minister Salim Hoss as a ''tragedy that struck
Lebanon in the heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat declared three days of mourning
in Palestinian areas and sent a telegram to the Damascus government
saying his people ''will stand with their brothers, the Syrian
people, to overcome this difficult moment.''
</P>
<P>
   French President Jacques Chirac said his nation supported
Assad's vision for stability, security and prosperity and would
''spare no effort to help (future) leaders fulfill this strong and
generous ambition.''
</P>
<P>
   Swedish Prime Minister Goeran Persson said Assad's most
important goal in the last year of his life was achieving a peace
agreement with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unfortunately he didn't experience this,'' Persson said. ''I
wish his successor prosperity in his new role and hope that he will
succeed in bringing the peace process to a successful close.''
</P>
<P>
   Assad, credited with bringing political stability to a country
that experienced a series of coups after independence from France
in 1946, dreamed of becoming the unchallenged leader of the Arab
world.
</P>
<P>
   His attempts to rally other Arab leaders to present a unified
front against Israel gained little ground, and Assad has clashed
with Arafat for control of the Palestinian cause.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent peace talks between Israel and Syria broke down
over Assad's insistence on Israel's withdrawal from the strategic
Golan Heights, which it captured during the 1967 Arab-Israeli war,
and Israel's refusal to make that commitment before security
arrangements and normalization were spelled out.
</P>
<P>
   Israel, which withdrew its troops from southern Lebanon on May
24 after an 18-year-occupation, said Saturday it hoped quiet would
be maintained along the border with Syria and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Prime Minister Tony Blair called Assad ''a figure of
stability in the Middle East and much respected in the Arab world
and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ''The best testimony to President Assad's memory would be for
all involved to redouble their efforts to bring a just and lasting
peace to the region and I will do everything I can to support their
efforts,'' Blair said.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem said his country's relations
with Syria had been improving.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am confident that the positive improvement will continue,''
he told television news.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey and Syria have been at odds for years over Turkish
charges that Syria was harboring Kurdish rebels. Relations improved
after Ankara forced Damascus to expel Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah
Ocalan two years ago. But the two countries are still at
loggerheads over sharing the waters of the Euphrates River.
</P>
<P>
   ''We share in the grief of our brothers, the Syrian people,''
Cem said.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Vladimir Putin called Assad ''a friend of our
country.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Assad was one of the most outstanding figures of our time''
who had played ''a historic role in the development of Syria,''
Putin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
