<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Massive fire at vacant factory evacuates neighborhoods  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MOHAWK, N.Y. (AP) - A huge fire at a sprawling old factory
brightened the night sky for miles Friday and forced the evacuation
of a neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   No serious injuries were reported, although a couple of
firefighters were overcome by heat.
</P>
<P>
   The fire broke out about 7 p.m. at the brick building commonly
known as the old Duofold building, in recent years called the
Mohawk Valley Warehouse. Flames poured from windows and a tower
roof and walls collapsed. Inside, fire silhouetted the stairwells
and large beams.
</P>
<P>
   The old factory is in a residential area, and officials ordered
residents to leave. Thirty-five to 40 homes were evacuated, Mohawk
Assistant Fire Chief Rob Phillips told the Utica Observer-Dispatch.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips wouldn't speculate on what might have caused the fire
in the former textile mill, which once employed hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Leo Kinville declared a state of emergency, which allowed
the village to request state aid.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Morse, who lives on East Main and Elizabeth streets, three
houses from the fire, said neighbors were fearful.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our back door was hot. Our cars were hot,'' Morse said from
the other side of East Main Street. ''My kids were in the back; I
told them to get in the house ... I started dragging all the kids
in the house. Then they came and told us to evacuate.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhood residents said they were surprised at how fast -
merely seconds - the whole building went from being cloaked in
billowing smoke to a full-blown fire.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Blais of Warren Street was in his back yard. When he got to
the front, smoke started pouring out of the factory.
</P>
<P>
   ''Then it went,'' Blais said. ''And when it went, it went - with
a boom.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's lucky there's no wind, or this would have been a lot
worse,'' said Mitchell Reale, owner of Warren Street Antiques and
Collectibles, as he watched the fire from his porch.
</P>
<P>
   At least one owner had high hopes for the old building, once the
home of long underwear manufacturer Duofold, which also had sites
in Ilion and Utica. But environmental problems dogged the property.
And any renovations would have incurred a large expense.
</P>
<P>
   It fell into Herkimer County's hands in the late 1990s and had
been sold to Paula Cogen of Fitchburg, Mass. She could not be
reached late Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
