<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.H. Crisis May Warrant Impeachment  </HEADLINE>
By NORMA LOVE
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Alleged improprieties by New Hampshire's
chief justice more than a decade ago appear serious enough to
warrant impeachment, two top lawmakers said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Donna Sytek and Deputy Speaker Donnalee Lozeau
said newly released documents appear to show Chief Justice David
Brock guilty of maladministration -- one of four impeachable
offenses listed in the state constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Sytek and Lozeau said they would make their final judgments
after six days of public questioning, scheduled to begin Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to be able to look him in the eye,'' Lozeau said.
</P>
<P>
   Brock's actions were revealed in depositions made public Friday
by the House Judiciary Committee. The committee began investigating
the state Supreme Court in April, after Attorney General Philip
McLaughlin accused four of its five members of ethics violations.
</P>
<P>
   One of the four, Justice Stephen Thayer, resigned March 31
rather than face criminal prosecution for trying to influence his
own divorce case.
</P>
<P>
   Brock, the chief justice, is accused of calling a lower court
judge in 1987 about a case involving then-Senate Majority Leader
Edward Dupont. Brock allegedly reminded the judge that Dupont could
help win pay raises for the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Brock has denied making the call.
</P>
<P>
   The allegation came to light when Dupont complained that the
lower-court judge, Douglas Gray, made improper comments about his
position on judicial pay raises.
</P>
<P>
   The other Supreme Court justices, including now-U.S. Supreme
Court Justice David Souter, determined that Brock had made the call
and that Gray could reasonably assume Brock was trying to influence
him.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than report Gray immediately to the Judicial Conduct
Committee, the justices held onto the complaint -- missing the
one-year deadline for considering it.
</P>
<P>
   Brock said the matter ''slipped through the cracks.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Brock told the Judiciary Committee that in 1989 ''a
lightbulb went off and I remembered we hadn't followed up on
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Since it was too late for the Conduct Committee to consider the
complaint, the court asked a Superior Court judge to look into it.
</P>
<P>
   Frederick Upton, committee chairman at the time, said the call
was ''the most innocuous thing you can imagine,'' and that the
justices' handling of it was appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   In his deposition, made public Friday, Brock said the justices
did not file Dupont's complaint immediately with the Conduct
Committee because it came from a politician involved in the court's
budget. They did not want to appear to be partial, Brock said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was not a unilateral decision by Justice Brock,'' Brock's
lawyer, David Barry, said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Mock said he had not
heard a good reason for the delay.
</P>
<P>
   ''Collectively, it presents a very troubling picture of the
court,'' Sytek said.
</P>
<P>
   To impeach any of the justices, the House Judiciary Committee
would have to recommend impeachment, the House would have to vote
on the recommendation, and the Senate would then hold a trial.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is expected to make its recommendation this
summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-10-00 2042 </TRAILER>
