<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmer stages library sit-in to protest public library's e-mail policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MALONE, N.Y. (AP) - A farmer staged a one-man sit-in to protest
a public library's e-mail ban on its computers.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Ritchie says the policy violates his First Amendment rights
and prevents struggling businesses from communicating.
</P>
<P>
   The 49-year-old Chateaugay resident was charged Friday afternoon
with trespassing and disorderly conduct at the Wead Library in this
rural village, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The library's Board of Directors decided not to allow e-mail use
''as long as there are chat rooms and with what goes on with
enticing youngsters,'' said David Minnick, library director.
Libraries that allow e-mail use, he said, ''are occasionally in
trouble because of individuals who misuse it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie, who says he is also a high school English teacher, says
the policy may be intended to prevent Internet predators, but he
was engaged in business - communicating with other farmers about
sheep and goat marketing - when Minnick told him to stop using
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ''Without this kind of access, none of us could do this,'' he
said. ''It's expensive for us as farmers to use computer equipment
and the service is so lousy in rural areas in the first place. I've
got drawers full of burned-out modems.''
</P>
<P>
   The library, Ritchie said, is ''standing in the way of poor
people and businessman to look for jobs and use online services.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnick asked Ritchie to leave, both said, but Ritchie refused
as what he called an act of civil disobedience. He told Minnick he
wanted to be arrested.
</P>
<P>
   In 43 years of library work, Minnick said it's the first time
he's asked police to arrest a patron.
</P>
<P>
   Malone is located in Franklin County about 10 miles south of the
Canadian border.
</P>
</TEXT>
