<HEADLINE> Four Die in Baltimore Rowhouse Fire  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- A burning candle in the hallway of a home
without electricity caused a fire that killed three children and
their grandmother in a rowhouse early Saturday, fire officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth child was hospitalized, fire department spokesman Mike
Maybin said.
</P>
<P>
   A Baltimore Gas &AMP; Electric Co. spokeswoman said power had been
cut off to the home since July for failure to pay the utility. The
home did not have smoke detectors, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials identified the victims as Lily Bell Posley, 53;
Marquan Williams, 6; Nigerra McCray, 4; and Shydein Scott, 2.
Dominique Derrico, 10, was listed in critical condition. The
children's mother was not home when the fire broke out.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the fire was extinguished, neighbors wrote messages
on plywood that covered the front door and left stuffed dolls at
the home.
</P>
<P>
   One message read: ''I will always keep yall in my heart no
matter where I go and what I do.''
</P>
