<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Irish tenor Frank Patterson dead at 58  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Frank Patterson, the Irish tenor who sang to
worldwide audiences including presidents and the pope, died
Saturday at a New York hospital. He was 58.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson had been diagnosed with cancer last month and had been
undergoing radiation therapy, said his manager, Vincent Mitchell.
He had been at the Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center since
Tuesday, after his condition took an unexpected turn for the worse.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson, a Westchester County resident, sang on some of the
world's most famous stages, including the Royal Albert Hall in
London and Carnegie Hall in New York. He performed at the White
House twice, along with wife Eily O'Grady, for Ronald Reagan and
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was a great friend of the Irish-American community,'' said
former Boston Mayor Ray Flynn, who said he had been friends with
Patterson for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   '' He's been a great figure, almost a symbol of success of the
Irish in America.''
</P>
<P>
   He also sang twice for Pope John Paul II, in Ireland and in New
York. He was also a favorite of Cardinal John O'Connor, and had
been scheduled to perform at O'Connor's funeral last month. But
that day, he was rushed to the hospital where doctors diagnosed his
illness.
</P>
<P>
   ''He had a good relationship with the archdiocese and with the
cardinal personally,'' said Joe Zwilling, a spokesman for the Roman
Catholic Archdiocese of New York. ''He was always ready to donate
his time and his talent to church activities. ... He was one of the
cardinal's favorite singers.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson took his talent to the silver screen, playing a tenor
in the films ''The Dead'' and ''Michael Collins.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Tipperary County, Ireland, Patterson started his vocal
studies in 1962. Those skills took him to Paris, where a radio
broadcast caught the attention of the Philips Record Company.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson went on to record 36 albums in six languages, covering
opera, inspirational songs, and Irish ballads.
</P>
<P>
   His last performance was June 4, at Regis College in Boston,
Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   Along with his wife, Patterson is survived by his mother and his
son, Eamon.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said a Mass for Patterson will be celebrated at 10 a.m.
Wednesday at St. Patrick's Cathedral. He said Patterson will be
buried in Ireland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
