<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Federal probe ordered into Buffalo-area rail problems  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUFFALO, N.Y.(AP) - Federal officials gave the two companies
controlling Buffalo-area rail transport 90 days to offer a solution
to service problems said to be crippling local industry.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Surface Transportation Board, responding to a request
from Rep. Jack Quinn, R-Hamburg, ordered CSX Corp. and Norfolk
Southern railroads to ''meet with shippers,railroads, and other
interested parties'' to propose solutions, estimate costs and offer
a timetable for improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn said he hoped the order would result in better movement of
goods in and out of the region, ''allowing our economy to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Corporations with plants in western New York say CSX's ongoing
computer problems mean cars going over their rails en route to
Norfolk Southern lines are bumped back and forth and getting lost.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, they criticize Norfolk Southern for lacking adequate
local track space.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Paul Tokasz, D-Cheektowaga, said the state
Legislature is poised to pass $35 million in railroad property tax
relief over five years. In exchange, Tokasz said, the railroads
would be expected to make investments in area infrastructure such
as a new draw bridge over the Buffalo River and an intermodal
rail-truck transfer point.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Sullivan, spokesman for CSX, said the company plans to spend
$65 million through 2003 in New York State, with nearly a quarter
of the money going to the Buffalo area.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Norfolk Southern, Ron Husband, said his company
continues to support construction of a new rail span across the
Buffalo River, but cautioned ''we have not made any firm financial
commitment yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The state has informally committed spending $10 million to
building a replacement for the closed CP Draw bridge.
</P>
<P>
   CSX Corp. and the rail unit of rival Norfolk Southern Corp. have
been troubled by service and safety problems - as well as
plummeting stock prices - resulting from their June 1, 1999 breakup
of Conrail Inc., the Philadelphia-based freight railroad.
</P>
<P>
   In April, CSX President Ronald Conway was removed by John W.
Snow, chairman and chief executive of the company, who took the
helm of the $10.8 billion company's rail unit himself.
</P>
<P>
   Conway seemed to underestimate the challenges of taking over
CSX's 42 percent of Conrail. Last fall, he told analysts CSX had
resolved its Conrail breakup problems and was ready to reap the
benefits of serving the key Northeastern markets it gained. But at
a January forum in Philadelphia, 300 shippers protested that
breakup problems persisted.
</P>
<P>
   Shippers have also expressed outrage over service delays and
disruptions since the 1996 Union Pacific-Southern Pacific merger.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints led the transportation board to approve a moratorium
on new rail mergers in March.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-10-00 2124 </TRAILER>
