<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Devils, Stars Scoreless After First  </HEADLINE>
By IRA PODELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- There were injuries and scoring chances but no
goals again in the first period Saturday night as the New Jersey
Devils tried for the second time to take the Stanley Cup away from
the Dallas Stars.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey holds a 3-2 advantage in the best-of seven Stanley
Cup finals, after losing 1-0 to the defending champion Stars in
triple overtime Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The teams that played scoreless hockey for 106 minutes, 21
seconds in Game 5, picked up where they left off. There has not
been a first-period goal in the series since Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams had opportunities, but no one could beat Dallas' Ed
Belfour or New Jersey's Martin Brodeur. The Devils held a shots
advantage of 11-7.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour has not been scored on in 104:13.
</P>
<P>
   Petr Sykora, a forward on the Devils' top line, was the most
seriously injured of three players that had to leave the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Sykora was leveled by Dallas captain Derian Hatcher, who caught
him high with a forearm that Sykora never saw coming. After a delay
of approximately five minutes, Sykora was wheeled off the ice with
his head and back immobilized.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Sydor, who left with a leg injury, and Joe Nieuwendyk,
who was dumped on his head, were lost to the Stars 28 seconds
apart. Sydor was hurt 3:20 when he fell back and got his leg pinned
after checking Scott Gomez in the defensive left circle.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk was forced to leave when he was dropped by Jason
Arnott.
</P>
<P>
   After the two matched up in a faceoff, Arnott slipped his stick
between Nieuwendyk's legs and flipped him back. Nieuwendyk look
shaky as he headed to the bench, but returned shortly after.
</P>
<P>
   Sydor was being evaluated and was lost for the game. No
penalties were called on any of the plays.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's Patrik Elias was stopped twice on one shift in
front by Belfour. Dallas' best chance came when Brett Hull streaked
in on a partial breakaway about five minutes in.
</P>
<P>
   Hull was slashed on the play by Ken Daneyko, drawing a power
play that was unsuccessful. The Stars failed on both man-advantages
in the first and are 2-for-14 in the series.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils had one power-play chance when Jon Sim went off for
elbowing and recorded no shots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-10-00 2131 </TRAILER>
