<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Meeting Next Target of Protests  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY (AP) -- Anti-trade protesters who targeted the World
Trade Organization and the Organization of American States in
recent months were preparing to disrupt a World Petroleum Congress
meeting that begins here on Sunday, police and activists said.
</P>
<P>
   The congress, comprising 3,000 delegates from 87 countries
representing the oil industry, is the next target of an
anti-globalization movement that combines mainstream activists with
more radical groups, Calgary police Insp. Murray Stooke said.
</P>
<P>
   Officers will have pepper spray and stun guns in case the
demonstrations turn violent, like the street clashes that disrupted
a December WTO meeting in Seattle, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have been training our people for what we call protest
awareness,'' Stooke said. ''We have a number of options available --
from negotiations, to warnings to lift and carry, and so on.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said a security zone has been set up around the meeting
side, similar to the fenced-in area at the OAS assembly in Windsor,
Ontario, last week. More than 40 people were arrested in minor
scuffles with police in Windsor, but the protests were mostly
peaceful and the OAS meeting continued.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters called the security response an overreaction.
</P>
<P>
   Groups planning to demonstrate in Calgary include Greenpeace
International, Friends of the Earth, Oil Watch Network and the
Sierra Club of Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Formed in 1933 by major energy nations, the World Petroleum
Congress meets every three years to discuss industry issues.
</P>
<P>
   John Sellers, director of the Ruckus Society, a group that
offers courses in effective protesting, said the demonstrations
planned for Calgary intended to spread a message, not shut down the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't want to base our success or our failure on tactics,''
he said. ''We want to frame our message of exploitation by oil
companies in a peaceful manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Some shopowners in Calgary have prepared for rioting, cutting
plywood to replace any windows that get broken and bolstering doors
with extra locks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-10-00 2152 </TRAILER>
