<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> LA's Bryant Uncertain For Game 3  </HEADLINE>
By GREG BEACHAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Some say Shaquille O'Neal has been carrying
the Los Angeles Lakers all season. On Saturday, Kobe Bryant's
sprained left ankle prompted him to assume that role quite
literally.
</P>
<P>
   The league MVP gave Bryant a piggyback ride into Conseco
Fieldhouse as Los Angeles began preparations for Game 3 of the NBA
Finals. The 21-year-old star is quite a load, but he's nothing
compared to the burden Shaq will be forced to shoulder if Bryant is
in street clothes Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said no decision has been made on whether he will play,
but his coaches and teammates made it clear they don't expect him
to be in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've played without players who have missed games or been
thrown out of games, and we've won those games,'' Lakers coach Phil
Jackson said. ''Now, playing a 48-minute game possibly without Kobe
Bryant will be tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Shaq led the Lakers to a win in Friday's Game 2 without
Bryant, his likely absence from Sunday's game could change the
nature of a series that appeared headed toward a quick resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, an All-NBA second-teamer and the Lakers' second-leading
scorer, rolled his ankle when he landed on Jalen Rose's foot while
attempting a jumper midway through the first quarter of Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't return, but the Lakers rallied behind O'Neal's 40
points and 24 rebounds to win 111-104 and take a 2-0 lead in the
series.
</P>
<P>
   After X-rays taken at Staples Center were negative, Bryant said
he spent a fitful, sleepless night receiving electrical stimulus on
the ankle. The electrodes were still hooked up when the Lakers flew
to Indianapolis on Saturday morning, and he did stretching
exercises with trainers Gary Vitti and Chip Schaefer while on the
charter flight.
</P>
<P>
   ''How does it feel? It feels sprained,'' said Bryant, who was
wearing a heavy wrap on the ankle and negotiating the Conseco court
on crutches.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're just trying to take care of it as well as possible, and
hopefully get me ready for Game 3, or if not, for Game 4.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers still were confident about their chances without
Kobe, who is averaging 22.3 points and a team-high 4.5 assists per
game in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Game 2's encouraging result, several players
noted that when Bryant missed the season's first 15 games with a
broken hand, the team still flourished in his absence.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've gotten used to playing without Kobe,'' O'Neal said.
''But when Kobe's not in the game, other guys have a chance to
shine -- guys like Glen Rice, who people don't realize is still one
of the best shooters in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Kobe's not there, the other guys are going to step up.''
</P>
<P>
   They did just that on Friday night. Rice and Ron Harper scored
21 points apiece, while Robert Horry accounted for some of Bryant's
strong defensive presence by blocking four shots.
</P>
<P>
   ''In (Sunday's) game we're going to be short one guy, a key guy
to our basketball team,'' Rice said. ''When he goes down, the first
thing we said was everybody has to step up and do more of what they
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Pacers admitted they blew a golden opportunity to
even the series, they praised the Lakers' role players for stepping
into Bryant's shoes. Indiana's supporting cast has had trouble
picking up the slack for shooting guard Reggie Miller, who went
1-for-16 in Game 1 and had just two points in the fourth quarter on
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously they picked up the pace of their game with Kobe
out,'' Indiana coach Larry Bird said. ''They've got weapons. Just
because one guy goes out, they're not going to slow down.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Lakers all but declared Bryant out of Sunday's game,
their hopes are higher for Game 4, when Bryant will have three
additional days of rest.
</P>
<P>
   But none of this concerns Shaq, who is averaging a fearsome 41.5
points and 21.5 rebounds in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't really change things at all,'' O'Neal said.
''Having Kobe is an advantage, but I think we're still good enough
to do certain things when he's not in the ballgame.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-10-00 2229 </TRAILER>
