<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Notes From Saturday's BB Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressINTERLEAGUE:
Pirates-Royals:
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH: Saturday was Salute to the Negro Leagues Night. The
Pirates wore the uniforms of the 1945 Homestead Grays and the
Royals wore those of the 1945 Kansas City Monarchs. The Grays and
the Monarchs met in the 1942 Negro Leagues World Series. ...
Pittsburgh's last eight home runs have been solo shots.
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: The fan who was injured from a gunshot wound during
Friday's game was released from the hospital. Virginia Olsthoorn,
64, of Haysville, Kan., apparently was shot during the ninth inning
from beyond the stadium grounds, Royals spokesman Jim Lachimia
said. ... The Royals gave away Monarchs replica caps to the first
25,000 fans attending the game. ... The Royals, 31-28 going into
Saturday, are guaranteed of reaching the 60-game mark with a
winning record for the first time in five seasons. From 1995
through 1999, the Royals were a combined 134-166 through 60 games.
Mets-Yankees:
</P>
<P>
   METS: GM Steve Phillips danced around questions on whether his
team would be interested in the Cubs' Sammy Sosa, if he's
available. ''I'm going to get in on everything, find out what the
price is,'' he said of the mid-summer trade market. But he refused
to discuss specific players. ... Dennis Cook gave up four runs and
six hits in two-thirds of an inning. ... The Mets had runners on in
13 of the first 14 innings of the series but avoided a 1-2-3 inning
just once in the last four Saturday. ... The first four batters in
the Mets' lineup were 9-for-18 with nine runs scored Friday, just
3-for-18 with no runs Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   YANKEES: 2B Chuck Knoblauch, who has missed five straight games
and is trying to avoid going on the DL for the first time in his
career, took 40-50 swings before the game in a batting cage
underneath the stands. ''I think there's a chance he will play
tomorrow,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said. Knoblauch has been
bothered by a strained left forearm. ... New York has been
successful on 26 of its last 28 stolen-base attempts, including one
by Derek Jeter in the first inning. He swiped second and scored New
York's first run on Bernie Williams' two-out double. ... Since
coming of the DL on May 28, Jeter is 30-for-61 (.492) in 13 games,
including nine multihit games.
Red Sox-Braves:
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: One day late, 2B Jose Offerman was activated from the
disabled list for Saturday's game. He went on the 15-day DL on May
27 with a strained left groin, but the team overlooked that the
move was retroactive to May 25, which would have allowed Offerman
to be activated Friday. He had a 12-game hitting streak when he
went on the DL and quickly extended it to 13, leading off with a
single against the Braves. ... The Red Sox optioned RHP Dan Smith
to Triple-A Pawtucket to clear a spot for Offerman.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: Sign of the times: The Braves had a team ERA of 4.06
prior to Saturday's game -- the highest it's been this late in the
season since 1990, the year before the team began a streak of eight
straight playoff appearances. A decade ago, the Atlanta staff had a
5.30 ERA after 59 games with the team en route to a last-place
finish in the NL West. Despite this year's higher-than-normal
number, the Braves still ranked second in the NL behind Arizona
(3.76).
Phillies-Orioles:
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: RHP Andy Ashby, Sunday's starter, will face
Baltimore for the first time in his 11-year career. ... Saturday's
starter, RHP Curt Schilling, made his major league debut with the
Orioles on Sept. 7, 1988, and pitched for the team from 1988-90.
... Schilling recorded his 1,500th strikeout for the Phillies in
the first inning, fanning Mike Bordick.
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: For the first time in his six seasons in an Orioles
uniform, DH Harold Baines hit eighth Saturday night. It was his
first start since May 31. ... Hall of Fame broadcaster Chuck
Thompson celebrated his 79th birthday. ... With a three-run first
inning Saturday, the Orioles have outscored their opponents 35-27
in the opening inning.
Brewers-Twins:
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: The Brewers announced the signing of first-round pick
Dave Krynzel from the recent draft. Krynzel, an 18-year-old OF from
Nevada, was the 11th overall selection. He batted .438 for Green
Valley High School last season. ... In each of the last three
games, the Brewers and their opponents have had the same amount of
hits.
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: The Twins and Brewers wore replica jerseys from 1969
for Saturday night's Turn Back the Clock game. ... The Twins
announced that they have signed seven draftees from the 2000 free
agent draft, including 18th-round selection Andy Persby. Persby, a
right-hander from Saint Paul, pitched for the University of
Minnesota and also played quarterback for the Gophers. ... Eric
Milton, who was struck on the left leg by Craig Biggio's line drive
on Tuesday, is expected to keep his spot in the rotation and start
Monday.
Cubs-White Sox:
</P>
<P>
   CUBS: Sammy Sosa insists his off-the-field distractions aren't
to blame for his eight strikeouts in the first two games of the
crosstown series. The slugger had a much-publicized blowup with
manager Don Baylor earlier in the week, and that was followed by
trade rumors. ''It just happens. It's part of the game,'' he said.
''I've just got to keep it continue and get ready, because I'm not
going to give up.'' ... Mark Grace fouled a pitch off his right
ankle before he homered in the sixth inning. ''When I did that, I
rolled it,'' he said. ''It basically hurts from my big toe to my
hip.'' ... Despite catching the entire 14-inning game Friday night,
C Joe Girardi was back in the lineup Saturday. ''I knew I was
going,'' said Girardi, who got about six hours of sleep. ''I can
rest Monday. And I will.''
</P>
<P>
   WHITE SOX: Though their next four series are against their
biggest AL rivals, the New York Yankees and the Cleveland Indians,
the White Sox aren't taking these three games with the Cubs
lightly. ''The Cleveland series is big, but there's something about
this one,'' Paul Konerko said. ''Two major league teams in the same
city. It's kind of like a high school game.'' ... Carlos Lee
extended his hitting streak to 11 games, four shy of his career
best. ... Frank Thomas finished 0-for-4 with three strikeouts.
Cardinals-Tigers:
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: Four members of the Cardinals had more than a casual
interest in the College World Series game between Southern
California and Florida State. Mark McGwire played baseball for USC
and J.D. Drew played for the Seminoles. Cardinals manager Tony La
Russa earned a law degree from Florida State after completing his
playing career. Strength and conditioning coach Pete Prinzi played
football for the Seminoles.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: 1B Tony Clark, who has been on the 15-day DL since May
13 with a strained left ribcage, went hitless in four at-bats
during his first rehab outing with Triple-A Toledo. Clark grounded
to first, hit two flyballs to center and grounded to shortstop in
the Mud Hens 10-5 win over Richmond. He didn't face John Rocker.
Reds-Indians:
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: Saturday was the 56th anniversary of Reds radio
broadcaster Joe Nuxhall making his major league debut at age 15,
the youngest player in major league history. Nuxhall, who pitched
with the Reds for 15 years, has been broadcasting games since 1967.
... C Eddie Taubensee, who was not in the lineup Saturday, doesn't
have an RBI in his last 23 games, a span of 82 at-bats. Taubensee,
who has 13 RBIs this season, drove in a career-high 87 last year.
... The Reds five straight losses are a season-high and their most
since an eight-game slide from June 17-24, 1998. ''We hit some
shots and their defense took it away from us,'' Michael Tucker said
following Saturday's 6-5 loss to the Indians. ''That's what happens
to a team going through what we're going through right now.''
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: 2B Roberto Alomar didn't hit a grand slam on
Saturday, but his fiancee won one. While Mary Pierce was winning
the French Open in Paris, Alomar was taking batting practice before
facing the Reds. ''She did?'' Alomar said as he came off the field.
''I'm really happy for her. It's a great win for her after all
she's been through.'' ... Following Saturday's game, RHPs Jaret
Wright and Steve Karsay were to be guests at sports talk show host
Jim Rome's tour stop in Cleveland. Indians OF-1B Richie Sexson sent
an autographed bat for Rome, who was appearing at Blossom Music
Center. ... OF Kenny Lofton, in the option year of his contract,
said he is concerned about the future. It will cost the Indians
$7.5 million if they pick up the 33-year-old's contract, $1.5
million if they buy it out. ''Sure it's on my mind,'' said Lofton,
who returned earlier than expected this year after undergoing
off-season shoulder surgery. ''I want to stay here. If I don't I'm
sure I can find a job elsewhere.''
Expos-Blue Jays:
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: The Expos are 5-3 in interleague play this season. ...
Montreal is 6-3 overall in June. ... Vladimir Guerrero has six home
runs in his last 10 games. ... Tony Armas Jr. has pitched five or
more innings in each of his six starts. ... Armas has allowed just
25 hits in 39 1-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: The Blue Jays dropped below .500 at home (16-17). ...
Kelvim Escobar allowed the first four batters he faced to score.
... Carlos Delgado has 32 RBIs in his last 21 games. ... Tony
Batista homered off a left-hander for the first time this season.
... Attendance was 30,239.
Marlins-Devil Rays:
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: Luis Castillo homered for the first time since
connecting off San Diego's Sterling Hitchcock on Aug. 8, 1998, a
span of 211 games, 783 at-bats. All three of the switch-hitter's
career homers have come from the right side of the plate ... Cliff
Floyd is hitting .333 during the stretch in which he's reached base
by hit, walk or being hit by a pitch in 37 consecutive games ...
RHP Reid Cornelius, who didn't allow a hit until Greg Vaughn's
seventh-inning single, fell two outs short of the most consecutive
hitless innings against the Devil Rays to start a game. Rick Reed
of the New York Mets didn't allow a hit against Tampa Bay for 6 2-3
innings on June 8, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: RHP Juan Guzman, on the disabled list with right
shoulder tendinitis, threw six innings in a rehab start for
Triple-A Durham on Friday night. He allowed four earned runs, nine
hits, no walks and struck out five. He threw 94 pitches. ''The
report on him was very good. He threw the ball well,'' manager
Larry Rothschild said, adding that Guzman probably will make at
least one more minor league start before returning to the rotation
... Devil Rays starting pitchers have worked five innings or more
in 14 consecutive games. The staff accomplished that only 26 times
in the team's first 46 games ... LHP Doug Creek pitched three
innings, matching the longest relief appearance of his career.
Rangers-Rockies:
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: The Rangers designated DH-OF Jason McDonald for
assignment to free a roster spot for OF Dave Martinez, who was
acquired Friday from the Chicago Cubs in a three-team trade. The
Rangers have 10 days to decide whether to trade McDonald, release
him or assign him to a minor league affiliate. ... Rafael Palmeiro
is tied with Orlando Cepeda and Tony Perez for 42nd place on the
all-time home run list with 379.
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: 2B Mike Lansing was held out of the starting lineup
with soreness in his back and tailbone, but was available if
needed. ... LHP Gabe White is within 5 1-3 innings of Curtis
Leskanic's franchise consecutive scoreless innings streak of 21 1-3
for the Rockies.
Angels-Diamondbacks:
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM: Jarrod Washburn is 5-0 in his career in June. ... Darin
Erstad's second-inning double gave him 100 hits in 61 games. He's
the fastest to reach 100 hits since Heinie Manush reached the
century mark in 60 games with the Washington Senators in 34 games.
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA: Luis Gonzalez has homered in three straight games and
five of his last six games. He's the fifth Diamondback to homer in
three straight games. ... Gonzalez's four-hit game was his second
of the season and 12th of his career. It came with his brother,
Rex, in attendance. Rex Gonzalez manages the Feather River Mudcats
of the independent Western League, who are in town to face the
local Valley Vipers. ... Omar Daal has lasted less than four
innings in two of his last five starts. ... Bernard Gilkey flied
out in a pinch-hitting appearance to extend his hitless streak to
21 at-bats. Gilkey is 1-for-40 in his last 19 games. ... Danny
Bautista, acquired from the Florida Marlins on Friday, was 0-for-2
in his Diamondbacks debut.
Mariners-Giants:
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: It didn't take Mariners pitcher Paul Abbott long to get
his first big league hit. The starter in Saturday's interleague
game at the NL's San Francisco Giants, Abbott doubled off Shawn
Estes in his first career at bat. He eventually scored on a
groundout. ... Seattle's pinch-hitters are slumping. After an
0-for-4 performance Friday night, the team's pinch-hitters are
batting a collective .118 (4-for-34) with just one RBI. They are
0-for-10 with two walks in their last 12 appearances.
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO: OF Terrell Lowery, designated for assignment
earlier this week, cleared waivers and on Saturday accepted an
outright assignment to Triple-A Fresno. San Francisco manager Dusty
Baker was pleasantly surprised Lowery had gone unclaimed. Lowery
was batting .556 in limited duty but was bumped from the 25-man
roster because of a numbers squeeze after pitcher Joe Nathan's
reinstatement from the DL. ''We're glad to have him back in our
system,'' Baker said. ''He not only has experience up here. He has
done well.''
Athletics-Dodgers:
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: Reliever Mike Magnante, scheduled to come off the DL
Monday from a strained left hamstring, had a rehab start on
Saturday with Triple-A Sacramento. Barring any complications, the
left-hander is expected to be activated on Monday for the start of
a series at Minnesota. ... This year's All-Star game will mark 30
years since Athletics broadcaster and former Cleveland catcher Ray
Fosse took the brunt of a violent collision at home plate with Pete
Rose, who scored the winning run for the NL. Fosse sustained a
fractured and separated left shoulder. But X-rays didn't reveal the
injuries because of inflammation already in that shoulder -- and he
did not miss a game. The physical pain is still there, said Fosse,
who declined to say whether or not Rose belongs in the Hall of
Fame. ''I don't have a vote and I've never been one to really say
yes or no, because the only thing that's going to happen if I say
it is that it's going to create a mess,'' Fosse said. ''So I've
never touched that (subject), and I really don't plan to.''
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: The strained right hamstring CF Todd Hollandsworth
sustained while running down Tim Salmon's fly ball in the gap on
June 3 against Anaheim isn't improving as quickly as the Dodgers
had anticipated. ''He definitely needs more time,'' manager Davey
Johnson said Friday. ''He's already been out a week; and if it
looks like it's going to be another four or five days before he's
even at 80 percent, then possibly we might retroactive him to the
DL.'' ... The Dodgers will probably decide by the middle of the
week what to do next with former Cy Young winner Orel Hershiser,
who already has made three starts for Class-A San Bernardino in an
attempt to regain his form. ''He suggested we move him up to
Double-A,'' Johnson joked. ... Even though Jeff Shaw is pitching
again and ready for his first save opportunity since getting a few
days off to rest his tender right shoulder, Mike Fetters will be
sharing the closing duties with Shaw until further notice. ''I've
got two guys who can both close, so I'm not going to go to the whip
(with Shaw),'' Johnson said.
Astros-Padres:
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: Jose Lima, scheduled to start Sunday's series finale
against San Diego, is 1-3 with a 7.40 ERA in his four career starts
against the Padres. He's 1-2 with a 9.22 ERA in three appearances
(two starts) at San Diego. ... With his two-run shot in the ninth
inning Friday, Jeff Bagwell joined an impressive group of players
who've hit game-winning homers off Padres closer Trevor Hoffman the
last two seasons. Besides Bagwell, the list includes Mike Piazza
(twice), Matt Williams and Sammy Sosa. ... Billy Wagner has allowed
16 earned runs this year compared to 13 all of last year. He blew
his seventh save Friday night. Last year he blew only three.
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO: After being the Padres' DH on a six-game trip to
Seattle and Oakland, Tony Gwynn is back to his schedule of one game
on, one game off to rest his degenerative left knee. Gwynn was out
of the lineup Saturday night after going 2-for-5 on Friday night to
push his average up to a season-high .306. ... Of Gwynn's 3,100
career hits, 317 have come off the Astros, his most against any
team.
</P>
</TEXT>
