<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Set Debuts At Grand Ole Opry  </HEADLINE>
By JIM PATTERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The homey red barn backdrop that has set
the tone for the Grand Ole Opry for years has been updated with
some fancy stage lighting and a more modern, high-tech touch.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Clark, Steve Wariner and Little Jimmy Dickens joined dozens
of Opry cast members in christening the new set before an audience
of 4,000 Saturday with a rendition of ''Will The Circle Be
Unbroken.''
</P>
<P>
   The new set advertises its web site -- ''www.Opry.com'' -- along
with ''650 WSM,'' the AM radio station which has aired the program
for 75 years.
</P>
<P>
   The wooden facade of the old barn is replaced with projection
screens that can turn the barn red or many other colors. There are
also three large video screens at center stage and four large
columns.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Ole Opry -- the longest continuously running radio show
in the country -- began in the downtown studios of WSM Radio in
1925, and moved to the Grand Ole Opry House in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   The old barn set, which had remained unchanged since 1978, will
be displayed in the new Country Music Hall of Fame, set to open in
Nashville next May.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest stars in country music have played the Opry show
over the years, including Roy Acuff, Hank Williams, Patsy Cline,
and Minnie Pearl. Current cast members include Garth Brooks, Trisha
Yearwood and Vince Gill.
</P>
<P>
   Terry London, president of Gaylord Entertainment, which owns the
Opry, called the Opry an American treasure.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our goal in life is to see that the property lasts another 75
years, paying attention to the tradition, but also allowing for all
of the opportunities and technology,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
