<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Region Sorrowful Over Assad's Death  </HEADLINE>
By TAREK EL-TABLAWY
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Syria's neighbors mourned the death of
President Hafez Assad, saying that it robbed the region of a
visionary who stood unwavering in the face of challenges to the
Arab nations.
</P>
<P>
   Around the Arab world, including the United Arab Emirates,
Qatar, Egypt, Libya, Kuwait, the Palestinian Authority, Morocco and
Bahrain, a three-day mourning period was declared.
</P>
<P>
   In Lebanon, where Syria has 30,000 troops stationed and has
served as the main power-broker for more than two decades, a
one-week mourning period was declared during which flags would be
flown at half-staff.
</P>
<P>
   Assad's death is a ''tragedy that struck Lebanon in the heart,''
said Prime Minister Salim Hoss. President Emil Lahoud, in a letter
to Assad's son and heir-apparent, Bashar, wrote that he was the
last to speak to the Syrian leader.
</P>
<P>
   ''The last phrase he told me was that our fate is to build for
our children an assuring future and it is our duty to make sure
they inherit better than what we inherited,'' Lahoud said. ''Then
there was a sudden silence and the line broke off.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Arab officials reflected on the life of a man who, in
three decades of autocratic leadership, came to be dubbed the
''Lion of Damascus.''
</P>
<P>
   ''In the peace process we will continue to stand behind our
brothers in Syria until they reach all their rights and get back
all their occupied territories,'' Jordanian Prime Minister
Abdur-Ra'uf S. Rawabdeh said after an emergency Cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Assad had been engaged in negotiations, suspended since January,
with Israel to secure the return of the Golan Heights, taken by
Israel in the 1967 Mideast war.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Palace in Amman, the Jordanian capital, declared a
40-day mourning period and the government announced a three-day
mourning period during which schools and government offices would
be closed.
</P>
<P>
   A statement from the office of Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak,
a close friend of Assad, called him ''the most noble partner in
peace,'' according to Egypt's Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Esmat Abdel-Meguid, secretary-general of the 21-nation Arab
League based in Cairo, said he did not expect Assad's death to
change Syria's position vis-a-vis the peace process with Israel,
but warned the ''other side will capitalize on the catastrophe to
propose new matters or to try to benefit'' from the death.
</P>
<P>
   Non-Arab Iran extended its condolences, with Iranian radio late
Saturday airing messages from Supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei
and President Mohammad Khatami, both of whom addressed their
statements to Assad's son, Bashar.
</P>
<P>
   Khamenei said Assad was ''a great leader, and he had an
undeniable, important role in the recent victories in Lebanon.''
</P>
<P>
   Syria and Iran were the chief backers of the Hezbollah
guerrillas who led the effort to oust Israel from southern Lebanon.
Israeli forces withdrew last month after 18 years of occupation.
</P>
<P>
   Syria's neighbor, Iraq, interrupted programing to briefly
announce Assad's death but issued no official reaction.
</P>
<P>
   The Muslim Brotherhood, Syria's biggest opposition group, said
in a statement hours after Assad's death that what Syria needs is
''a peaceful change of power and a free and popular choosing of the
ruler in a way that preserves for the citizens their security and
dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali Sadreddine al-Beyanouni, the Brotherhood leader based in
Amman, Jordan, said ''no matter how long the life of a person is,
this will be his fate in the end. Let those alive learn and the
those who are strong stop being arrogant.''
</P>
<P>
   Assad's army crushed a 1982 uprising by the Muslim Brotherhood,
a Sunni Muslim fundamentalist movement, in the city of Hama. Syrian
troops killed thousands of people and flattened much of the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-10-00 2239 </TRAILER>
