<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, June 10, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Syrian President Hafez Assad Dies
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) -- Syrian President Hafez Assad died Saturday before he
was able to win back the treasured Golan Heights he lost to Israel 33 years ago.
Assad, 69, had been suffering from heart problems, lymphoma and kidney failure,
according to a Lebanese heart surgeon close to the Assad family. The surgeon,
who insisted on anonymity, said Assad died of heart failure. The death of the
skillful and ruthless leader could deal a blow to Mideast peace prospects by
ushering in a prolonged period of instability, but it could also mean an
opportunity for Syria to forsake at least part of its implacable enmity toward
Israel.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Landmark Korean Summit Postponed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The first-ever meeting between South Korean
President Kim Dae-jung and North Korean leader Kim Jong Il, scheduled to begin
Monday, was delayed a day for ''unavoidable technical reasons,'' Kim's office
said in a news release. No further details were released. The three-day summit
caps six months of vigorous diplomacy with China, Italy, Australia, the United
States and other countries. The presence of 37,000 American troops in South
Korea and Pyongyang's nuclear and missile programs are among the most
contentious topics.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Urges Higher Education for All
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NORTHFIELD, Minn. (AP) -- President Clinton today told graduates of a private
liberal arts college where annual costs exceed $29,000 that the United States
can't afford to deny college to students just because they don't have the money
for it. ''Over the past 20 years, the cost of college has quadrupled,'' Clinton
told 423 graduates of Carleton College, about 40 miles south of Minneapolis.
''I'll bet there are a lot of parents here who have taken second mortgages or
second jobs to help pay those tuition bills.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Hopes for Political Revival
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- After a week in which he launched a multimillion-dollar TV
ad campaign, released the first in a series of economic initiatives and
announced a lengthy ''progress and prosperity tour,'' Vice President Al Gore
says he has reached a turning point in his campaign against George W. Bush.
National polls show the race is tight, after Bush held slight leads in recent
weeks. The Texas governor remains ahead in the more important state-by-state
battle, however, with leads in enough states to give him more than two-thirds of
the 270 electoral votes required to win the White House.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Strong Quake Rocks Taiwan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- A strong earthquake shook central Taiwan on Sunday,
causing rock slides and injuring more than a dozen people, officials and
seismologists said. No deaths were reported. The quake, with a preliminary
magnitude of 6.7, was centered about 30 miles north of Mount Yu, Taiwan's
highest mountain, about 180 miles south of the capital, Taipei, the Central
Weather Bureau said. The quake was followed by seven aftershocks with magnitudes
of 4 and 5. All the quakes were considered aftershocks of a 7.6-magnitude
earthquake that devastated the region September, killing 2,400 people.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fatal Baltimore Fire Blamed on Candle
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- A burning candle in the hallway of a home without
electricity caused a fire that killed three children and their grandmother in a
rowhouse early today, fire officials said. A fourth child was hospitalized, fire
department spokesman Mike Maybin said. A Baltimore Gas &AMP; Electric Co.
spokeswoman said power had been cut off to the home since July for failure to
pay the utility. The home did not have smoke detectors, officials said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Beach Reopens After Shark Attack
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GULF SHORES, Ala. (AP) -- One of the Gulf Coast's most popular beaches
reopened to swimmers today, a day after Alabama's first confirmed shark attack
in 25 years. The attack prompted officials to close a 30-mile stretch of land at
the height of tourist season. Chuck Anderson, 44, a high school coach and vice
principal, lost his right arm above the elbow. And Richard Watley, a 55-year-old
Gulf Shores barber, was bitten on his right hip and right arm. They were among a
group training for a triathlon when the shark attacked. It wasn't immediately
known what kind of shark attacked the men.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Braves Blank Red Sox 6-0
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Terry Mulholland pitched five shutout innings despite a
pulled hamstring, and the Atlanta Braves made it two in a row over the Boston
Red Sox with a 6-0 victory tonight. The Braves broke open the game with four
runs in the fourth, including Andres Galarraga's 17th homer and a two-run triple
by Walt Weiss. Weiss started instead of rookie Rafael Furcal, who was arrested
early Saturday on charges on drunken driving and underage alcohol consumption.
AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON 
</P>
