<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rockies 12, Rangers 6  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Larry Walker hit a three-run homer for his first
home run since coming off the disabled list as the Colorado Rockies
won their seventh straight home game, beating the Texas Rangers
12-6 on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Shumpert went 3-for-4 with a home run and three RBIs.
Colorado reliever Gabe White hit his first career home run in his
25th career at-bat as the Rockies (33-25) moved eight games over
.500 for the first time since May 12, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Rodriguez homered twice and drove in four runs for Texas.
Dave Martinez went 2-for-3 with a home run and scored two runs in
his first game with the Rangers, who lost for the fourth straight
time.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, who came off the DL on Friday after a stress fracture in
his right elbow sidelined him for 30 days, homered with two on in
his first at bat, also had a double and was walked three times.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Helton lowered his batting average to .400 with a 1-for-5
night. Scott Karl (2-2), who had been demoted to the bullpen,
worked 2 2-3 scoreless innings for his first win since May 27.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers led 2-0 in the first inning on Rodriguez's 20th
homer.
</P>
<P>
   Esteban Loaiza (3-4) immediately got in trouble walking Tom
Goodwin and Shumpert before Walker's first homer since May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Texas took a 5-3 lead in the third inning when Martinez and
Rodriguez homered to right. Rodriguez's second homer of the game
came with Palmeiro aboard. It was Rodriguez's fourth multihomer
game of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies scored five runs in their half of the third to knock
out Loaiza. Hammonds had an RBI single, Goodwin had a sacrifice
fly, Shumpert had a two-run triple and scored on Matt Perisho's
wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Royce Clayton tripled and scored on Palmeiro's two-out single to
center off Jarvis getting the Rangers within 8-6. Karl relieved
Jarvis and got Rodriguez to ground out to end the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Doubles by Walker and Jeff Cirillo to open the sixth inning
increased Colorado's lead to 9-6. White and Shumpert hit solo home
runs in the seventh inning off Perisho.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Texas designated OF Jason McDonald for assignment on
Saturday to free a roster spot for OF Dave Martinez, who was
acquired Friday from the Cubs in a three-team trade. ... Walker
emphatically gave high-fives to teammates after hitting his first
inning home run. ... Loazia's 2 2-3 inning outing matched his
shortest outing of the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-10-00 2323 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000610.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Devils, Stars Tied 1-1 In OT  </HEADLINE>
By IRA PODELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- For the second straight game, New Jersey and
Dallas went into overtime with the Devils trying to win the Stanley
Cup and the Stars fighting to hold on to it.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Niedermayer gave New Jersey a brief lead in the second
period before Mike Keane answered for Dallas, and the teams went
into the extra session tied 1-1 Saturday night in Game 6 of the
Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey leads the best-of-seven series 3-2 and is making its
second attempt to take the Stanley Cup away from the defending
champion Stars. Game 6 was made necessary when Dallas beat the
Devils 1-0 in triple overtime Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Before Game 5, the Devils -- trying for their second championship
-- played a team-record tying 22 straight games without needing
overtime. That was one short of the NHL record.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas also beat Colorado in overtime in Game 5 of the Western
Conference finals, the Stars' only other overtime playoff game this
season.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half of the third period, the pace picked up as
the teams fought to end it in regulation. But as has been the case
in the last two games, New Jersey goalie Martin Brodeur and Dallas'
Ed Belfour refused to give in.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur denied Scott Thornton and Brett Hull in close and
Belfour turned aside a good chance for Patrik Elias.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour made 30 saves -- 78 in two games -- to 28 for Brodeur in
regulation. The Devils goalie stopped all but two of 70 shots in
that span.
</P>
<P>
   Niedermayer scored the Devils' second short-handed goal of the
series 5:18 into the second, with Brian Rafalski off for holding.
Niedermayer's fifth of the playoffs snapped Belfour's scoreless
streak at 145:31, dating to early in the final period of Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, 2-for-15 in the series with the man-advantage, have
allowed as many goals on their power plays as they've scored.
</P>
<P>
   Keane made it 1-1 just 1:09 later when he took a beautiful pass
in the right circle from Scott Thornton and wristed a shot over
Brodeur's glove. The teams have been tied for 165:12 of the last
166:21, covering over seven periods.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey almost retook the lead twice, but were denied by
Belfour and the goalposts.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie John Madden, who has the Devils' other short-handed goal
in the series, sent a shot off the post just past the midway point.
With just under five minutes remaining, Patrik Elias had his shot
from the slot hit Belfour and then the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas had a 3-on-1 late in the period, but Brodeur was able to
knock the puck into the stands with Brenden Morrow in front.
</P>
<P>
   The physical play picked up and the two captains traded punches
with 6:12 left in the period. Dallas' Derian Hatcher and New
Jersey's Scott Stevens were sent off for roughing.
</P>
<P>
   Emotions were high after a first period that saw three injuries
and no goals.
</P>
<P>
   The teams that played scoreless hockey for 106 minutes, 21
seconds in Game 5, picked up where they left off. There has not
been a first-period goal in the series since Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   Petr Sykora, a forward on the Devils' top line, was the most
seriously injured when he was leveled by Hatcher. The Dallas
captain caught him high with a forearm that Sykora never saw
coming. After a delay of about five minutes, Sykora was wheeled off
the ice with his head and back immobilized.
</P>
<P>
   He was given a CT scan that was normal and held overnight in the
hospital for observation.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Sydor, who left with a leg injury, and Joe Nieuwendyk,
who was dumped on his head, were lost to the Stars 28 seconds
apart. Sydor was hurt at 3:20 when he fell back and got his leg
pinned after checking Scott Gomez in the defensive left circle.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk was forced to leave when he was dropped by Jason
Arnott.
</P>
<P>
   After the two matched up in a faceoff, Arnott slipped his stick
between Nieuwendyk's legs and flipped him back. Nieuwendyk looked
shaky as he headed to the bench, but returned shortly after.
</P>
<P>
   Sydor was being evaluated and was ruled out for the game. No
penalties were called on any of the plays.
</P>
<P>
   Elias was stopped twice on one shift in front by Belfour.
Dallas' best chance came when Hull streaked in on a partial
breakaway about five minutes in.
</P>
<P>
   Hull was slashed on the play by Ken Daneyko, drawing a power
play that was unsuccessful. The Stars failed on both man-advantages
in the first.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils had one power-play chance when Jon Sim went off for
elbowing and recorded no shots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-10-00 2329 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000610.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York farmers say federal aid measures leave them out  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) - Lots of apples, little worth.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, New York's apple growers say, the federal
government doesn't get it.
</P>
<P>
   The growers are hoping their state and national representatives
will be able to push through emergency legislation to help
Northeast apple farmers.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Charles Schumer backs the legislation, part of the
federal 2001 Agricultural Appropriations bill, as do Reps. James
Walsh, R- Onondaga, and Maurice Hinchey, D-Saugerties.
</P>
<P>
   After hail from the 1998 Labor Day storm wiped out $500,000
worth of Albion apple grower Bruce Krenning's crops, this past
fall's batch of New York apples had great volume, but too small a
size for marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't keep doing this,'' Krenning said Friday at a meeting
of farmers, agriculture officials and politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two years, Krenning said, his loss reached
$700,000.
</P>
<P>
   Existing agricultural disaster relief has been geared toward
Southern and Midwestern crops that either grow or don't, said state
Department of Agriculture Deputy Commissioner Rick Zimmerman.
</P>
<P>
   The government says, ''You still have an apple, so what's the
problem?'' Zimmerman said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is stalled in the House of Representatives. It includes
trade provisions with Cuba, which have been strongly opposed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-10-00 2347 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000610.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, June 10, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Assad's Son Clears Leadership Hurdle
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) -- Following the death of President Hafez Assad
Saturday, Syria's parliament overwhelmingly voted to amend an article in the
constitution that requires the head of state to be at least 40 years old,
clearing the way for Assad's son, Bashar, to assume the presidency. The
legislators voted to lower the age to 34. Bashar is 34. Then parliament
adjourned until June 25. Assad had been grooming Bashar for future leadership,
but the British-educated ophthalmologist has held no major political office. But
he was expected to be brought into the ruling Baath Party leadership at a
congress scheduled for later this month.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Solomon Islands Provincial Capital Seized
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HONIARA, Solomon Islands (AP) -- Militants seized a provincial capital in the
western Solomon Islands early Sunday, bringing a third warring faction into the
volatile crisis gripping this tiny South Pacific nation, radio reported. One
young person was killed in the attack in the city of Gizo, according to a
broadcast by New Zealand's National Radio. The Australian Broadcasting Corp.
quoted provincial Solomon Islands police as saying 45 armed men, some apparently
from neighboring Papua New Guinea, raided the Gizo police station and
telecommunications facilities.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Albright To Attend Assad Funeral
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NORTHFIELD, Minn. (AP) -- The White House announced Saturday that Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright would represent the United States at Syrian
President Hafez Assad's funeral. Spokesman Joe Lockhart confirmed that neither
President Clinton nor Vice President Al Gore would attend the service. ''I think
the president believes that Secretary Albright is the appropriate person to
attend,'' he said. He declined to say whether Clinton had been advised not to
make the trip.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Korean Summit Delayed One Day
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The first-ever meeting between South Korean
President Kim Dae-jung and North Korean leader Kim Jong Il, scheduled to begin
Monday, was delayed a day for ''unavoidable technical reasons,'' Kim's office
said in a news release. No further details were released. The three-day summit
caps six months of vigorous diplomacy with China, Italy, Australia, the United
States and other countries. The presence of 37,000 American troops in South
Korea and Pyongyang's nuclear and missile programs are among the most
contentious topics.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mrs. Clinton Can't Open Gap in NY
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Despite the departure of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani from the
closely watched U.S. Senate race in New York, Hillary Rodham Clinton has been
unable to open up a gap over the Republican opposition, according to three
independent polls. When Giuliani pulled out of the race on May 19, Republican
leaders predicted that by late summer or early fall their new candidate, Rep.
Rick Lazio, would be running even with the first lady. But on June 7, the
Quinnipiac University Polling Institute came out with its offering. It showed
Clinton and Lazio tied, at 44 percent each.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Northwest Offers Discount for Late Luggage
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   EAGAN, Minn. (AP) -- Northwest Airlines will begin offering discounts on
future flights to passengers whose luggage doesn't arrive on time. Terry
Tripler, who follows the industry for 1travel.com, said the program is the only
one of its kind among the major airlines. The discount begins Thursday and will
be based on a sliding scale, starting at $25 and depending on the price of the
passenger's ticket, Northwest spokeswoman Mary Beth Schubert said Saturday. In
addition to the discount, a letter of apology from Northwest will be attached to
the handle of delayed luggage, she said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Homeless Man Bluffs Way Into Hospital
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- A homeless man carrying fake credentials bluffed his way
into a hospital emergency room and worked the night shift as a physician's
assistant before revealing he is HIV-positive, police said. The man, who
identified himself as Gary Lee Stearley, 26, was closely supervised throughout
the shift at Mercy Hospital and no patients were hurt, police said. He was
charged with trespassing and false impersonation and was being held Saturday in
lieu of $25,000 bail.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rockies Defeat Rangers 12-6
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Larry Walker hit a three-run homer for his first home run
since coming off the disabled list as the Colorado Rockies won their seventh
straight home game, beating the Texas Rangers 12-6 on Saturday night. Terry
Shumpert went 3-for-4 with a home run and three RBIs. Colorado reliever Gabe
White hit his first career home run in his 25th career at-bat as the Rockies
(33-25) moved eight games over .500 for the first time since May 12, 1997.
AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON 
</P>
